ArithmeticError.descr: The base class for those built-in exceptions that are raised for various arithmetic errors: OverflowError, ZeroDivisionError, FloatingPointError.
ArithmeticError.name: ArithmeticError

AttributeError.descr: Raised when an attribute reference (see Attribute references) or assignment fails. (When an object does not support attribute references or attribute assignments at all, TypeError is raised.)
AttributeError.name: AttributeError

BaseException.descr: The base class for all built-in exceptions. It is not meant to be directly inherited by user-defined classes (for that, use Exception). If str() is called on an instance of this class, the representation of the argument(s) to the instance are returned, or the empty string when there were no arguments.
BaseException.name: BaseException

BaseException.args.descr: The tuple of arguments given to the exception constructor. Some built-in exceptions (like IOError) expect a certain number of arguments and assign a special meaning to the elements of this tuple, while others are usually called only with a single string giving an error message.
BaseException.args.name: BaseException.args

BaseException.with_traceback.descr: This method sets tb as the new traceback for the exception and returns the exception object. It is usually used in exception handling code like this:
BaseException.with_traceback.name: BaseException.with_traceback

BlockingIOError.descr: Raised when an operation would block on an object (e.g. socket) set for non-blocking operation. Corresponds to errno EAGAIN, EALREADY, EWOULDBLOCK and EINPROGRESS.
BlockingIOError.name: BlockingIOError

BlockingIOError.characters_written.descr: An integer containing the number of characters written to the stream before it blocked. This attribute is available when using the buffered I/O classes from the io module.
BlockingIOError.characters_written.name: BlockingIOError.characters_written

BrokenPipeError.descr: A subclass of ConnectionError, raised when trying to write on a pipe while the other end has been closed, or trying to write on a socket which has been shutdown for writing. Corresponds to errno EPIPE and ESHUTDOWN.
BrokenPipeError.name: BrokenPipeError

BufferError.descr: Raised when a buffer related operation cannot be performed.
BufferError.name: BufferError

BytesWarning.descr: Base class for warnings related to bytes and bytearray.
BytesWarning.name: BytesWarning

ChildProcessError.descr: Raised when an operation on a child process failed. Corresponds to errno ECHILD.
ChildProcessError.name: ChildProcessError

ConnectionAbortedError.descr: A subclass of ConnectionError, raised when a connection attempt is aborted by the peer. Corresponds to errno ECONNABORTED.
ConnectionAbortedError.name: ConnectionAbortedError

ConnectionError.descr: A base class for connection-related issues.
ConnectionError.name: ConnectionError

ConnectionRefusedError.descr: A subclass of ConnectionError, raised when a connection attempt is refused by the peer. Corresponds to errno ECONNREFUSED.
ConnectionRefusedError.name: ConnectionRefusedError

ConnectionResetError.descr: A subclass of ConnectionError, raised when a connection is reset by the peer. Corresponds to errno ECONNRESET.
ConnectionResetError.name: ConnectionResetError

DeprecationWarning.descr: Base class for warnings about deprecated features.
DeprecationWarning.name: DeprecationWarning

EOFError.descr: Raised when the input() function hits an end-of-file condition (EOF) without reading any data. (N.B.: the io.IOBase.read() and io.IOBase.readline() methods return an empty string when they hit EOF.)
EOFError.name: EOFError

Ellipsis.descr: The same as .... Special value used mostly in conjunction with extended slicing syntax for user-defined container data types.
Ellipsis.name: Ellipsis

Exception.descr: All built-in, non-system-exiting exceptions are derived from this class. All user-defined exceptions should also be derived from this class.
Exception.name: Exception

False.descr: The false value of the bool type. Assignments to False are illegal and raise a SyntaxError.
False.name: False

FileExistsError.descr: Raised when trying to create a file or directory which already exists. Corresponds to errno EEXIST.
FileExistsError.name: FileExistsError

FileNotFoundError.descr: Raised when a file or directory is requested but doesn’t exist. Corresponds to errno ENOENT.
FileNotFoundError.name: FileNotFoundError

FloatingPointError.descr: Raised when a floating point operation fails. This exception is always defined, but can only be raised when Python is configured with the --with-fpectl option, or the WANT_SIGFPE_HANDLER symbol is defined in the pyconfig.h file.
FloatingPointError.name: FloatingPointError

FutureWarning.descr: Base class for warnings about constructs that will change semantically in the future.
FutureWarning.name: FutureWarning

GeneratorExit.descr: Raise when a generator‘s close() method is called. It directly inherits from BaseException instead of Exception since it is technically not an error.
GeneratorExit.name: GeneratorExit

ImportError.descr: Raised when an import statement fails to find the module definition or when a from ... import fails to find a name that is to be imported.
ImportError.name: ImportError

ImportWarning.descr: Base class for warnings about probable mistakes in module imports.
ImportWarning.name: ImportWarning

IndentationError.descr: Base class for syntax errors related to incorrect indentation. This is a subclass of SyntaxError.
IndentationError.name: IndentationError

IndexError.descr: Raised when a sequence subscript is out of range. (Slice indices are silently truncated to fall in the allowed range; if an index is not an integer, TypeError is raised.)
IndexError.name: IndexError

InterruptedError.descr: Raised when a system call is interrupted by an incoming signal. Corresponds to errno EINTR.
InterruptedError.name: InterruptedError

IsADirectoryError.descr: Raised when a file operation (such as os.remove()) is requested on a directory. Corresponds to errno EISDIR.
IsADirectoryError.name: IsADirectoryError

KeyError.descr: Raised when a mapping (dictionary) key is not found in the set of existing keys.
KeyError.name: KeyError

KeyboardInterrupt.descr: Raised when the user hits the interrupt key (normally Control-C or Delete). During execution, a check for interrupts is made regularly. The exception inherits from BaseException so as to not be accidentally caught by code that catches Exception and thus prevent the interpreter from exiting.
KeyboardInterrupt.name: KeyboardInterrupt

LookupError.descr: The base class for the exceptions that are raised when a key or index used on a mapping or sequence is invalid: IndexError, KeyError. This can be raised directly by codecs.lookup().
LookupError.name: LookupError

MemoryError.descr: Raised when an operation runs out of memory but the situation may still be rescued (by deleting some objects). The associated value is a string indicating what kind of (internal) operation ran out of memory. Note that because of the underlying memory management architecture (C’s malloc() function), the interpreter may not always be able to completely recover from this situation; it nevertheless raises an exception so that a stack traceback can be printed, in case a run-away program was the cause.
MemoryError.name: MemoryError

NameError.descr: Raised when a local or global name is not found. This applies only to unqualified names. The associated value is an error message that includes the name that could not be found.
NameError.name: NameError

None.descr: The sole value of the type NoneType. None is frequently used to represent the absence of a value, as when default arguments are not passed to a function. Assignments to None are illegal and raise a SyntaxError.
None.name: None

NotADirectoryError.descr: Raised when a directory operation (such as os.listdir()) is requested on something which is not a directory. Corresponds to errno ENOTDIR.
NotADirectoryError.name: NotADirectoryError

NotImplemented.descr: Special value which can be returned by the “rich comparison” special methods (__eq__(), __lt__(), and friends), to indicate that the comparison is not implemented with respect to the other type.
NotImplemented.name: NotImplemented

NotImplementedError.descr: This exception is derived from RuntimeError. In user defined base classes, abstract methods should raise this exception when they require derived classes to override the method.
NotImplementedError.name: NotImplementedError

OSError.descr: Under Windows, the winerror attribute gives you the native Windows error code. The errno attribute is then an approximate translation, in POSIX terms, of that native error code.
OSError.name: OSError

OverflowError.descr: Raised when the result of an arithmetic operation is too large to be represented. This cannot occur for integers (which would rather raise MemoryError than give up). Because of the lack of standardization of floating point exception handling in C, most floating point operations also aren’t checked.
OverflowError.name: OverflowError

PendingDeprecationWarning.descr: Base class for warnings about features which will be deprecated in the future.
PendingDeprecationWarning.name: PendingDeprecationWarning

PermissionError.descr: Raised when trying to run an operation without the adequate access rights - for example filesystem permissions. Corresponds to errno EACCES and EPERM.
PermissionError.name: PermissionError

ProcessLookupError.descr: Raised when a given process doesn’t exist. Corresponds to errno ESRCH.
ProcessLookupError.name: ProcessLookupError

ReferenceError.descr: This exception is raised when a weak reference proxy, created by the weakref.proxy() function, is used to access an attribute of the referent after it has been garbage collected. For more information on weak references, see the weakref module.
ReferenceError.name: ReferenceError

ResourceWarning.descr: Base class for warnings related to resource usage.
ResourceWarning.name: ResourceWarning

RuntimeError.descr: Raised when an error is detected that doesn’t fall in any of the other categories. The associated value is a string indicating what precisely went wrong.
RuntimeError.name: RuntimeError

RuntimeWarning.descr: Base class for warnings about dubious runtime behavior.
RuntimeWarning.name: RuntimeWarning

StopIteration.descr: Raised by built-in function next() and an iterator‘s __next__() method to signal that there are no further items produced by the iterator.
StopIteration.name: StopIteration

SyntaxError.descr: Raised when the parser encounters a syntax error. This may occur in an import statement, in a call to the built-in functions exec() or eval(), or when reading the initial script or standard input (also interactively).
SyntaxError.name: SyntaxError

SyntaxWarning.descr: Base class for warnings about dubious syntax
SyntaxWarning.name: SyntaxWarning

SystemError.descr: Raised when the interpreter finds an internal error, but the situation does not look so serious to cause it to abandon all hope. The associated value is a string indicating what went wrong (in low-level terms).
SystemError.name: SystemError

SystemExit.descr: This exception is raised by the sys.exit() function. When it is not handled, the Python interpreter exits; no stack traceback is printed. If the associated value is an integer, it specifies the system exit status (passed to C’s exit() function); if it is None, the exit status is zero; if it has another type (such as a string), the object’s value is printed and the exit status is one.
SystemExit.name: SystemExit

TabError.descr: Raised when indentation contains an inconsistent use of tabs and spaces. This is a subclass of IndentationError.
TabError.name: TabError

TimeoutError.descr: Raised when a system function timed out at the system level. Corresponds to errno ETIMEDOUT.
TimeoutError.name: TimeoutError

True.descr: The true value of the bool type. Assignments to True are illegal and raise a SyntaxError.
True.name: True

TypeError.descr: Raised when an operation or function is applied to an object of inappropriate type. The associated value is a string giving details about the type mismatch.
TypeError.name: TypeError

UnboundLocalError.descr: Raised when a reference is made to a local variable in a function or method, but no value has been bound to that variable. This is a subclass of NameError.
UnboundLocalError.name: UnboundLocalError

UnicodeDecodeError.descr: Raised when a Unicode-related error occurs during decoding. It is a subclass of UnicodeError.
UnicodeDecodeError.name: UnicodeDecodeError

UnicodeEncodeError.descr: Raised when a Unicode-related error occurs during encoding. It is a subclass of UnicodeError.
UnicodeEncodeError.name: UnicodeEncodeError

UnicodeError.descr: Raised when a Unicode-related encoding or decoding error occurs. It is a subclass of ValueError.
UnicodeError.name: UnicodeError

UnicodeError.encoding.descr: The name of the encoding that raised the error.
UnicodeError.encoding.name: UnicodeError.encoding

UnicodeError.end.descr: The index after the last invalid data in object.
UnicodeError.end.name: UnicodeError.end

UnicodeError.object.descr: The object the codec was attempting to encode or decode.
UnicodeError.object.name: UnicodeError.object

UnicodeError.reason.descr: A string describing the specific codec error.
UnicodeError.reason.name: UnicodeError.reason

UnicodeError.start.descr: The first index of invalid data in object.
UnicodeError.start.name: UnicodeError.start

UnicodeTranslateError.descr: Raised when a Unicode-related error occurs during translating. It is a subclass of UnicodeError.
UnicodeTranslateError.name: UnicodeTranslateError

UnicodeWarning.descr: Base class for warnings related to Unicode.
UnicodeWarning.name: UnicodeWarning

UserWarning.descr: Base class for warnings generated by user code.
UserWarning.name: UserWarning

ValueError.descr: Raised when a built-in operation or function receives an argument that has the right type but an inappropriate value, and the situation is not described by a more precise exception such as IndexError.
ValueError.name: ValueError

ZeroDivisionError.descr: Raised when the second argument of a division or modulo operation is zero. The associated value is a string indicating the type of the operands and the operation.
ZeroDivisionError.name: ZeroDivisionError

__debug__.descr: This constant is true if Python was not started with an -O option. See also the assert statement.
__debug__.name: __debug__

__import__.descr: This function is invoked by the import statement. It can be replaced (by importing the builtins module and assigning to builtins.__import__) in order to change semantics of the import statement, but doing so is strongly discouraged as it is usually simpler to use import hooks (see PEP 302) to attain the same goals and does not cause issues with code which assumes the default import implementation is in use. Direct use of __import__() is also discouraged in favor of importlib.import_module().
__import__.name: __import__

_thread.LockType.descr: This is the type of lock objects.
_thread.LockType.name: _thread.LockType

_thread.allocate_lock.descr: Return a new lock object. Methods of locks are described below. The lock is initially unlocked.
_thread.allocate_lock.name: _thread.allocate_lock

_thread.exit.descr: Raise the SystemExit exception. When not caught, this will cause the thread to exit silently.
_thread.exit.name: _thread.exit

_thread.get_ident.descr: Return the ‘thread identifier’ of the current thread. This is a nonzero integer. Its value has no direct meaning; it is intended as a magic cookie to be used e.g. to index a dictionary of thread-specific data. Thread identifiers may be recycled when a thread exits and another thread is created.
_thread.get_ident.name: _thread.get_ident

_thread.interrupt_main.descr: Raise a KeyboardInterrupt exception in the main thread. A subthread can use this function to interrupt the main thread.
_thread.interrupt_main.name: _thread.interrupt_main

_thread.lock.acquire.descr: Without any optional argument, this method acquires the lock unconditionally, if necessary waiting until it is released by another thread (only one thread at a time can acquire a lock — that’s their reason for existence).
_thread.lock.acquire.name: _thread.lock.acquire

_thread.lock.locked.descr: Return the status of the lock: True if it has been acquired by some thread, False if not.
_thread.lock.locked.name: _thread.lock.locked

_thread.lock.release.descr: Releases the lock. The lock must have been acquired earlier, but not necessarily by the same thread.
_thread.lock.release.name: _thread.lock.release

_thread.stack_size.descr: Return the thread stack size used when creating new threads. The optional size argument specifies the stack size to be used for subsequently created threads, and must be 0 (use platform or configured default) or a positive integer value of at least 32,768 (32 KiB). If changing the thread stack size is unsupported, a RuntimeError is raised. If the specified stack size is invalid, a ValueError is raised and the stack size is unmodified. 32 KiB is currently the minimum supported stack size value to guarantee sufficient stack space for the interpreter itself. Note that some platforms may have particular restrictions on values for the stack size, such as requiring a minimum stack size > 32 KiB or requiring allocation in multiples of the system memory page size - platform documentation should be referred to for more information (4 KiB pages are common; using multiples of 4096 for the stack size is the suggested approach in the absence of more specific information). Availability: Windows, systems with POSIX threads.
_thread.stack_size.name: _thread.stack_size

_thread.start_new_thread.descr: Start a new thread and return its identifier. The thread executes the function function with the argument list args (which must be a tuple). The optional kwargs argument specifies a dictionary of keyword arguments. When the function returns, the thread silently exits. When the function terminates with an unhandled exception, a stack trace is printed and then the thread exits (but other threads continue to run).
_thread.start_new_thread.name: _thread.start_new_thread

abc.ABCMeta.descr: Metaclass for defining Abstract Base Classes (ABCs).
abc.ABCMeta.name: abc.ABCMeta

abc.ABCMeta.__subclasshook__.descr: (Must be defined as a class method.)
abc.ABCMeta.__subclasshook__.name: abc.ABCMeta.__subclasshook__

abc.ABCMeta.register.descr: Register subclass as a “virtual subclass” of this ABC. For example:
abc.ABCMeta.register.name: abc.ABCMeta.register

abc.abstractclassmethod.descr: A subclass of the built-in classmethod(), indicating an abstract classmethod. Otherwise it is similar to abstractmethod().
abc.abstractclassmethod.name: abc.abstractclassmethod

abc.abstractproperty.descr: A subclass of the built-in property(), indicating an abstract property.
abc.abstractproperty.name: abc.abstractproperty

abc.abstractstaticmethod.descr: A subclass of the built-in staticmethod(), indicating an abstract staticmethod. Otherwise it is similar to abstractmethod().
abc.abstractstaticmethod.name: abc.abstractstaticmethod

abs.descr: Return the absolute value of a number. The argument may be an integer or a floating point number. If the argument is a complex number, its magnitude is returned.
abs.name: abs

aifc.aifc.aifc.descr: Create an AIFF-C file. The default is that an AIFF-C file is created, unless the name of the file ends in '.aiff' in which case the default is an AIFF file.
aifc.aifc.aifc.name: aifc.aifc.aifc

aifc.aifc.aiff.descr: Create an AIFF file. The default is that an AIFF-C file is created, unless the name of the file ends in '.aiff' in which case the default is an AIFF file.
aifc.aifc.aiff.name: aifc.aifc.aiff

aifc.aifc.close.descr: Close the AIFF file. After calling this method, the object can no longer be used.
aifc.aifc.close.name: aifc.aifc.close

aifc.aifc.getcompname.descr: Return a bytes array convertible to a human-readable description of the type of compression used in the audio file. For AIFF files, the returned value is b'not compressed'.
aifc.aifc.getcompname.name: aifc.aifc.getcompname

aifc.aifc.getcomptype.descr: Return a bytes array of length 4 describing the type of compression used in the audio file. For AIFF files, the returned value is b'NONE'.
aifc.aifc.getcomptype.name: aifc.aifc.getcomptype

aifc.aifc.getframerate.descr: Return the sampling rate (number of audio frames per second).
aifc.aifc.getframerate.name: aifc.aifc.getframerate

aifc.aifc.getmark.descr: Return the tuple as described in getmarkers() for the mark with the given id.
aifc.aifc.getmark.name: aifc.aifc.getmark

aifc.aifc.getmarkers.descr: Return a list of markers in the audio file. A marker consists of a tuple of three elements. The first is the mark ID (an integer), the second is the mark position in frames from the beginning of the data (an integer), the third is the name of the mark (a string).
aifc.aifc.getmarkers.name: aifc.aifc.getmarkers

aifc.aifc.getnchannels.descr: Return the number of audio channels (1 for mono, 2 for stereo).
aifc.aifc.getnchannels.name: aifc.aifc.getnchannels

aifc.aifc.getnframes.descr: Return the number of audio frames in the file.
aifc.aifc.getnframes.name: aifc.aifc.getnframes

aifc.aifc.getparams.descr: Return a tuple consisting of all of the above values in the above order.
aifc.aifc.getparams.name: aifc.aifc.getparams

aifc.aifc.getsampwidth.descr: Return the size in bytes of individual samples.
aifc.aifc.getsampwidth.name: aifc.aifc.getsampwidth

aifc.aifc.readframes.descr: Read and return the next nframes frames from the audio file. The returned data is a string containing for each frame the uncompressed samples of all channels.
aifc.aifc.readframes.name: aifc.aifc.readframes

aifc.aifc.rewind.descr: Rewind the read pointer. The next readframes() will start from the beginning.
aifc.aifc.rewind.name: aifc.aifc.rewind

aifc.aifc.setframerate.descr: Specify the sampling frequency in frames per second.
aifc.aifc.setframerate.name: aifc.aifc.setframerate

aifc.aifc.setmark.descr: Add a mark with the given id (larger than 0), and the given name at the given position. This method can be called at any time before close().
aifc.aifc.setmark.name: aifc.aifc.setmark

aifc.aifc.setnchannels.descr: Specify the number of channels in the audio file.
aifc.aifc.setnchannels.name: aifc.aifc.setnchannels

aifc.aifc.setnframes.descr: Specify the number of frames that are to be written to the audio file. If this parameter is not set, or not set correctly, the file needs to support seeking.
aifc.aifc.setnframes.name: aifc.aifc.setnframes

aifc.aifc.setparams.descr: Set all the above parameters at once. The argument is a tuple consisting of the various parameters. This means that it is possible to use the result of a getparams() call as argument to setparams().
aifc.aifc.setparams.name: aifc.aifc.setparams

aifc.aifc.setpos.descr: Seek to the specified frame number.
aifc.aifc.setpos.name: aifc.aifc.setpos

aifc.aifc.setsampwidth.descr: Specify the size in bytes of audio samples.
aifc.aifc.setsampwidth.name: aifc.aifc.setsampwidth

aifc.aifc.writeframes.descr: Write data to the output file. This method can only be called after the audio file parameters have been set.
aifc.aifc.writeframes.name: aifc.aifc.writeframes

aifc.aifc.writeframesraw.descr: Like writeframes(), except that the header of the audio file is not updated.
aifc.aifc.writeframesraw.name: aifc.aifc.writeframesraw

aifc.open.descr: Open an AIFF or AIFF-C file and return an object instance with methods that are described below. The argument file is either a string naming a file or a file object. mode must be 'r' or 'rb' when the file must be opened for reading, or 'w' or 'wb' when the file must be opened for writing. If omitted, file.mode is used if it exists, otherwise 'rb' is used. When used for writing, the file object should be seekable, unless you know ahead of time how many samples you are going to write in total and use writeframesraw() and setnframes().
aifc.open.name: aifc.open

all.descr: Return True if all elements of the iterable are true (or if the iterable is empty). Equivalent to:
all.name: all

any.descr: Return True if any element of the iterable is true. If the iterable is empty, return False. Equivalent to:
any.name: any

append.descr: Append a new item with value x to the end of the array.
append.name: array.array.append

argparse.ArgumentDefaultsHelpFormatter.descr: RawDescriptionHelpFormatter and RawTextHelpFormatter give more control over how textual descriptions are displayed. By default, ArgumentParser objects line-wrap the description and epilog texts in command-line help messages:
argparse.ArgumentDefaultsHelpFormatter.name: argparse.ArgumentDefaultsHelpFormatter

argparse.ArgumentParser.descr: Create a new ArgumentParser object. All parameters should be passed as keyword arguments. Each parameter has its own more detailed description below, but in short they are:
argparse.ArgumentParser.name: argparse.ArgumentParser
argparse.ArgumentParser.syntax: class argparse.ArgumentParser(prog=None, usage=None, description=None, epilog=None, parents=[], formatter_class=argparse.HelpFormatter, prefix_chars='-', fromfile_prefix_chars=None, argument_default=None, conflict_handler='error', add_help=True)

argparse.ArgumentParser.add_argument.descr: Define how a single command-line argument should be parsed. Each parameter has its own more detailed description below, but in short they are:
argparse.ArgumentParser.add_argument.name: argparse.ArgumentParser.add_argument
argparse.ArgumentParser.add_argument.syntax: ArgumentParser.add_argument(name or flags...[, action][, nargs][, const][, default][, type][, choices][, required][, help][, metavar][, dest])

argparse.ArgumentParser.add_argument_gro.descr: By default, ArgumentParser groups command-line arguments into “positional arguments” and “optional arguments” when displaying help messages. When there is a better conceptual grouping of arguments than this default one, appropriate groups can be created using the add_argument_group() method:
argparse.ArgumentParser.add_argument_gro.name: argparse.ArgumentParser.add_argument_group

argparse.ArgumentParser.add_mutually_exc.descr: Create a mutually exclusive group. argparse will make sure that only one of the arguments in the mutually exclusive group was present on the command line:
argparse.ArgumentParser.add_mutually_exc.name: argparse.ArgumentParser.add_mutually_exclusive_group

argparse.ArgumentParser.add_subparsers.descr: Many programs split up their functionality into a number of sub-commands, for example, the svn program can invoke sub-commands like svn checkout, svn update, and svn commit. Splitting up functionality this way can be a particularly good idea when a program performs several different functions which require different kinds of command-line arguments. ArgumentParser supports the creation of such sub-commands with the add_subparsers() method. The add_subparsers() method is normally called with no arguments and returns a special action object. This object has a single method, add_parser(), which takes a command name and any ArgumentParser constructor arguments, and returns an ArgumentParser object that can be modified as usual.
argparse.ArgumentParser.add_subparsers.name: argparse.ArgumentParser.add_subparsers
argparse.ArgumentParser.add_subparsers.syntax: ArgumentParser.add_subparsers([title][, description][, prog][, parser_class][, action][, option_string][, dest][, help][, metavar])

argparse.ArgumentParser.convert_arg_line.descr: Arguments that are read from a file (see the fromfile_prefix_chars keyword argument to the ArgumentParser constructor) are read one argument per line. convert_arg_line_to_args() can be overriden for fancier reading.
argparse.ArgumentParser.convert_arg_line.name: argparse.ArgumentParser.convert_arg_line_to_args

argparse.ArgumentParser.error.descr: This method prints a usage message including the message to the standard error and terminates the program with a status code of 2.
argparse.ArgumentParser.error.name: argparse.ArgumentParser.error

argparse.ArgumentParser.exit.descr: This method terminates the program, exiting with the specified status and, if given, it prints a message before that.
argparse.ArgumentParser.exit.name: argparse.ArgumentParser.exit

argparse.ArgumentParser.format_help.descr: Return a string containing a help message, including the program usage and information about the arguments registered with the ArgumentParser.
argparse.ArgumentParser.format_help.name: argparse.ArgumentParser.format_help

argparse.ArgumentParser.format_usage.descr: Return a string containing a brief description of how the ArgumentParser should be invoked on the command line.
argparse.ArgumentParser.format_usage.name: argparse.ArgumentParser.format_usage

argparse.ArgumentParser.get_default.descr: Get the default value for a namespace attribute, as set by either add_argument() or by set_defaults():
argparse.ArgumentParser.get_default.name: argparse.ArgumentParser.get_default

argparse.ArgumentParser.parse_args.descr: Convert argument strings to objects and assign them as attributes of the namespace. Return the populated namespace.
argparse.ArgumentParser.parse_args.name: argparse.ArgumentParser.parse_args

argparse.ArgumentParser.parse_known_args.descr: Sometimes a script may only parse a few of the command-line arguments, passing the remaining arguments on to another script or program. In these cases, the parse_known_args() method can be useful. It works much like parse_args() except that it does not produce an error when extra arguments are present. Instead, it returns a two item tuple containing the populated namespace and the list of remaining argument strings.
argparse.ArgumentParser.parse_known_args.name: argparse.ArgumentParser.parse_known_args

argparse.ArgumentParser.print_help.descr: Print a help message, including the program usage and information about the arguments registered with the ArgumentParser. If file is None, sys.stdout is assumed.
argparse.ArgumentParser.print_help.name: argparse.ArgumentParser.print_help

argparse.ArgumentParser.print_usage.descr: Print a brief description of how the ArgumentParser should be invoked on the command line. If file is None, sys.stdout is assumed.
argparse.ArgumentParser.print_usage.name: argparse.ArgumentParser.print_usage

argparse.ArgumentParser.set_defaults.descr: Most of the time, the attributes of the object returned by parse_args() will be fully determined by inspecting the command-line arguments and the argument actions. set_defaults() allows some additional attributes that are determined without any inspection of the command line to be added:
argparse.ArgumentParser.set_defaults.name: argparse.ArgumentParser.set_defaults

argparse.FileType.descr: The FileType factory creates objects that can be passed to the type argument of ArgumentParser.add_argument(). Arguments that have FileType objects as their type will open command-line arguments as files with the requested modes and buffer sizes:
argparse.FileType.name: argparse.FileType

argparse.MetavarTypeHelpFormatter.descr: RawDescriptionHelpFormatter and RawTextHelpFormatter give more control over how textual descriptions are displayed. By default, ArgumentParser objects line-wrap the description and epilog texts in command-line help messages:
argparse.MetavarTypeHelpFormatter.name: argparse.MetavarTypeHelpFormatter

argparse.Namespace.descr: Simple class used by default by parse_args() to create an object holding attributes and return it.
argparse.Namespace.name: argparse.Namespace

argparse.RawDescriptionHelpFormatter.descr: RawDescriptionHelpFormatter and RawTextHelpFormatter give more control over how textual descriptions are displayed. By default, ArgumentParser objects line-wrap the description and epilog texts in command-line help messages:
argparse.RawDescriptionHelpFormatter.name: argparse.RawDescriptionHelpFormatter

argparse.RawTextHelpFormatter.descr: RawDescriptionHelpFormatter and RawTextHelpFormatter give more control over how textual descriptions are displayed. By default, ArgumentParser objects line-wrap the description and epilog texts in command-line help messages:
argparse.RawTextHelpFormatter.name: argparse.RawTextHelpFormatter

array.descr: A new array whose items are restricted by typecode, and initialized from the optional initializer value, which must be a list, a bytes-like object, or iterable over elements of the appropriate type.
array.name: array.array

array.array.descr: A new array whose items are restricted by typecode, and initialized from the optional initializer value, which must be a list, a bytes-like object, or iterable over elements of the appropriate type.
array.array.name: array.array

array.array.append.descr: Append a new item with value x to the end of the array.
array.array.append.name: array.array.append

array.array.buffer_info.descr: Return a tuple (address, length) giving the current memory address and the length in elements of the buffer used to hold array’s contents. The size of the memory buffer in bytes can be computed as array.buffer_info()[1] * array.itemsize. This is occasionally useful when working with low-level (and inherently unsafe) I/O interfaces that require memory addresses, such as certain ioctl() operations. The returned numbers are valid as long as the array exists and no length-changing operations are applied to it.
array.array.buffer_info.name: array.array.buffer_info

array.array.byteswap.descr: “Byteswap” all items of the array. This is only supported for values which are 1, 2, 4, or 8 bytes in size; for other types of values, RuntimeError is raised. It is useful when reading data from a file written on a machine with a different byte order.
array.array.byteswap.name: array.array.byteswap

array.array.count.descr: Return the number of occurrences of x in the array.
array.array.count.name: array.array.count

array.array.extend.descr: Append items from iterable to the end of the array. If iterable is another array, it must have exactly the same type code; if not, TypeError will be raised. If iterable is not an array, it must be iterable and its elements must be the right type to be appended to the array.
array.array.extend.name: array.array.extend

array.array.frombytes.descr: Appends items from the string, interpreting the string as an array of machine values (as if it had been read from a file using the fromfile() method).
array.array.frombytes.name: array.array.frombytes

array.array.fromfile.descr: Read n items (as machine values) from the file object f and append them to the end of the array. If less than n items are available, EOFError is raised, but the items that were available are still inserted into the array. f must be a real built-in file object; something else with a read() method won’t do.
array.array.fromfile.name: array.array.fromfile

array.array.fromlist.descr: Append items from the list. This is equivalent to for x in list: a.append(x) except that if there is a type error, the array is unchanged.
array.array.fromlist.name: array.array.fromlist

array.array.fromunicode.descr: Extends this array with data from the given unicode string. The array must be a type 'u' array; otherwise a ValueError is raised. Use array.frombytes(unicodestring.encode(enc)) to append Unicode data to an array of some other type.
array.array.fromunicode.name: array.array.fromunicode

array.array.index.descr: Return the smallest i such that i is the index of the first occurrence of x in the array.
array.array.index.name: array.array.index

array.array.insert.descr: Insert a new item with value x in the array before position i. Negative values are treated as being relative to the end of the array.
array.array.insert.name: array.array.insert

array.array.itemsize.descr: The length in bytes of one array item in the internal representation.
array.array.itemsize.name: array.array.itemsize

array.array.pop.descr: Removes the item with the index i from the array and returns it. The optional argument defaults to -1, so that by default the last item is removed and returned.
array.array.pop.name: array.array.pop

array.array.remove.descr: Remove the first occurrence of x from the array.
array.array.remove.name: array.array.remove

array.array.reverse.descr: Reverse the order of the items in the array.
array.array.reverse.name: array.array.reverse

array.array.tobytes.descr: Convert the array to an array of machine values and return the bytes representation (the same sequence of bytes that would be written to a file by the tofile() method.)
array.array.tobytes.name: array.array.tobytes

array.array.tofile.descr: Write all items (as machine values) to the file object f.
array.array.tofile.name: array.array.tofile

array.array.tolist.descr: Convert the array to an ordinary list with the same items.
array.array.tolist.name: array.array.tolist

array.array.tounicode.descr: Convert the array to a unicode string. The array must be a type 'u' array; otherwise a ValueError is raised. Use array.tobytes().decode(enc) to obtain a unicode string from an array of some other type.
array.array.tounicode.name: array.array.tounicode

array.array.typecode.descr: The typecode character used to create the array.
array.array.typecode.name: array.array.typecode

array.typecodes.descr: A string with all available type codes.
array.typecodes.name: array.typecodes

as_integer_ratio.descr: Return a pair of integers whose ratio is exactly equal to the original float and with a positive denominator. Raises OverflowError on infinities and a ValueError on NaNs.
as_integer_ratio.name: float.as_integer_ratio

ascii.descr: As repr(), return a string containing a printable representation of an object, but escape the non-ASCII characters in the string returned by repr() using \x, \u or \U escapes. This generates a string similar to that returned by repr() in Python 2.
ascii.name: ascii

asynchat.async_chat.descr: This class is an abstract subclass of asyncore.dispatcher. To make practical use of the code you must subclass async_chat, providing meaningful collect_incoming_data() and found_terminator() methods. The asyncore.dispatcher methods can be used, although not all make sense in a message/response context.
asynchat.async_chat.name: asynchat.async_chat

asynchat.async_chat.close_when_done.descr: Pushes a None on to the producer fifo. When this producer is popped off the fifo it causes the channel to be closed.
asynchat.async_chat.close_when_done.name: asynchat.async_chat.close_when_done

asynchat.async_chat.collect_incoming_dat.descr: Called with data holding an arbitrary amount of received data. The default method, which must be overridden, raises a NotImplementedError exception.
asynchat.async_chat.collect_incoming_dat.name: asynchat.async_chat.collect_incoming_data

asynchat.async_chat.discard_buffers.descr: In emergencies this method will discard any data held in the input and/or output buffers and the producer fifo.
asynchat.async_chat.discard_buffers.name: asynchat.async_chat.discard_buffers

asynchat.async_chat.found_terminator.descr: Called when the incoming data stream matches the termination condition set by set_terminator(). The default method, which must be overridden, raises a NotImplementedError exception. The buffered input data should be available via an instance attribute.
asynchat.async_chat.found_terminator.name: asynchat.async_chat.found_terminator

asynchat.async_chat.get_terminator.descr: Returns the current terminator for the channel.
asynchat.async_chat.get_terminator.name: asynchat.async_chat.get_terminator

asynchat.async_chat.push.descr: Pushes data on to the channel’s fifo to ensure its transmission. This is all you need to do to have the channel write the data out to the network, although it is possible to use your own producers in more complex schemes to implement encryption and chunking, for example.
asynchat.async_chat.push.name: asynchat.async_chat.push

asynchat.async_chat.push_with_producer.descr: Takes a producer object and adds it to the producer fifo associated with the channel. When all currently-pushed producers have been exhausted the channel will consume this producer’s data by calling its more() method and send the data to the remote endpoint.
asynchat.async_chat.push_with_producer.name: asynchat.async_chat.push_with_producer

asynchat.async_chat.set_terminator.descr: Sets the terminating condition to be recognized on the channel. term may be any of three types of value, corresponding to three different ways to handle incoming protocol data.
asynchat.async_chat.set_terminator.name: asynchat.async_chat.set_terminator

asynchat.fifo.descr: A fifo holding data which has been pushed by the application but not yet popped for writing to the channel. A fifo is a list used to hold data and/or producers until they are required. If the list argument is provided then it should contain producers or data items to be written to the channel.
asynchat.fifo.name: asynchat.fifo

asynchat.fifo.first.descr: Returns the least-recently push()ed item from the fifo.
asynchat.fifo.first.name: asynchat.fifo.first

asynchat.fifo.is_empty.descr: Returns True if and only if the fifo is empty.
asynchat.fifo.is_empty.name: asynchat.fifo.is_empty

asynchat.fifo.pop.descr: If the fifo is not empty, returns True, first(), deleting the popped item. Returns False, None for an empty fifo.
asynchat.fifo.pop.name: asynchat.fifo.pop

asynchat.fifo.push.descr: Adds the given data (which may be a string or a producer object) to the producer fifo.
asynchat.fifo.push.name: asynchat.fifo.push

asyncore.dispatcher.descr: The dispatcher class is a thin wrapper around a low-level socket object. To make it more useful, it has a few methods for event-handling which are called from the asynchronous loop. Otherwise, it can be treated as a normal non-blocking socket object.
asyncore.dispatcher.name: asyncore.dispatcher

asyncore.dispatcher.accept.descr: Accept a connection. The socket must be bound to an address and listening for connections. The return value can be either None or a pair (conn, address) where conn is a new socket object usable to send and receive data on the connection, and address is the address bound to the socket on the other end of the connection. When None is returned it means the connection didn’t take place, in which case the server should just ignore this event and keep listening for further incoming connections.
asyncore.dispatcher.accept.name: asyncore.dispatcher.accept

asyncore.dispatcher.bind.descr: Bind the socket to address. The socket must not already be bound. (The format of address depends on the address family — refer to the socket documentation for more information.) To mark the socket as re-usable (setting the SO_REUSEADDR option), call the dispatcher object’s set_reuse_addr() method.
asyncore.dispatcher.bind.name: asyncore.dispatcher.bind

asyncore.dispatcher.close.descr: Close the socket. All future operations on the socket object will fail. The remote end-point will receive no more data (after queued data is flushed). Sockets are automatically closed when they are garbage-collected.
asyncore.dispatcher.close.name: asyncore.dispatcher.close

asyncore.dispatcher.connect.descr: As with the normal socket object, address is a tuple with the first element the host to connect to, and the second the port number.
asyncore.dispatcher.connect.name: asyncore.dispatcher.connect

asyncore.dispatcher.create_socket.descr: This is identical to the creation of a normal socket, and will use the same options for creation. Refer to the socket documentation for information on creating sockets.
asyncore.dispatcher.create_socket.name: asyncore.dispatcher.create_socket

asyncore.dispatcher.handle_accept.descr: Called on listening channels (passive openers) when a connection can be established with a new remote endpoint that has issued a connect() call for the local endpoint. Deprecated in version 3.2; use handle_accepted() instead.
asyncore.dispatcher.handle_accept.name: asyncore.dispatcher.handle_accept

asyncore.dispatcher.handle_accepted.descr: Called on listening channels (passive openers) when a connection has been established with a new remote endpoint that has issued a connect() call for the local endpoint. sock is a new socket object usable to send and receive data on the connection, and addr is the address bound to the socket on the other end of the connection.
asyncore.dispatcher.handle_accepted.name: asyncore.dispatcher.handle_accepted

asyncore.dispatcher.handle_close.descr: Called when the socket is closed.
asyncore.dispatcher.handle_close.name: asyncore.dispatcher.handle_close

asyncore.dispatcher.handle_connect.descr: Called when the active opener’s socket actually makes a connection. Might send a “welcome” banner, or initiate a protocol negotiation with the remote endpoint, for example.
asyncore.dispatcher.handle_connect.name: asyncore.dispatcher.handle_connect

asyncore.dispatcher.handle_error.descr: Called when an exception is raised and not otherwise handled. The default version prints a condensed traceback.
asyncore.dispatcher.handle_error.name: asyncore.dispatcher.handle_error

asyncore.dispatcher.handle_expt.descr: Called when there is out of band (OOB) data for a socket connection. This will almost never happen, as OOB is tenuously supported and rarely used.
asyncore.dispatcher.handle_expt.name: asyncore.dispatcher.handle_expt

asyncore.dispatcher.handle_read.descr: Called when the asynchronous loop detects that a read() call on the channel’s socket will succeed.
asyncore.dispatcher.handle_read.name: asyncore.dispatcher.handle_read

asyncore.dispatcher.handle_write.descr: Called when the asynchronous loop detects that a writable socket can be written. Often this method will implement the necessary buffering for performance. For example:
asyncore.dispatcher.handle_write.name: asyncore.dispatcher.handle_write

asyncore.dispatcher.listen.descr: Listen for connections made to the socket. The backlog argument specifies the maximum number of queued connections and should be at least 1; the maximum value is system-dependent (usually 5).
asyncore.dispatcher.listen.name: asyncore.dispatcher.listen

asyncore.dispatcher.readable.descr: Called each time around the asynchronous loop to determine whether a channel’s socket should be added to the list on which read events can occur. The default method simply returns True, indicating that by default, all channels will be interested in read events.
asyncore.dispatcher.readable.name: asyncore.dispatcher.readable

asyncore.dispatcher.recv.descr: Read at most buffer_size bytes from the socket’s remote end-point. An empty bytes object implies that the channel has been closed from the other end.
asyncore.dispatcher.recv.name: asyncore.dispatcher.recv

asyncore.dispatcher.send.descr: Send data to the remote end-point of the socket.
asyncore.dispatcher.send.name: asyncore.dispatcher.send

asyncore.dispatcher.writable.descr: Called each time around the asynchronous loop to determine whether a channel’s socket should be added to the list on which write events can occur. The default method simply returns True, indicating that by default, all channels will be interested in write events.
asyncore.dispatcher.writable.name: asyncore.dispatcher.writable

asyncore.dispatcher_with_send.descr: A dispatcher subclass which adds simple buffered output capability, useful for simple clients. For more sophisticated usage use asynchat.async_chat.
asyncore.dispatcher_with_send.name: asyncore.dispatcher_with_send

asyncore.file_dispatcher.descr: A file_dispatcher takes a file descriptor or file object along with an optional map argument and wraps it for use with the poll() or loop() functions. If provided a file object or anything with a fileno() method, that method will be called and passed to the file_wrapper constructor. Availability: UNIX.
asyncore.file_dispatcher.name: asyncore.file_dispatcher

asyncore.file_wrapper.descr: A file_wrapper takes an integer file descriptor and calls os.dup() to duplicate the handle so that the original handle may be closed independently of the file_wrapper. This class implements sufficient methods to emulate a socket for use by the file_dispatcher class. Availability: UNIX.
asyncore.file_wrapper.name: asyncore.file_wrapper

asyncore.loop.descr: Enter a polling loop that terminates after count passes or all open channels have been closed. All arguments are optional. The count parameter defaults to None, resulting in the loop terminating only when all channels have been closed. The timeout argument sets the timeout parameter for the appropriate select() or poll() call, measured in seconds; the default is 30 seconds. The use_poll parameter, if true, indicates that poll() should be used in preference to select() (the default is False).
asyncore.loop.name: asyncore.loop

atexit.register.descr: Register func as a function to be executed at termination. Any optional arguments that are to be passed to func must be passed as arguments to register(). It is possible to register the same function and arguments more than once.
atexit.register.name: atexit.register

atexit.unregister.descr: Remove func from the list of functions to be run at interpreter shutdown. After calling unregister(), func is guaranteed not to be called when the interpreter shuts down, even if it was registered more than once. unregister() silently does nothing if func was not previously registered.
atexit.unregister.name: atexit.unregister

audioop.add.descr: Return a fragment which is the addition of the two samples passed as parameters. width is the sample width in bytes, either 1, 2 or 4. Both fragments should have the same length. Samples are truncated in case of overflow.
audioop.add.name: audioop.add

audioop.adpcm2lin.descr: Decode an Intel/DVI ADPCM coded fragment to a linear fragment. See the description of lin2adpcm() for details on ADPCM coding. Return a tuple (sample, newstate) where the sample has the width specified in width.
audioop.adpcm2lin.name: audioop.adpcm2lin

audioop.alaw2lin.descr: Convert sound fragments in a-LAW encoding to linearly encoded sound fragments. a-LAW encoding always uses 8 bits samples, so width refers only to the sample width of the output fragment here.
audioop.alaw2lin.name: audioop.alaw2lin

audioop.avg.descr: Return the average over all samples in the fragment.
audioop.avg.name: audioop.avg

audioop.avgpp.descr: Return the average peak-peak value over all samples in the fragment. No filtering is done, so the usefulness of this routine is questionable.
audioop.avgpp.name: audioop.avgpp

audioop.bias.descr: Return a fragment that is the original fragment with a bias added to each sample. Samples wrap around in case of overflow.
audioop.bias.name: audioop.bias

audioop.cross.descr: Return the number of zero crossings in the fragment passed as an argument.
audioop.cross.name: audioop.cross

audioop.error.descr: This exception is raised on all errors, such as unknown number of bytes per sample, etc.
audioop.error.name: audioop.error

audioop.findfactor.descr: Return a factor F such that rms(add(fragment, mul(reference, -F))) is minimal, i.e., return the factor with which you should multiply reference to make it match as well as possible to fragment. The fragments should both contain 2-byte samples.
audioop.findfactor.name: audioop.findfactor

audioop.findfit.descr: Try to match reference as well as possible to a portion of fragment (which should be the longer fragment). This is (conceptually) done by taking slices out of fragment, using findfactor() to compute the best match, and minimizing the result. The fragments should both contain 2-byte samples. Return a tuple (offset, factor) where offset is the (integer) offset into fragment where the optimal match started and factor is the (floating-point) factor as per findfactor().
audioop.findfit.name: audioop.findfit

audioop.findmax.descr: Search fragment for a slice of length length samples (not bytes!) with maximum energy, i.e., return i for which rms(fragment[i*2:(i+length)*2]) is maximal. The fragments should both contain 2-byte samples.
audioop.findmax.name: audioop.findmax

audioop.getsample.descr: Return the value of sample index from the fragment.
audioop.getsample.name: audioop.getsample

audioop.lin2adpcm.descr: Convert samples to 4 bit Intel/DVI ADPCM encoding. ADPCM coding is an adaptive coding scheme, whereby each 4 bit number is the difference between one sample and the next, divided by a (varying) step. The Intel/DVI ADPCM algorithm has been selected for use by the IMA, so it may well become a standard.
audioop.lin2adpcm.name: audioop.lin2adpcm

audioop.lin2alaw.descr: Convert samples in the audio fragment to a-LAW encoding and return this as a bytes object. a-LAW is an audio encoding format whereby you get a dynamic range of about 13 bits using only 8 bit samples. It is used by the Sun audio hardware, among others.
audioop.lin2alaw.name: audioop.lin2alaw

audioop.lin2ulaw.descr: Convert samples in the audio fragment to u-LAW encoding and return this as a bytes object. u-LAW is an audio encoding format whereby you get a dynamic range of about 14 bits using only 8 bit samples. It is used by the Sun audio hardware, among others.
audioop.lin2ulaw.name: audioop.lin2ulaw

audioop.max.descr: Return the maximum of the absolute value of all samples in a fragment.
audioop.max.name: audioop.max

audioop.maxpp.descr: Return the maximum peak-peak value in the sound fragment.
audioop.maxpp.name: audioop.maxpp

audioop.minmax.descr: Return a tuple consisting of the minimum and maximum values of all samples in the sound fragment.
audioop.minmax.name: audioop.minmax

audioop.mul.descr: Return a fragment that has all samples in the original fragment multiplied by the floating-point value factor. Samples are truncated in case of overflow.
audioop.mul.name: audioop.mul

audioop.ratecv.descr: Convert the frame rate of the input fragment.
audioop.ratecv.name: audioop.ratecv
audioop.ratecv.syntax: audioop.ratecv(fragment, width, nchannels, inrate, outrate, state[, weightA[, weightB]])

audioop.reverse.descr: Reverse the samples in a fragment and returns the modified fragment.
audioop.reverse.name: audioop.reverse

audioop.rms.descr: Return the root-mean-square of the fragment, i.e. sqrt(sum(S_i^2)/n).
audioop.rms.name: audioop.rms

audioop.tomono.descr: Convert a stereo fragment to a mono fragment. The left channel is multiplied by lfactor and the right channel by rfactor before adding the two channels to give a mono signal.
audioop.tomono.name: audioop.tomono

audioop.tostereo.descr: Generate a stereo fragment from a mono fragment. Each pair of samples in the stereo fragment are computed from the mono sample, whereby left channel samples are multiplied by lfactor and right channel samples by rfactor.
audioop.tostereo.name: audioop.tostereo

audioop.ulaw2lin.descr: Convert sound fragments in u-LAW encoding to linearly encoded sound fragments. u-LAW encoding always uses 8 bits samples, so width refers only to the sample width of the output fragment here.
audioop.ulaw2lin.name: audioop.ulaw2lin

base64.b16decode.descr: Decode a Base16 encoded byte string.
base64.b16decode.name: base64.b16decode

base64.b16encode.descr: Encode a byte string using Base16.
base64.b16encode.name: base64.b16encode

base64.b32decode.descr: Decode a Base32 encoded byte string.
base64.b32decode.name: base64.b32decode

base64.b32encode.descr: Encode a byte string using Base32. s is the string to encode. The encoded string is returned.
base64.b32encode.name: base64.b32encode

base64.b64decode.descr: Decode a Base64 encoded byte string.
base64.b64decode.name: base64.b64decode

base64.b64encode.descr: Encode a byte string using Base64.
base64.b64encode.name: base64.b64encode

base64.decode.descr: Decode the contents of the binary input file and write the resulting binary data to the output file. input and output must be file objects. input will be read until input.read() returns an empty bytes object.
base64.decode.name: base64.decode

base64.decodebytes.descr: Decode the byte string s, which must contain one or more lines of base64 encoded data, and return a byte string containing the resulting binary data. decodestring is a deprecated alias.
base64.decodebytes.name: base64.decodebytes

base64.decodestring.descr: Decode the byte string s, which must contain one or more lines of base64 encoded data, and return a byte string containing the resulting binary data. decodestring is a deprecated alias.
base64.decodestring.name: base64.decodestring

base64.encode.descr: Encode the contents of the binary input file and write the resulting base64 encoded data to the output file. input and output must be file objects. input will be read until input.read() returns an empty bytes object. encode() returns the encoded data plus a trailing newline character (b'\n').
base64.encode.name: base64.encode

base64.encodebytes.descr: Encode the byte string s, which can contain arbitrary binary data, and return a byte string containing one or more lines of base64-encoded data. encodebytes() returns a string containing one or more lines of base64-encoded data always including an extra trailing newline (b'\n'). encodestring is a deprecated alias.
base64.encodebytes.name: base64.encodebytes

base64.encodestring.descr: Encode the byte string s, which can contain arbitrary binary data, and return a byte string containing one or more lines of base64-encoded data. encodebytes() returns a string containing one or more lines of base64-encoded data always including an extra trailing newline (b'\n'). encodestring is a deprecated alias.
base64.encodestring.name: base64.encodestring

base64.standard_b64decode.descr: Decode byte string s using the standard Base64 alphabet.
base64.standard_b64decode.name: base64.standard_b64decode

base64.standard_b64encode.descr: Encode byte string s using the standard Base64 alphabet.
base64.standard_b64encode.name: base64.standard_b64encode

base64.urlsafe_b64decode.descr: Decode byte string s using a URL-safe alphabet, which substitutes - instead of + and _ instead of / in the standard Base64 alphabet.
base64.urlsafe_b64decode.name: base64.urlsafe_b64decode

base64.urlsafe_b64encode.descr: Encode byte string s using a URL-safe alphabet, which substitutes - instead of + and _ instead of / in the standard Base64 alphabet. The result can still contain =.
base64.urlsafe_b64encode.name: base64.urlsafe_b64encode

bdb.Bdb.descr: The Bdb class acts as a generic Python debugger base class.
bdb.Bdb.name: bdb.Bdb

bdb.Bdb.break_anywhere.descr: This method checks if there is a breakpoint in the filename of the current frame.
bdb.Bdb.break_anywhere.name: bdb.Bdb.break_anywhere

bdb.Bdb.break_here.descr: This method checks if there is a breakpoint in the filename and line belonging to frame or, at least, in the current function. If the breakpoint is a temporary one, this method deletes it.
bdb.Bdb.break_here.name: bdb.Bdb.break_here

bdb.Bdb.canonic.descr: Auxiliary method for getting a filename in a canonical form, that is, as a case-normalized (on case-insensitive filesystems) absolute path, stripped of surrounding angle brackets.
bdb.Bdb.canonic.name: bdb.Bdb.canonic

bdb.Bdb.clear_all_file_breaks.descr: Delete all breakpoints in filename. If none were set, an error message is returned.
bdb.Bdb.clear_all_file_breaks.name: bdb.Bdb.clear_all_file_breaks

bdb.Bdb.clear_bpbynumber.descr: Delete the breakpoint which has the index arg in the Breakpoint.bpbynumber. If arg is not numeric or out of range, return an error message.
bdb.Bdb.clear_bpbynumber.name: bdb.Bdb.clear_bpbynumber

bdb.Bdb.clear_break.descr: Delete the breakpoints in filename and lineno. If none were set, an error message is returned.
bdb.Bdb.clear_break.name: bdb.Bdb.clear_break

bdb.Bdb.dispatch_call.descr: If the debugger should stop on this function call, invoke the user_call() method (which should be overridden in subclasses). Raise a BdbQuit exception if the Bdb.quitting flag is set (which can be set from user_call()). Return a reference to the trace_dispatch() method for further tracing in that scope.
bdb.Bdb.dispatch_call.name: bdb.Bdb.dispatch_call

bdb.Bdb.dispatch_exception.descr: If the debugger should stop at this exception, invokes the user_exception() method (which should be overridden in subclasses). Raise a BdbQuit exception if the Bdb.quitting flag is set (which can be set from user_exception()). Return a reference to the trace_dispatch() method for further tracing in that scope.
bdb.Bdb.dispatch_exception.name: bdb.Bdb.dispatch_exception

bdb.Bdb.dispatch_line.descr: If the debugger should stop on the current line, invoke the user_line() method (which should be overridden in subclasses). Raise a BdbQuit exception if the Bdb.quitting flag is set (which can be set from user_line()). Return a reference to the trace_dispatch() method for further tracing in that scope.
bdb.Bdb.dispatch_line.name: bdb.Bdb.dispatch_line

bdb.Bdb.dispatch_return.descr: If the debugger should stop on this function return, invoke the user_return() method (which should be overridden in subclasses). Raise a BdbQuit exception if the Bdb.quitting flag is set (which can be set from user_return()). Return a reference to the trace_dispatch() method for further tracing in that scope.
bdb.Bdb.dispatch_return.name: bdb.Bdb.dispatch_return

bdb.Bdb.do_clear.descr: Handle how a breakpoint must be removed when it is a temporary one.
bdb.Bdb.do_clear.name: bdb.Bdb.do_clear

bdb.Bdb.format_stack_entry.descr: Return a string with information about a stack entry, identified by a (frame, lineno) tuple:
bdb.Bdb.format_stack_entry.name: bdb.Bdb.format_stack_entry

bdb.Bdb.get_all_breaks.descr: Return all breakpoints that are set.
bdb.Bdb.get_all_breaks.name: bdb.Bdb.get_all_breaks

bdb.Bdb.get_bpbynumber.descr: Return a breakpoint specified by the given number. If arg is a string, it will be converted to a number. If arg is a non-numeric string, if the given breakpoint never existed or has been deleted, a ValueError is raised.
bdb.Bdb.get_bpbynumber.name: bdb.Bdb.get_bpbynumber

bdb.Bdb.get_break.descr: Check if there is a breakpoint for lineno of filename.
bdb.Bdb.get_break.name: bdb.Bdb.get_break

bdb.Bdb.get_breaks.descr: Return all breakpoints for lineno in filename, or an empty list if none are set.
bdb.Bdb.get_breaks.name: bdb.Bdb.get_breaks

bdb.Bdb.get_file_breaks.descr: Return all breakpoints in filename, or an empty list if none are set.
bdb.Bdb.get_file_breaks.name: bdb.Bdb.get_file_breaks

bdb.Bdb.get_stack.descr: Get a list of records for a frame and all higher (calling) and lower frames, and the size of the higher part.
bdb.Bdb.get_stack.name: bdb.Bdb.get_stack

bdb.Bdb.reset.descr: Set the botframe, stopframe, returnframe and quitting attributes with values ready to start debugging.
bdb.Bdb.reset.name: bdb.Bdb.reset

bdb.Bdb.run.descr: Debug a statement executed via the exec() function. globals defaults to __main__.__dict__, locals defaults to globals.
bdb.Bdb.run.name: bdb.Bdb.run

bdb.Bdb.runcall.descr: Debug a single function call, and return its result.
bdb.Bdb.runcall.name: bdb.Bdb.runcall

bdb.Bdb.runctx.descr: For backwards compatibility. Calls the run() method.
bdb.Bdb.runctx.name: bdb.Bdb.runctx

bdb.Bdb.runeval.descr: Debug an expression executed via the eval() function. globals and locals have the same meaning as in run().
bdb.Bdb.runeval.name: bdb.Bdb.runeval

bdb.Bdb.set_break.descr: Set a new breakpoint. If the lineno line doesn’t exist for the filename passed as argument, return an error message. The filename should be in canonical form, as described in the canonic() method.
bdb.Bdb.set_break.name: bdb.Bdb.set_break

bdb.Bdb.set_continue.descr: Stop only at breakpoints or when finished. If there are no breakpoints, set the system trace function to None.
bdb.Bdb.set_continue.name: bdb.Bdb.set_continue

bdb.Bdb.set_next.descr: Stop on the next line in or below the given frame.
bdb.Bdb.set_next.name: bdb.Bdb.set_next

bdb.Bdb.set_quit.descr: Set the quitting attribute to True. This raises BdbQuit in the next call to one of the dispatch_*() methods.
bdb.Bdb.set_quit.name: bdb.Bdb.set_quit

bdb.Bdb.set_return.descr: Stop when returning from the given frame.
bdb.Bdb.set_return.name: bdb.Bdb.set_return

bdb.Bdb.set_step.descr: Stop after one line of code.
bdb.Bdb.set_step.name: bdb.Bdb.set_step

bdb.Bdb.set_trace.descr: Start debugging from frame. If frame is not specified, debugging starts from caller’s frame.
bdb.Bdb.set_trace.name: bdb.Bdb.set_trace

bdb.Bdb.set_until.descr: Stop when the line with the line no greater than the current one is reached or when returning from current frame
bdb.Bdb.set_until.name: bdb.Bdb.set_until

bdb.Bdb.stop_here.descr: This method checks if the frame is somewhere below botframe in the call stack. botframe is the frame in which debugging started.
bdb.Bdb.stop_here.name: bdb.Bdb.stop_here

bdb.Bdb.trace_dispatch.descr: This function is installed as the trace function of debugged frames. Its return value is the new trace function (in most cases, that is, itself).
bdb.Bdb.trace_dispatch.name: bdb.Bdb.trace_dispatch

bdb.Bdb.user_call.descr: This method is called from dispatch_call() when there is the possibility that a break might be necessary anywhere inside the called function.
bdb.Bdb.user_call.name: bdb.Bdb.user_call

bdb.Bdb.user_exception.descr: This method is called from dispatch_exception() when stop_here() yields True.
bdb.Bdb.user_exception.name: bdb.Bdb.user_exception

bdb.Bdb.user_line.descr: This method is called from dispatch_line() when either stop_here() or break_here() yields True.
bdb.Bdb.user_line.name: bdb.Bdb.user_line

bdb.Bdb.user_return.descr: This method is called from dispatch_return() when stop_here() yields True.
bdb.Bdb.user_return.name: bdb.Bdb.user_return

bdb.BdbQuit.descr: Exception raised by the Bdb class for quitting the debugger.
bdb.BdbQuit.name: bdb.BdbQuit

bdb.Breakpoint.descr: This class implements temporary breakpoints, ignore counts, disabling and (re-)enabling, and conditionals.
bdb.Breakpoint.name: bdb.Breakpoint
bdb.Breakpoint.syntax: class bdb.Breakpoint(self, file, line, temporary=0, cond=None, funcname=None)

bdb.Breakpoint.bpformat.descr: Return a string with all the information about the breakpoint, nicely formatted:
bdb.Breakpoint.bpformat.name: bdb.Breakpoint.bpformat

bdb.Breakpoint.bpprint.descr: Print the output of bpformat() to the file out, or if it is None, to standard output.
bdb.Breakpoint.bpprint.name: bdb.Breakpoint.bpprint

bdb.Breakpoint.deleteMe.descr: Delete the breakpoint from the list associated to a file/line. If it is the last breakpoint in that position, it also deletes the entry for the file/line.
bdb.Breakpoint.deleteMe.name: bdb.Breakpoint.deleteMe

bdb.checkfuncname.descr: Check whether we should break here, depending on the way the breakpoint b was set.
bdb.checkfuncname.name: bdb.checkfuncname

bdb.effective.descr: Determine if there is an effective (active) breakpoint at this line of code. Return a tuple of the breakpoint and a boolean that indicates if it is ok to delete a temporary breakpoint. Return (None, None) if there is no matching breakpoint.
bdb.effective.name: bdb.effective

bdb.set_trace.descr: Start debugging with a Bdb instance from caller’s frame.
bdb.set_trace.name: bdb.set_trace

bin.descr: Convert an integer number to a binary string. The result is a valid Python expression. If x is not a Python int object, it has to define an __index__() method that returns an integer.
bin.name: bin

binascii.Error.descr: Exception raised on errors. These are usually programming errors.
binascii.Error.name: binascii.Error

binascii.Incomplete.descr: Exception raised on incomplete data. These are usually not programming errors, but may be handled by reading a little more data and trying again.
binascii.Incomplete.name: binascii.Incomplete

binascii.a2b_base64.descr: Convert a block of base64 data back to binary and return the binary data. More than one line may be passed at a time.
binascii.a2b_base64.name: binascii.a2b_base64

binascii.a2b_hex.descr: Return the binary data represented by the hexadecimal string hexstr. This function is the inverse of b2a_hex(). hexstr must contain an even number of hexadecimal digits (which can be upper or lower case), otherwise a TypeError is raised.
binascii.a2b_hex.name: binascii.a2b_hex

binascii.a2b_hqx.descr: Convert binhex4 formatted ASCII data to binary, without doing RLE-decompression. The string should contain a complete number of binary bytes, or (in case of the last portion of the binhex4 data) have the remaining bits zero.
binascii.a2b_hqx.name: binascii.a2b_hqx

binascii.a2b_qp.descr: Convert a block of quoted-printable data back to binary and return the binary data. More than one line may be passed at a time. If the optional argument header is present and true, underscores will be decoded as spaces.
binascii.a2b_qp.name: binascii.a2b_qp

binascii.a2b_uu.descr: Convert a single line of uuencoded data back to binary and return the binary data. Lines normally contain 45 (binary) bytes, except for the last line. Line data may be followed by whitespace.
binascii.a2b_uu.name: binascii.a2b_uu

binascii.b2a_base64.descr: Convert binary data to a line of ASCII characters in base64 coding. The return value is the converted line, including a newline char. The length of data should be at most 57 to adhere to the base64 standard.
binascii.b2a_base64.name: binascii.b2a_base64

binascii.b2a_hex.descr: Return the hexadecimal representation of the binary data. Every byte of data is converted into the corresponding 2-digit hex representation. The returned bytes object is therefore twice as long as the length of data.
binascii.b2a_hex.name: binascii.b2a_hex

binascii.b2a_hqx.descr: Perform hexbin4 binary-to-ASCII translation and return the resulting string. The argument should already be RLE-coded, and have a length divisible by 3 (except possibly the last fragment).
binascii.b2a_hqx.name: binascii.b2a_hqx

binascii.b2a_qp.descr: Convert binary data to a line(s) of ASCII characters in quoted-printable encoding. The return value is the converted line(s). If the optional argument quotetabs is present and true, all tabs and spaces will be encoded. If the optional argument istext is present and true, newlines are not encoded but trailing whitespace will be encoded. If the optional argument header is present and true, spaces will be encoded as underscores per RFC1522. If the optional argument header is present and false, newline characters will be encoded as well; otherwise linefeed conversion might corrupt the binary data stream.
binascii.b2a_qp.name: binascii.b2a_qp

binascii.b2a_uu.descr: Convert binary data to a line of ASCII characters, the return value is the converted line, including a newline char. The length of data should be at most 45.
binascii.b2a_uu.name: binascii.b2a_uu

binascii.crc32.descr: Compute CRC-32, the 32-bit checksum of data, starting with an initial crc. This is consistent with the ZIP file checksum. Since the algorithm is designed for use as a checksum algorithm, it is not suitable for use as a general hash algorithm. Use as follows:
binascii.crc32.name: binascii.crc32

binascii.crc_hqx.descr: Compute the binhex4 crc value of data, starting with an initial crc and returning the result.
binascii.crc_hqx.name: binascii.crc_hqx

binascii.hexlify.descr: Return the hexadecimal representation of the binary data. Every byte of data is converted into the corresponding 2-digit hex representation. The returned bytes object is therefore twice as long as the length of data.
binascii.hexlify.name: binascii.hexlify

binascii.rlecode_hqx.descr: Perform binhex4 style RLE-compression on data and return the result.
binascii.rlecode_hqx.name: binascii.rlecode_hqx

binascii.rledecode_hqx.descr: Perform RLE-decompression on the data, as per the binhex4 standard. The algorithm uses 0x90 after a byte as a repeat indicator, followed by a count. A count of 0 specifies a byte value of 0x90. The routine returns the decompressed data, unless data input data ends in an orphaned repeat indicator, in which case the Incomplete exception is raised.
binascii.rledecode_hqx.name: binascii.rledecode_hqx

binascii.unhexlify.descr: Return the binary data represented by the hexadecimal string hexstr. This function is the inverse of b2a_hex(). hexstr must contain an even number of hexadecimal digits (which can be upper or lower case), otherwise a TypeError is raised.
binascii.unhexlify.name: binascii.unhexlify

binhex.Error.descr: Exception raised when something can’t be encoded using the binhex format (for example, a filename is too long to fit in the filename field), or when input is not properly encoded binhex data.
binhex.Error.name: binhex.Error

binhex.binhex.descr: Convert a binary file with filename input to binhex file output. The output parameter can either be a filename or a file-like object (any object supporting a write() and close() method).
binhex.binhex.name: binhex.binhex

binhex.hexbin.descr: Decode a binhex file input. input may be a filename or a file-like object supporting read() and close() methods. The resulting file is written to a file named output, unless the argument is None in which case the output filename is read from the binhex file.
binhex.hexbin.name: binhex.hexbin

bisect.bisect.descr: Similar to bisect_left(), but returns an insertion point which comes after (to the right of) any existing entries of x in a.
bisect.bisect.name: bisect.bisect

bisect.bisect_left.descr: Locate the insertion point for x in a to maintain sorted order. The parameters lo and hi may be used to specify a subset of the list which should be considered; by default the entire list is used. If x is already present in a, the insertion point will be before (to the left of) any existing entries. The return value is suitable for use as the first parameter to list.insert() assuming that a is already sorted.
bisect.bisect_left.name: bisect.bisect_left

bisect.bisect_right.descr: Similar to bisect_left(), but returns an insertion point which comes after (to the right of) any existing entries of x in a.
bisect.bisect_right.name: bisect.bisect_right

bisect.insort.descr: Similar to insort_left(), but inserting x in a after any existing entries of x.
bisect.insort.name: bisect.insort

bisect.insort_left.descr: Insert x in a in sorted order. This is equivalent to a.insert(bisect.bisect_left(a, x, lo, hi), x) assuming that a is already sorted. Keep in mind that the O(log n) search is dominated by the slow O(n) insertion step.
bisect.insort_left.name: bisect.insort_left

bisect.insort_right.descr: Similar to insort_left(), but inserting x in a after any existing entries of x.
bisect.insort_right.name: bisect.insort_right

bit_length.descr: Return the number of bits necessary to represent an integer in binary, excluding the sign and leading zeros:
bit_length.name: int.bit_length

bool.descr: Convert a value to a Boolean, using the standard truth testing procedure. If x is false or omitted, this returns False; otherwise it returns True. bool is also a class, which is a subclass of int (see Numeric Types — int, float, complex). Class bool cannot be subclassed further. Its only instances are False and True (see Boolean Values).
bool.name: bool

buffer_info.descr: Return a tuple (address, length) giving the current memory address and the length in elements of the buffer used to hold array’s contents. The size of the memory buffer in bytes can be computed as array.buffer_info()[1] * array.itemsize. This is occasionally useful when working with low-level (and inherently unsafe) I/O interfaces that require memory addresses, such as certain ioctl() operations. The returned numbers are valid as long as the array exists and no length-changing operations are applied to it.
buffer_info.name: array.array.buffer_info

bytearray.descr: Return a new array of bytes. The bytearray type is a mutable sequence of integers in the range 0 <= x < 256. It has most of the usual methods of mutable sequences, described in Mutable Sequence Types, as well as most methods that the bytes type has, see Bytes and Bytearray Operations.
bytearray.name: bytearray

bytearray.decode.descr: Return a string decoded from the given bytes. Default encoding is 'utf-8'. errors may be given to set a different error handling scheme. The default for errors is 'strict', meaning that encoding errors raise a UnicodeError. Other possible values are 'ignore', 'replace' and any other name registered via codecs.register_error(), see section Codec Base Classes. For a list of possible encodings, see section Standard Encodings.
bytearray.decode.name: bytearray.decode

bytearray.fromhex.descr: This bytes class method returns a bytes or bytearray object, decoding the given string object. The string must contain two hexadecimal digits per byte, spaces are ignored.
bytearray.fromhex.name: bytearray.fromhex

bytearray.translate.descr: Return a copy of the bytes or bytearray object where all bytes occurring in the optional argument delete are removed, and the remaining bytes have been mapped through the given translation table, which must be a bytes object of length 256.
bytearray.translate.name: bytearray.translate

bytes.descr: Return a new “bytes” object, which is an immutable sequence of integers in the range 0 <= x < 256. bytes is an immutable version of bytearray – it has the same non-mutating methods and the same indexing and slicing behavior.
bytes.name: bytes

bytes.decode.descr: Return a string decoded from the given bytes. Default encoding is 'utf-8'. errors may be given to set a different error handling scheme. The default for errors is 'strict', meaning that encoding errors raise a UnicodeError. Other possible values are 'ignore', 'replace' and any other name registered via codecs.register_error(), see section Codec Base Classes. For a list of possible encodings, see section Standard Encodings.
bytes.decode.name: bytes.decode

bytes.fromhex.descr: This bytes class method returns a bytes or bytearray object, decoding the given string object. The string must contain two hexadecimal digits per byte, spaces are ignored.
bytes.fromhex.name: bytes.fromhex

bytes.translate.descr: Return a copy of the bytes or bytearray object where all bytes occurring in the optional argument delete are removed, and the remaining bytes have been mapped through the given translation table, which must be a bytes object of length 256.
bytes.translate.name: bytes.translate

byteswap.descr: “Byteswap” all items of the array. This is only supported for values which are 1, 2, 4, or 8 bytes in size; for other types of values, RuntimeError is raised. It is useful when reading data from a file written on a machine with a different byte order.
byteswap.name: array.array.byteswap

bz2.BZ2Compressor.descr: Create a new compressor object. This object may be used to compress data incrementally. For one-shot compression, use the compress() function instead.
bz2.BZ2Compressor.name: bz2.BZ2Compressor

bz2.BZ2Compressor.compress.descr: Provide data to the compressor object. Returns a chunk of compressed data if possible, or an empty byte string otherwise.
bz2.BZ2Compressor.compress.name: bz2.BZ2Compressor.compress

bz2.BZ2Compressor.flush.descr: Finish the compression process. Returns the compressed data left in internal buffers.
bz2.BZ2Compressor.flush.name: bz2.BZ2Compressor.flush
