importlib.abc.PyPycLoader.get_filename.descr: A concrete implementation of ExecutionLoader.get_filename() that relies on PyLoader.source_path() and bytecode_path(). If source_path() returns a path, then that value is returned. Else if bytecode_path() returns a path, that path will be returned. If a path is not available from both methods, ImportError is raised.
importlib.abc.PyPycLoader.get_filename.name: importlib.abc.PyPycLoader.get_filename

importlib.abc.PyPycLoader.source_mtime.descr: An abstract method which returns the modification time for the source code of the specified module. The modification time should be an integer. If there is no source code, return None. If the module cannot be found then ImportError is raised.
importlib.abc.PyPycLoader.source_mtime.name: importlib.abc.PyPycLoader.source_mtime

importlib.abc.PyPycLoader.write_bytecode.descr: An abstract method which has the loader write bytecode for future use. If the bytecode is written, return True. Return False if the bytecode could not be written. This method should not be called if sys.dont_write_bytecode is true. The bytecode argument should be a bytes string or bytes array.
importlib.abc.PyPycLoader.write_bytecode.name: importlib.abc.PyPycLoader.write_bytecode

importlib.abc.ResourceLoader.descr: An abstract base class for a loader which implements the optional PEP 302 protocol for loading arbitrary resources from the storage back-end.
importlib.abc.ResourceLoader.name: importlib.abc.ResourceLoader

importlib.abc.ResourceLoader.get_data.descr: An abstract method to return the bytes for the data located at path. Loaders that have a file-like storage back-end that allows storing arbitrary data can implement this abstract method to give direct access to the data stored. IOError is to be raised if the path cannot be found. The path is expected to be constructed using a module’s __file__ attribute or an item from a package’s __path__.
importlib.abc.ResourceLoader.get_data.name: importlib.abc.ResourceLoader.get_data

importlib.abc.SourceLoader.descr: An abstract base class for implementing source (and optionally bytecode) file loading. The class inherits from both ResourceLoader and ExecutionLoader, requiring the implementation of:
importlib.abc.SourceLoader.name: importlib.abc.SourceLoader

importlib.abc.SourceLoader.is_package.descr: Concrete implementation of InspectLoader.is_package(). A module is determined to be a package if its file path (as provided by ExecutionLoader.get_filename()) is a file named __init__ when the file extension is removed and the module name itself does not end in __init__.
importlib.abc.SourceLoader.is_package.name: importlib.abc.SourceLoader.is_package

importlib.abc.SourceLoader.path_mtime.descr: Optional abstract method which returns the modification time for the specified path.
importlib.abc.SourceLoader.path_mtime.name: importlib.abc.SourceLoader.path_mtime

importlib.abc.SourceLoader.path_stats.descr: Optional abstract method which returns a dict containing metadata about the specifed path. Supported dictionary keys are:
importlib.abc.SourceLoader.path_stats.name: importlib.abc.SourceLoader.path_stats

importlib.abc.SourceLoader.set_data.descr: Optional abstract method which writes the specified bytes to a file path. Any intermediate directories which do not exist are to be created automatically.
importlib.abc.SourceLoader.set_data.name: importlib.abc.SourceLoader.set_data

importlib.find_loader.descr: Find the loader for a module, optionally within the specified path. If the module is in sys.modules, then sys.modules[name].__loader__ is returned (unless the loader would be None, in which case ValueError is raised). Otherwise a search using sys.meta_path is done. None is returned if no loader is found.
importlib.find_loader.name: importlib.find_loader

importlib.import_module.descr: Import a module. The name argument specifies what module to import in absolute or relative terms (e.g. either pkg.mod or ..mod). If the name is specified in relative terms, then the package argument must be set to the name of the package which is to act as the anchor for resolving the package name (e.g. import_module('..mod', 'pkg.subpkg') will import pkg.mod).
importlib.import_module.name: importlib.import_module

importlib.invalidate_caches.descr: Invalidate the internal caches of finders stored at sys.meta_path. If a finder implements invalidate_caches() then it will be called to perform the invalidation. This function should be called if any modules are created/installed while your program is running to guarantee all finders will notice the new module’s existence.
importlib.invalidate_caches.name: importlib.invalidate_caches

importlib.machinery.BYTECODE_SUFFIXES.descr: A list of strings representing the recognized file suffixes for bytecode modules. Set to either DEBUG_BYTECODE_SUFFIXES or OPTIMIZED_BYTECODE_SUFFIXES based on whether __debug__ is true.
importlib.machinery.BYTECODE_SUFFIXES.name: importlib.machinery.BYTECODE_SUFFIXES

importlib.machinery.BuiltinImporter.descr: An importer for built-in modules. All known built-in modules are listed in sys.builtin_module_names. This class implements the importlib.abc.MetaPathFinder and importlib.abc.InspectLoader ABCs.
importlib.machinery.BuiltinImporter.name: importlib.machinery.BuiltinImporter

importlib.machinery.DEBUG_BYTECODE_SUFFI.descr: A list of strings representing the file suffixes for non-optimized bytecode modules.
importlib.machinery.DEBUG_BYTECODE_SUFFI.name: importlib.machinery.DEBUG_BYTECODE_SUFFIXES

importlib.machinery.EXTENSION_SUFFIXES.descr: A list of strings representing the recognized file suffixes for extension modules.
importlib.machinery.EXTENSION_SUFFIXES.name: importlib.machinery.EXTENSION_SUFFIXES

importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader.descr: A concrete implementation of importlib.abc.InspectLoader for extension modules.
importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader.name: importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader

importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader..descr: Returns None as extension modules lack a code object.
importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader..name: importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader.get_code

importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader..descr: Returns None as extension modules do not have source code.
importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader..name: importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader.get_source

importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader..descr: Returns True if the file path points to a package’s __init__ module based on EXTENSION_SUFFIXES.
importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader..name: importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader.is_package

importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader..descr: Loads the extension module if and only if fullname is the same as name or is None.
importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader..name: importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader.load_module

importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader..descr: Name of the module the loader supports.
importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader..name: importlib.machinery.ExtensionFileLoader.name

importlib.machinery.FileFinder.descr: A concrete implementation of importlib.abc.PathEntryFinder which caches results from the file system.
importlib.machinery.FileFinder.name: importlib.machinery.FileFinder

importlib.machinery.FileFinder.find_load.descr: Attempt to find the loader to handle fullname within path.
importlib.machinery.FileFinder.find_load.name: importlib.machinery.FileFinder.find_loader

importlib.machinery.FileFinder.path.descr: The path the finder will search in.
importlib.machinery.FileFinder.path.name: importlib.machinery.FileFinder.path

importlib.machinery.FileFinder.path_hook.descr: A class method which returns a closure for use on sys.path_hooks. An instance of FileFinder is returned by the closure using the path argument given to the closure directly and loader_details indirectly.
importlib.machinery.FileFinder.path_hook.name: importlib.machinery.FileFinder.path_hook

importlib.machinery.FrozenImporter.descr: An importer for frozen modules. This class implements the importlib.abc.MetaPathFinder and importlib.abc.InspectLoader ABCs.
importlib.machinery.FrozenImporter.name: importlib.machinery.FrozenImporter

importlib.machinery.OPTIMIZED_BYTECODE_S.descr: A list of strings representing the file suffixes for optimized bytecode modules.
importlib.machinery.OPTIMIZED_BYTECODE_S.name: importlib.machinery.OPTIMIZED_BYTECODE_SUFFIXES

importlib.machinery.PathFinder.descr: A Finder for sys.path and package __path__ attributes. This class implements the importlib.abc.MetaPathFinder ABC.
importlib.machinery.PathFinder.name: importlib.machinery.PathFinder

importlib.machinery.PathFinder.find_modu.descr: Class method that attempts to find a loader for the module specified by fullname on sys.path or, if defined, on path. For each path entry that is searched, sys.path_importer_cache is checked. If a non-false object is found then it is used as the path entry finder to look for the module being searched for. If no entry is found in sys.path_importer_cache, then sys.path_hooks is searched for a finder for the path entry and, if found, is stored in sys.path_importer_cache along with being queried about the module. If no finder is ever found then None is both stored in the cache and returned.
importlib.machinery.PathFinder.find_modu.name: importlib.machinery.PathFinder.find_module

importlib.machinery.PathFinder.invalidat.descr: Calls importlib.abc.PathEntryFinder.invalidate_caches() on all finders stored in sys.path_importer_cache.
importlib.machinery.PathFinder.invalidat.name: importlib.machinery.PathFinder.invalidate_caches

importlib.machinery.SOURCE_SUFFIXES.descr: A list of strings representing the recognized file suffixes for source modules.
importlib.machinery.SOURCE_SUFFIXES.name: importlib.machinery.SOURCE_SUFFIXES

importlib.machinery.SourceFileLoader.descr: A concrete implementation of importlib.abc.SourceLoader by subclassing importlib.abc.FileLoader and providing some concrete implementations of other methods.
importlib.machinery.SourceFileLoader.name: importlib.machinery.SourceFileLoader

importlib.machinery.SourceFileLoader.is_.descr: Return true if path appears to be for a package.
importlib.machinery.SourceFileLoader.is_.name: importlib.machinery.SourceFileLoader.is_package

importlib.machinery.SourceFileLoader.nam.descr: The name of the module that this loader will handle.
importlib.machinery.SourceFileLoader.nam.name: importlib.machinery.SourceFileLoader.name

importlib.machinery.SourceFileLoader.pat.descr: The path to the source file.
importlib.machinery.SourceFileLoader.pat.name: importlib.machinery.SourceFileLoader.path

importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader.descr: A concrete implementation of importlib.abc.FileLoader which can import bytecode files (i.e. no source code files exist).
importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader.name: importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader

importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader.descr: Returns the code object for name created from path.
importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader.name: importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader.get_code

importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader.descr: Returns None as bytecode files have no source when this loader is used.
importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader.name: importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader.get_source

importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader.descr: Determines if the module is a package based on path.
importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader.name: importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader.is_package

importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader.descr: The name of the module the loader will handle.
importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader.name: importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader.name

importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader.descr: The path to the bytecode file.
importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader.name: importlib.machinery.SourcelessFileLoader.path

importlib.machinery.WindowsRegistryFinde.descr: Finder for modules declared in the Windows registry. This class implements the importlib.abc.Finder ABC.
importlib.machinery.WindowsRegistryFinde.name: importlib.machinery.WindowsRegistryFinder

importlib.machinery.all_suffixes.descr: Returns a combined list of strings representing all file suffixes for modules recognized by the standard import machinery. This is a helper for code which simply needs to know if a filesystem path potentially refers to a module without needing any details on the kind of module (for example, inspect.getmodulename())
importlib.machinery.all_suffixes.name: importlib.machinery.all_suffixes

importlib.util.module_for_loader.descr: A decorator for a loader method, to handle selecting the proper module object to load with. The decorated method is expected to have a call signature taking two positional arguments (e.g. load_module(self, module)) for which the second argument will be the module object to be used by the loader. Note that the decorator will not work on static methods because of the assumption of two arguments.
importlib.util.module_for_loader.name: importlib.util.module_for_loader

importlib.util.resolve_name.descr: Resolve a relative module name to an absolute one.
importlib.util.resolve_name.name: importlib.util.resolve_name

importlib.util.set_package.descr: A decorator for a loader to set the __package__ attribute on the module returned by the loader. If __package__ is set and has a value other than None it will not be changed. Note that the module returned by the loader is what has the attribute set on and not the module found in sys.modules.
importlib.util.set_package.name: importlib.util.set_package

index.descr: Like find(), but raise ValueError when the substring is not found.
index.name: str.index

input.descr: If the prompt argument is present, it is written to standard output without a trailing newline. The function then reads a line from input, converts it to a string (stripping a trailing newline), and returns that. When EOF is read, EOFError is raised. Example:
input.name: input

insert.descr: Insert a new item with value x in the array before position i. Negative values are treated as being relative to the end of the array.
insert.name: array.array.insert

inspect.BoundArguments.descr: Result of a Signature.bind() or Signature.bind_partial() call. Holds the mapping of arguments to the function’s parameters.
inspect.BoundArguments.name: inspect.BoundArguments

inspect.BoundArguments.args.descr: A tuple of positional arguments values. Dynamically computed from the arguments attribute.
inspect.BoundArguments.args.name: inspect.BoundArguments.args

inspect.BoundArguments.arguments.descr: An ordered, mutable mapping (collections.OrderedDict) of parameters’ names to arguments’ values. Contains only explicitly bound arguments. Changes in arguments will reflect in args and kwargs.
inspect.BoundArguments.arguments.name: inspect.BoundArguments.arguments

inspect.BoundArguments.kwargs.descr: A dict of keyword arguments values. Dynamically computed from the arguments attribute.
inspect.BoundArguments.kwargs.name: inspect.BoundArguments.kwargs

inspect.Parameter.descr: Parameter objects are immutable. Instead of modifying a Parameter object, you can use Parameter.replace() to create a modified copy.
inspect.Parameter.name: inspect.Parameter

inspect.Parameter.annotation.descr: The annotation for the parameter. If the parameter has no annotation, this attribute is set to Parameter.empty.
inspect.Parameter.annotation.name: inspect.Parameter.annotation

inspect.Parameter.default.descr: The default value for the parameter. If the parameter has no default value, this attribute is set to Parameter.empty.
inspect.Parameter.default.name: inspect.Parameter.default

inspect.Parameter.empty.descr: A special class-level marker to specify absence of default values and annotations.
inspect.Parameter.empty.name: inspect.Parameter.empty

inspect.Parameter.kind.descr: Describes how argument values are bound to the parameter. Possible values (accessible via Parameter, like Parameter.KEYWORD_ONLY):
inspect.Parameter.kind.name: inspect.Parameter.kind

inspect.Parameter.name.descr: The name of the parameter as a string. Must be a valid python identifier name (with the exception of POSITIONAL_ONLY parameters, which can have it set to None).
inspect.Parameter.name.name: inspect.Parameter.name

inspect.Parameter.replace.descr: Create a new Parameter instance based on the instance replaced was invoked on. To override a Parameter attribute, pass the corresponding argument. To remove a default value or/and an annotation from a Parameter, pass Parameter.empty.
inspect.Parameter.replace.name: inspect.Parameter.replace

inspect.Signature.descr: A Signature object represents the call signature of a function and its return annotation. For each parameter accepted by the function it stores a Parameter object in its parameters collection.
inspect.Signature.name: inspect.Signature

inspect.Signature.bind.descr: Create a mapping from positional and keyword arguments to parameters. Returns BoundArguments if *args and **kwargs match the signature, or raises a TypeError.
inspect.Signature.bind.name: inspect.Signature.bind

inspect.Signature.bind_partial.descr: Works the same way as Signature.bind(), but allows the omission of some required arguments (mimics functools.partial() behavior.) Returns BoundArguments, or raises a TypeError if the passed arguments do not match the signature.
inspect.Signature.bind_partial.name: inspect.Signature.bind_partial

inspect.Signature.empty.descr: A special class-level marker to specify absence of a return annotation.
inspect.Signature.empty.name: inspect.Signature.empty

inspect.Signature.parameters.descr: An ordered mapping of parameters’ names to the corresponding Parameter objects.
inspect.Signature.parameters.name: inspect.Signature.parameters

inspect.Signature.replace.descr: Create a new Signature instance based on the instance replace was invoked on. It is possible to pass different parameters and/or return_annotation to override the corresponding properties of the base signature. To remove return_annotation from the copied Signature, pass in Signature.empty.
inspect.Signature.replace.name: inspect.Signature.replace

inspect.Signature.return_annotation.descr: The “return” annotation for the callable. If the callable has no “return” annotation, this attribute is set to Signature.empty.
inspect.Signature.return_annotation.name: inspect.Signature.return_annotation

inspect.cleandoc.descr: Clean up indentation from docstrings that are indented to line up with blocks of code. Any whitespace that can be uniformly removed from the second line onwards is removed. Also, all tabs are expanded to spaces.
inspect.cleandoc.name: inspect.cleandoc

inspect.currentframe.descr: Return the frame object for the caller’s stack frame.
inspect.currentframe.name: inspect.currentframe

inspect.formatargspec.descr: Format a pretty argument spec from the values returned by getargspec() or getfullargspec().
inspect.formatargspec.name: inspect.formatargspec
inspect.formatargspec.syntax: inspect.formatargspec(args[, varargs, varkw, defaults, kwonlyargs, kwonlydefaults, annotations[, formatarg, formatvarargs, formatvarkw, formatvalue, formatreturns, formatannotations]])

inspect.formatargvalues.descr: Format a pretty argument spec from the four values returned by getargvalues(). The format* arguments are the corresponding optional formatting functions that are called to turn names and values into strings.
inspect.formatargvalues.name: inspect.formatargvalues
inspect.formatargvalues.syntax: inspect.formatargvalues(args[, varargs, varkw, locals, formatarg, formatvarargs, formatvarkw, formatvalue])

inspect.getargspec.descr: Get the names and default values of a Python function’s arguments. A named tuple ArgSpec(args, varargs, keywords, defaults) is returned. args is a list of the argument names. varargs and keywords are the names of the * and ** arguments or None. defaults is a tuple of default argument values or None if there are no default arguments; if this tuple has n elements, they correspond to the last n elements listed in args.
inspect.getargspec.name: inspect.getargspec

inspect.getargvalues.descr: Get information about arguments passed into a particular frame. A named tuple ArgInfo(args, varargs, keywords, locals) is returned. args is a list of the argument names. varargs and keywords are the names of the * and ** arguments or None. locals is the locals dictionary of the given frame.
inspect.getargvalues.name: inspect.getargvalues

inspect.getattr_static.descr: Retrieve attributes without triggering dynamic lookup via the descriptor protocol, __getattr__() or __getattribute__().
inspect.getattr_static.name: inspect.getattr_static

inspect.getcallargs.descr: Bind the args and kwds to the argument names of the Python function or method func, as if it was called with them. For bound methods, bind also the first argument (typically named self) to the associated instance. A dict is returned, mapping the argument names (including the names of the * and ** arguments, if any) to their values from args and kwds. In case of invoking func incorrectly, i.e. whenever func(*args, **kwds) would raise an exception because of incompatible signature, an exception of the same type and the same or similar message is raised. For example:
inspect.getcallargs.name: inspect.getcallargs

inspect.getclasstree.descr: Arrange the given list of classes into a hierarchy of nested lists. Where a nested list appears, it contains classes derived from the class whose entry immediately precedes the list. Each entry is a 2-tuple containing a class and a tuple of its base classes. If the unique argument is true, exactly one entry appears in the returned structure for each class in the given list. Otherwise, classes using multiple inheritance and their descendants will appear multiple times.
inspect.getclasstree.name: inspect.getclasstree

inspect.getclosurevars.descr: Get the mapping of external name references in a Python function or method func to their current values. A named tuple ClosureVars(nonlocals, globals, builtins, unbound) is returned. nonlocals maps referenced names to lexical closure variables, globals to the function’s module globals and builtins to the builtins visible from the function body. unbound is the set of names referenced in the function that could not be resolved at all given the current module globals and builtins.
inspect.getclosurevars.name: inspect.getclosurevars

inspect.getcomments.descr: Return in a single string any lines of comments immediately preceding the object’s source code (for a class, function, or method), or at the top of the Python source file (if the object is a module).
inspect.getcomments.name: inspect.getcomments

inspect.getdoc.descr: Get the documentation string for an object, cleaned up with cleandoc().
inspect.getdoc.name: inspect.getdoc

inspect.getfile.descr: Return the name of the (text or binary) file in which an object was defined. This will fail with a TypeError if the object is a built-in module, class, or function.
inspect.getfile.name: inspect.getfile

inspect.getframeinfo.descr: Get information about a frame or traceback object. A named tuple Traceback(filename, lineno, function, code_context, index) is returned.
inspect.getframeinfo.name: inspect.getframeinfo

inspect.getfullargspec.descr: Get the names and default values of a Python function’s arguments. A named tuple is returned:
inspect.getfullargspec.name: inspect.getfullargspec

inspect.getgeneratorlocals.descr: Get the mapping of live local variables in generator to their current values. A dictionary is returned that maps from variable names to values. This is the equivalent of calling locals() in the body of the generator, and all the same caveats apply.
inspect.getgeneratorlocals.name: inspect.getgeneratorlocals

inspect.getgeneratorstate.descr: Get current state of a generator-iterator.
inspect.getgeneratorstate.name: inspect.getgeneratorstate

inspect.getinnerframes.descr: Get a list of frame records for a traceback’s frame and all inner frames. These frames represent calls made as a consequence of frame. The first entry in the list represents traceback; the last entry represents where the exception was raised.
inspect.getinnerframes.name: inspect.getinnerframes

inspect.getmembers.descr: Return all the members of an object in a list of (name, value) pairs sorted by name. If the optional predicate argument is supplied, only members for which the predicate returns a true value are included.
inspect.getmembers.name: inspect.getmembers

inspect.getmodule.descr: Try to guess which module an object was defined in.
inspect.getmodule.name: inspect.getmodule

inspect.getmoduleinfo.descr: Returns a named tuple ModuleInfo(name, suffix, mode, module_type) of values that describe how Python will interpret the file identified by path if it is a module, or None if it would not be identified as a module. In that tuple, name is the name of the module without the name of any enclosing package, suffix is the trailing part of the file name (which may not be a dot-delimited extension), mode is the open() mode that would be used ('r' or 'rb'), and module_type is an integer giving the type of the module. module_type will have a value which can be compared to the constants defined in the imp module; see the documentation for that module for more information on module types.
inspect.getmoduleinfo.name: inspect.getmoduleinfo

inspect.getmodulename.descr: Return the name of the module named by the file path, without including the names of enclosing packages. The file extension is checked against all of the entries in importlib.machinery.all_suffixes(). If it matches, the final path component is returned with the extension removed. Otherwise, None is returned.
inspect.getmodulename.name: inspect.getmodulename

inspect.getmro.descr: Return a tuple of class cls’s base classes, including cls, in method resolution order. No class appears more than once in this tuple. Note that the method resolution order depends on cls’s type. Unless a very peculiar user-defined metatype is in use, cls will be the first element of the tuple.
inspect.getmro.name: inspect.getmro

inspect.getouterframes.descr: Get a list of frame records for a frame and all outer frames. These frames represent the calls that lead to the creation of frame. The first entry in the returned list represents frame; the last entry represents the outermost call on frame‘s stack.
inspect.getouterframes.name: inspect.getouterframes

inspect.getsource.descr: Return the text of the source code for an object. The argument may be a module, class, method, function, traceback, frame, or code object. The source code is returned as a single string. An OSError is raised if the source code cannot be retrieved.
inspect.getsource.name: inspect.getsource

inspect.getsourcefile.descr: Return the name of the Python source file in which an object was defined. This will fail with a TypeError if the object is a built-in module, class, or function.
inspect.getsourcefile.name: inspect.getsourcefile

inspect.getsourcelines.descr: Return a list of source lines and starting line number for an object. The argument may be a module, class, method, function, traceback, frame, or code object. The source code is returned as a list of the lines corresponding to the object and the line number indicates where in the original source file the first line of code was found. An OSError is raised if the source code cannot be retrieved.
inspect.getsourcelines.name: inspect.getsourcelines

inspect.isabstract.descr: Return true if the object is an abstract base class.
inspect.isabstract.name: inspect.isabstract

inspect.isbuiltin.descr: Return true if the object is a built-in function or a bound built-in method.
inspect.isbuiltin.name: inspect.isbuiltin

inspect.isclass.descr: Return true if the object is a class, whether built-in or created in Python code.
inspect.isclass.name: inspect.isclass

inspect.iscode.descr: Return true if the object is a code.
inspect.iscode.name: inspect.iscode

inspect.isdatadescriptor.descr: Return true if the object is a data descriptor.
inspect.isdatadescriptor.name: inspect.isdatadescriptor

inspect.isframe.descr: Return true if the object is a frame.
inspect.isframe.name: inspect.isframe

inspect.isfunction.descr: Return true if the object is a Python function, which includes functions created by a lambda expression.
inspect.isfunction.name: inspect.isfunction

inspect.isgenerator.descr: Return true if the object is a generator.
inspect.isgenerator.name: inspect.isgenerator

inspect.isgeneratorfunction.descr: Return true if the object is a Python generator function.
inspect.isgeneratorfunction.name: inspect.isgeneratorfunction

inspect.isgetsetdescriptor.descr: Return true if the object is a getset descriptor.
inspect.isgetsetdescriptor.name: inspect.isgetsetdescriptor

inspect.ismemberdescriptor.descr: Return true if the object is a member descriptor.
inspect.ismemberdescriptor.name: inspect.ismemberdescriptor

inspect.ismethod.descr: Return true if the object is a bound method written in Python.
inspect.ismethod.name: inspect.ismethod

inspect.ismethoddescriptor.descr: Return true if the object is a method descriptor, but not if ismethod(), isclass(), isfunction() or isbuiltin() are true.
inspect.ismethoddescriptor.name: inspect.ismethoddescriptor

inspect.ismodule.descr: Return true if the object is a module.
inspect.ismodule.name: inspect.ismodule

inspect.isroutine.descr: Return true if the object is a user-defined or built-in function or method.
inspect.isroutine.name: inspect.isroutine

inspect.istraceback.descr: Return true if the object is a traceback.
inspect.istraceback.name: inspect.istraceback

inspect.signature.descr: Return a Signature object for the given callable:
inspect.signature.name: inspect.signature

inspect.stack.descr: Return a list of frame records for the caller’s stack. The first entry in the returned list represents the caller; the last entry represents the outermost call on the stack.
inspect.stack.name: inspect.stack

inspect.trace.descr: Return a list of frame records for the stack between the current frame and the frame in which an exception currently being handled was raised in. The first entry in the list represents the caller; the last entry represents where the exception was raised.
inspect.trace.name: inspect.trace

instance.__class__.descr: The class to which a class instance belongs.
instance.__class__.name: instance.__class__

int.descr: Convert a number or string x to an integer, or return 0 if no arguments are given. If x is a number, return x.__int__(). For floating point numbers, this truncates towards zero.
int.name: int

int.bit_length.descr: Return the number of bits necessary to represent an integer in binary, excluding the sign and leading zeros:
int.bit_length.name: int.bit_length

int.from_bytes.descr: Return the integer represented by the given array of bytes.
int.from_bytes.name: int.from_bytes

int.to_bytes.descr: Return an array of bytes representing an integer.
int.to_bytes.name: int.to_bytes

io.BlockingIOError.descr: This is a compatibility alias for the builtin BlockingIOError exception.
io.BlockingIOError.name: io.BlockingIOError

io.BufferedIOBase.descr: Base class for binary streams that support some kind of buffering. It inherits IOBase. There is no public constructor.
io.BufferedIOBase.name: io.BufferedIOBase

io.BufferedIOBase.detach.descr: Separate the underlying raw stream from the buffer and return it.
io.BufferedIOBase.detach.name: io.BufferedIOBase.detach

io.BufferedIOBase.raw.descr: The underlying raw stream (a RawIOBase instance) that BufferedIOBase deals with. This is not part of the BufferedIOBase API and may not exist on some implementations.
io.BufferedIOBase.raw.name: io.BufferedIOBase.raw

io.BufferedIOBase.read.descr: Read and return up to n bytes, with at most one call to the underlying raw stream’s read() method. This can be useful if you are implementing your own buffering on top of a BufferedIOBase object.
io.BufferedIOBase.read.name: io.BufferedIOBase.read

io.BufferedIOBase.read1.descr: Read and return up to n bytes, with at most one call to the underlying raw stream’s read() method. This can be useful if you are implementing your own buffering on top of a BufferedIOBase object.
io.BufferedIOBase.read1.name: io.BufferedIOBase.read1

io.BufferedIOBase.readinto.descr: Read up to len(b) bytes into bytearray b and return the number of bytes read.
io.BufferedIOBase.readinto.name: io.BufferedIOBase.readinto

io.BufferedIOBase.write.descr: Write the given bytes or bytearray object, b and return the number of bytes written (never less than len(b), since if the write fails an OSError will be raised). Depending on the actual implementation, these bytes may be readily written to the underlying stream, or held in a buffer for performance and latency reasons.
io.BufferedIOBase.write.name: io.BufferedIOBase.write

io.BufferedRWPair.descr: A buffered I/O object combining two unidirectional RawIOBase objects – one readable, the other writeable – into a single bidirectional endpoint. It inherits BufferedIOBase.
io.BufferedRWPair.name: io.BufferedRWPair

io.BufferedRandom.descr: A buffered interface to random access streams. It inherits BufferedReader and BufferedWriter, and further supports seek() and tell() functionality.
io.BufferedRandom.name: io.BufferedRandom

io.BufferedReader.descr: A buffer providing higher-level access to a readable, sequential RawIOBase object. It inherits BufferedIOBase. When reading data from this object, a larger amount of data may be requested from the underlying raw stream, and kept in an internal buffer. The buffered data can then be returned directly on subsequent reads.
io.BufferedReader.name: io.BufferedReader

io.BufferedReader.peek.descr: Return bytes from the stream without advancing the position. At most one single read on the raw stream is done to satisfy the call. The number of bytes returned may be less or more than requested.
io.BufferedReader.peek.name: io.BufferedReader.peek

io.BufferedReader.read.descr: Read and return up to n bytes with only one call on the raw stream. If at least one byte is buffered, only buffered bytes are returned. Otherwise, one raw stream read call is made.
io.BufferedReader.read.name: io.BufferedReader.read

io.BufferedReader.read1.descr: Read and return up to n bytes with only one call on the raw stream. If at least one byte is buffered, only buffered bytes are returned. Otherwise, one raw stream read call is made.
io.BufferedReader.read1.name: io.BufferedReader.read1

io.BufferedWriter.descr: A buffer providing higher-level access to a writeable, sequential RawIOBase object. It inherits BufferedIOBase. When writing to this object, data is normally placed into an internal buffer. The buffer will be written out to the underlying RawIOBase object under various conditions, including:
io.BufferedWriter.name: io.BufferedWriter

io.BufferedWriter.flush.descr: Force bytes held in the buffer into the raw stream. A BlockingIOError should be raised if the raw stream blocks.
io.BufferedWriter.flush.name: io.BufferedWriter.flush

io.BufferedWriter.write.descr: Write the bytes or bytearray object, b and return the number of bytes written. When in non-blocking mode, a BlockingIOError is raised if the buffer needs to be written out but the raw stream blocks.
io.BufferedWriter.write.name: io.BufferedWriter.write

io.BytesIO.descr: A stream implementation using an in-memory bytes buffer. It inherits BufferedIOBase.
io.BytesIO.name: io.BytesIO

io.BytesIO.getbuffer.descr: Return a readable and writable view over the contents of the buffer without copying them. Also, mutating the view will transparently update the contents of the buffer:
io.BytesIO.getbuffer.name: io.BytesIO.getbuffer

io.BytesIO.getvalue.descr: Return bytes containing the entire contents of the buffer.
io.BytesIO.getvalue.name: io.BytesIO.getvalue

io.BytesIO.read1.descr: In BytesIO, this is the same as read().
io.BytesIO.read1.name: io.BytesIO.read1

io.FileIO.descr: FileIO represents an OS-level file containing bytes data. It implements the RawIOBase interface (and therefore the IOBase interface, too).
io.FileIO.name: io.FileIO

io.FileIO.mode.descr: The mode as given in the constructor.
io.FileIO.mode.name: io.FileIO.mode

io.FileIO.name.descr: The file name. This is the file descriptor of the file when no name is given in the constructor.
io.FileIO.name.name: io.FileIO.name

io.IOBase.descr: The abstract base class for all I/O classes, acting on streams of bytes. There is no public constructor.
io.IOBase.name: io.IOBase

io.IOBase.close.descr: Flush and close this stream. This method has no effect if the file is already closed. Once the file is closed, any operation on the file (e.g. reading or writing) will raise a ValueError.
io.IOBase.close.name: io.IOBase.close

io.IOBase.closed.descr: True if the stream is closed.
io.IOBase.closed.name: io.IOBase.closed

io.IOBase.fileno.descr: Return the underlying file descriptor (an integer) of the stream if it exists. An OSError is raised if the IO object does not use a file descriptor.
io.IOBase.fileno.name: io.IOBase.fileno

io.IOBase.flush.descr: Flush the write buffers of the stream if applicable. This does nothing for read-only and non-blocking streams.
io.IOBase.flush.name: io.IOBase.flush

io.IOBase.isatty.descr: Return True if the stream is interactive (i.e., connected to a terminal/tty device).
io.IOBase.isatty.name: io.IOBase.isatty

io.IOBase.readable.descr: Return True if the stream can be read from. If False, read() will raise OSError.
io.IOBase.readable.name: io.IOBase.readable

io.IOBase.readline.descr: Read and return one line from the stream. If limit is specified, at most limit bytes will be read.
io.IOBase.readline.name: io.IOBase.readline

io.IOBase.readlines.descr: Read and return a list of lines from the stream. hint can be specified to control the number of lines read: no more lines will be read if the total size (in bytes/characters) of all lines so far exceeds hint.
io.IOBase.readlines.name: io.IOBase.readlines

io.IOBase.seek.descr: Change the stream position to the given byte offset. offset is interpreted relative to the position indicated by whence. Values for whence are:
io.IOBase.seek.name: io.IOBase.seek

io.IOBase.seekable.descr: Return True if the stream supports random access. If False, seek(), tell() and truncate() will raise OSError.
io.IOBase.seekable.name: io.IOBase.seekable

io.IOBase.truncate.descr: Resize the stream to the given size in bytes (or the current position if size is not specified). The current stream position isn’t changed. This resizing can extend or reduce the current file size. In case of extension, the contents of the new file area depend on the platform (on most systems, additional bytes are zero-filled, on Windows they’re undetermined). The new file size is returned.
io.IOBase.truncate.name: io.IOBase.truncate

io.IOBase.writable.descr: Return True if the stream supports writing. If False, write() and truncate() will raise OSError.
io.IOBase.writable.name: io.IOBase.writable

io.IOBase.writelines.descr: Write a list of lines to the stream. Line separators are not added, so it is usual for each of the lines provided to have a line separator at the end.
io.IOBase.writelines.name: io.IOBase.writelines

io.IncrementalNewlineDecoder.descr: A helper codec that decodes newlines for universal newlines mode. It inherits codecs.IncrementalDecoder.
io.IncrementalNewlineDecoder.name: io.IncrementalNewlineDecoder

io.RawIOBase.descr: Base class for raw binary I/O. It inherits IOBase. There is no public constructor.
io.RawIOBase.name: io.RawIOBase

io.RawIOBase.read.descr: Read up to n bytes from the object and return them. As a convenience, if n is unspecified or -1, readall() is called. Otherwise, only one system call is ever made. Fewer than n bytes may be returned if the operating system call returns fewer than n bytes.
io.RawIOBase.read.name: io.RawIOBase.read

io.RawIOBase.readall.descr: Read and return all the bytes from the stream until EOF, using multiple calls to the stream if necessary.
io.RawIOBase.readall.name: io.RawIOBase.readall

io.RawIOBase.readinto.descr: Read up to len(b) bytes into bytearray b and return the number of bytes read. If the object is in non-blocking mode and no bytes are available, None is returned.
io.RawIOBase.readinto.name: io.RawIOBase.readinto

io.RawIOBase.write.descr: Write the given bytes or bytearray object, b, to the underlying raw stream and return the number of bytes written. This can be less than len(b), depending on specifics of the underlying raw stream, and especially if it is in non-blocking mode. None is returned if the raw stream is set not to block and no single byte could be readily written to it.
io.RawIOBase.write.name: io.RawIOBase.write

io.StringIO.descr: An in-memory stream for text I/O.
io.StringIO.name: io.StringIO

io.StringIO.getvalue.descr: Return a str containing the entire contents of the buffer at any time before the StringIO object’s close() method is called.
io.StringIO.getvalue.name: io.StringIO.getvalue

io.TextIOBase.descr: Base class for text streams. This class provides a character and line based interface to stream I/O. There is no readinto() method because Python’s character strings are immutable. It inherits IOBase. There is no public constructor.
io.TextIOBase.name: io.TextIOBase

io.TextIOBase.buffer.descr: The underlying binary buffer (a BufferedIOBase instance) that TextIOBase deals with. This is not part of the TextIOBase API and may not exist in some implementations.
io.TextIOBase.buffer.name: io.TextIOBase.buffer

io.TextIOBase.detach.descr: Separate the underlying binary buffer from the TextIOBase and return it.
io.TextIOBase.detach.name: io.TextIOBase.detach

io.TextIOBase.encoding.descr: The name of the encoding used to decode the stream’s bytes into strings, and to encode strings into bytes.
io.TextIOBase.encoding.name: io.TextIOBase.encoding

io.TextIOBase.errors.descr: The error setting of the decoder or encoder.
io.TextIOBase.errors.name: io.TextIOBase.errors

io.TextIOBase.newlines.descr: A string, a tuple of strings, or None, indicating the newlines translated so far. Depending on the implementation and the initial constructor flags, this may not be available.
io.TextIOBase.newlines.name: io.TextIOBase.newlines

io.TextIOBase.read.descr: Read and return at most n characters from the stream as a single str. If n is negative or None, reads until EOF.
io.TextIOBase.read.name: io.TextIOBase.read

io.TextIOBase.readline.descr: Read until newline or EOF and return a single str. If the stream is already at EOF, an empty string is returned.
io.TextIOBase.readline.name: io.TextIOBase.readline

io.TextIOBase.seek.descr: Change the stream position to the given offset. Behaviour depends on the whence parameter:
io.TextIOBase.seek.name: io.TextIOBase.seek

io.TextIOBase.tell.descr: Return the current stream position as an opaque number. The number does not usually represent a number of bytes in the underlying binary storage.
io.TextIOBase.tell.name: io.TextIOBase.tell

io.TextIOBase.write.descr: Write the string s to the stream and return the number of characters written.
io.TextIOBase.write.name: io.TextIOBase.write

io.TextIOWrapper.descr: A buffered text stream over a BufferedIOBase binary stream. It inherits TextIOBase.
io.TextIOWrapper.name: io.TextIOWrapper
io.TextIOWrapper.syntax: class io.TextIOWrapper(buffer, encoding=None, errors=None, newline=None, line_buffering=False, write_through=False)

io.UnsupportedOperation.descr: An exception inheriting OSError and ValueError that is raised when an unsupported operation is called on a stream.
io.UnsupportedOperation.name: io.UnsupportedOperation

io.open.descr: This is an alias for the builtin open() function.
io.open.name: io.open
io.open.syntax: io.open(file, mode='r', buffering=-1, encoding=None, errors=None, newline=None, closefd=True, opener=None)

ipaddress.AddressValueError.descr: Any value error related to the address.
ipaddress.AddressValueError.name: ipaddress.AddressValueError

ipaddress.IPv4Address.descr: Construct an IPv4 address. An AddressValueError is raised if address is not a valid IPv4 address.
ipaddress.IPv4Address.name: ipaddress.IPv4Address

ipaddress.IPv4Address.compressed.descr: The string representation in dotted decimal notation. Leading zeroes are never included in the representation.
ipaddress.IPv4Address.compressed.name: ipaddress.IPv4Address.compressed

ipaddress.IPv4Address.exploded.descr: The string representation in dotted decimal notation. Leading zeroes are never included in the representation.
ipaddress.IPv4Address.exploded.name: ipaddress.IPv4Address.exploded

ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_link_local.descr: True if the address is reserved for link-local usage. See RFC 3927.
ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_link_local.name: ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_link_local

ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_loopback.descr: True if this is a loopback address. See RFC 3330 (for IPv4) or RFC 2373 (for IPv6).
ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_loopback.name: ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_loopback

ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_multicast.descr: True if the address is reserved for multicast use. See RFC 3171 (for IPv4) or RFC 2373 (for IPv6).
ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_multicast.name: ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_multicast

ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_private.descr: True if the address is allocated for private networks. See RFC 1918 (for IPv4) or RFC 4193 (for IPv6).
ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_private.name: ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_private

ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_reserved.descr: True if the address is otherwise IETF reserved.
ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_reserved.name: ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_reserved

ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_unspecified.descr: True if the address is unspecified. See RFC 5735 (for IPv4) or RFC 2373 (for IPv6).
ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_unspecified.name: ipaddress.IPv4Address.is_unspecified

ipaddress.IPv4Address.max_prefixlen.descr: The total number of bits in the address representation for this version: 32 for IPv4, 128 for IPv6.
ipaddress.IPv4Address.max_prefixlen.name: ipaddress.IPv4Address.max_prefixlen

ipaddress.IPv4Address.packed.descr: The binary representation of this address - a bytes object of the appropriate length (most significant octet first). This is 4 bytes for IPv4 and 16 bytes for IPv6.
ipaddress.IPv4Address.packed.name: ipaddress.IPv4Address.packed

ipaddress.IPv4Address.version.descr: The appropriate version number: 4 for IPv4, 6 for IPv6.
ipaddress.IPv4Address.version.name: ipaddress.IPv4Address.version

ipaddress.IPv4Interface.descr: Construct an IPv4 interface. The meaning of address is as in the constructor of IPv4Network, except that arbitrary host addresses are always accepted.
ipaddress.IPv4Interface.name: ipaddress.IPv4Interface

ipaddress.IPv4Interface.network.descr: The network (IPv4Network) this interface belongs to.
ipaddress.IPv4Interface.network.name: ipaddress.IPv4Interface.network

ipaddress.IPv4Interface.with_hostmask.descr: A string representation of the interface with the network as a host mask.
ipaddress.IPv4Interface.with_hostmask.name: ipaddress.IPv4Interface.with_hostmask

ipaddress.IPv4Interface.with_netmask.descr: A string representation of the interface with the network as a net mask.
ipaddress.IPv4Interface.with_netmask.name: ipaddress.IPv4Interface.with_netmask

ipaddress.IPv4Interface.with_prefixlen.descr: A string representation of the interface with the mask in prefix notation.
ipaddress.IPv4Interface.with_prefixlen.name: ipaddress.IPv4Interface.with_prefixlen

ipaddress.IPv4Network.descr: Construct an IPv4 network definition. address can be one of the following:
ipaddress.IPv4Network.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network

ipaddress.IPv4Network.address_exclude.descr: Computes the network definitions resulting from removing the given network from this one. Returns an iterator of network objects. Raises ValueError if network is not completely contained in this network.
ipaddress.IPv4Network.address_exclude.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.address_exclude

ipaddress.IPv4Network.broadcast_address.descr: The broadcast address for the network. Packets sent to the broadcast address should be received by every host on the network.
ipaddress.IPv4Network.broadcast_address.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.broadcast_address

ipaddress.IPv4Network.compare_networks.descr: Compare this network to other. In this comparison only the network addresses are considered; host bits aren’t. Returns either -1, 0 or 1.
ipaddress.IPv4Network.compare_networks.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.compare_networks

ipaddress.IPv4Network.compressed.descr: A string representation of the network, with the mask in prefix notation.
ipaddress.IPv4Network.compressed.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.compressed

ipaddress.IPv4Network.exploded.descr: A string representation of the network, with the mask in prefix notation.
ipaddress.IPv4Network.exploded.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.exploded

ipaddress.IPv4Network.hostmask.descr: The host mask, as a string.
ipaddress.IPv4Network.hostmask.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.hostmask

ipaddress.IPv4Network.hosts.descr: Returns an iterator over the usable hosts in the network. The usable hosts are all the IP addresses that belong to the network, except the network address itself and the network broadcast address.
ipaddress.IPv4Network.hosts.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.hosts

ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_link_local.descr: These attributes are true for the network as a whole if they are true for both the network address and the broadcast address
ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_link_local.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_link_local

ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_loopback.descr: These attributes are true for the network as a whole if they are true for both the network address and the broadcast address
ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_loopback.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_loopback

ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_multicast.descr: These attributes are true for the network as a whole if they are true for both the network address and the broadcast address
ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_multicast.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_multicast

ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_private.descr: These attributes are true for the network as a whole if they are true for both the network address and the broadcast address
ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_private.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_private

ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_reserved.descr: These attributes are true for the network as a whole if they are true for both the network address and the broadcast address
ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_reserved.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_reserved

ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_unspecified.descr: These attributes are true for the network as a whole if they are true for both the network address and the broadcast address
ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_unspecified.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.is_unspecified

ipaddress.IPv4Network.max_prefixlen.descr: Refer to the corresponding attribute documentation in IPv4Address
ipaddress.IPv4Network.max_prefixlen.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.max_prefixlen

ipaddress.IPv4Network.network_address.descr: The network address for the network. The network address and the prefix length together uniquely define a network.
ipaddress.IPv4Network.network_address.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.network_address

ipaddress.IPv4Network.num_addresses.descr: The total number of addresses in the network.
ipaddress.IPv4Network.num_addresses.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.num_addresses

ipaddress.IPv4Network.overlaps.descr: True if this network is partly or wholly contained in other or other is wholly contained in this network.
ipaddress.IPv4Network.overlaps.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.overlaps

ipaddress.IPv4Network.prefixlen.descr: Length of the network prefix, in bits.
ipaddress.IPv4Network.prefixlen.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.prefixlen

ipaddress.IPv4Network.subnets.descr: The subnets that join to make the current network definition, depending on the argument values. prefixlen_diff is the amount our prefix length should be increased by. new_prefix is the desired new prefix of the subnets; it must be larger than our prefix. ipaddress.IPv4Network.subnets.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.subnets

ipaddress.IPv4Network.supernet.descr: The supernet containing this network definition, depending on the argument values. prefixlen_diff is the amount our prefix length should be decreased by. new_prefix is the desired new prefix of the supernet; it must be smaller than our prefix. One and only one of prefixlen_diff and new_prefix must be set. Returns a single network object.
ipaddress.IPv4Network.supernet.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.supernet

ipaddress.IPv4Network.version.descr: Refer to the corresponding attribute documentation in IPv4Address
ipaddress.IPv4Network.version.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.version

ipaddress.IPv4Network.with_hostmask.descr: A string representation of the network, with the mask in host mask notation.
ipaddress.IPv4Network.with_hostmask.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.with_hostmask

ipaddress.IPv4Network.with_netmask.descr: A string representation of the network, with the mask in net mask notation.
ipaddress.IPv4Network.with_netmask.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.with_netmask

ipaddress.IPv4Network.with_prefixlen.descr: A string representation of the network, with the mask in prefix notation.
ipaddress.IPv4Network.with_prefixlen.name: ipaddress.IPv4Network.with_prefixlen

ipaddress.IPv6Address.descr: Construct an IPv6 address. An AddressValueError is raised if address is not a valid IPv6 address.
ipaddress.IPv6Address.name: ipaddress.IPv6Address

ipaddress.IPv6Address.compressed.descr: The short form of the address representation, with leading zeroes in groups omitted and the longest sequence of groups consisting entirely of zeroes collapsed to a single empty group.
ipaddress.IPv6Address.compressed.name: ipaddress.IPv6Address.compressed

ipaddress.IPv6Address.exploded.descr: The long form of the address representation, with all leading zeroes and groups consisting entirely of zeroes included.
ipaddress.IPv6Address.exploded.name: ipaddress.IPv6Address.exploded

ipaddress.IPv6Address.ipv4_mapped.descr: For addresses that appear to be IPv4 mapped addresses (starting with ::FFFF/96), this property will report the embedded IPv4 address. For any other address, this property will be None.
ipaddress.IPv6Address.ipv4_mapped.name: ipaddress.IPv6Address.ipv4_mapped

isalpha.descr: Return true if all characters in the string are alphabetic and there is at least one character, false otherwise. Note that this is different from the “Alphabetic” property defined in the Unicode Standard.

isdigit.descr: Return true if all characters in the string are digits and there is at least one character, false otherwise. If classinfo is not a class (type object), it may be a tuple of type objects, or may recursively contain other such tuples (other sequence types are not accepted). If classinfo is not a type or tuple of types and such tuples, a TypeError exception is raised.
isinstance.name: isinstance

Formally, numeric characters are those with the property value Numeric_Type=Digit, Numeric_Type=Decimal or Numeric_Type=Numeric.
isnumeric.name: str.isnumeric

isprintable.descr: Return true if all characters in the string are printable or the string is empty, false otherwise. (Note that printable characters in this context are those which should not be escaped when repr() is invoked on a string. It has no bearing on the handling of strings written to sys.stdout or sys.stderr.)

iter.descr: Return an iterator object. The first argument is interpreted very differently depending on the presence of the second argument. Without a second argument, object must be a collection object which supports the iteration protocol (the __iter__() method), or it must support the sequence protocol (the __getitem__() method with integer arguments starting at 0). If it does not support either of those protocols, TypeError is raised. If the second argument, sentinel, is given, then object must be a callable object. The iterator created in this case will call object with no arguments for each call to its __next__() method; if the value returned is equal to sentinel, StopIteration will be raised, otherwise the value will be returned.

itertools.islice.descr: Make an iterator that returns selected elements from the iterable. If start is non-zero, then elements from the iterable are skipped until start is reached. If stop is None, then iteration continues until the iterator is exhausted, if at all; otherwise, it stops at the specified position. Unlike regular slicing, islice() does not support negative values for start, stop, or step. Can be used to extract related fields from data where the internal structure has been flattened (for example, a multi-line report may list a name field on every third line). Equivalent to:
