tkinter.tix.Form.descr: The Form geometry manager based on attachment rules for all Tk widgets.
tkinter.tix.Form.name: tkinter.tix.Form

tkinter.tix.HList.descr: The HList widget can be used to display any data that have a hierarchical structure, for example, file system directory trees. The list entries are indented and connected by branch lines according to their places in the hierarchy.
tkinter.tix.HList.name: tkinter.tix.HList

tkinter.tix.InputOnly.descr: The InputOnly widgets are to accept inputs from the user, which can be done with the bind command (Unix only).
tkinter.tix.InputOnly.name: tkinter.tix.InputOnly

tkinter.tix.LabelEntry.descr: The LabelEntry widget packages an entry widget and a label into one mega widget. It can be used be used to simplify the creation of “entry-form” type of interface.
tkinter.tix.LabelEntry.name: tkinter.tix.LabelEntry

tkinter.tix.LabelFrame.descr: The LabelFrame widget packages a frame widget and a label into one mega widget. To create widgets inside a LabelFrame widget, one creates the new widgets relative to the frame subwidget and manage them inside the frame subwidget.
tkinter.tix.LabelFrame.name: tkinter.tix.LabelFrame

tkinter.tix.ListNoteBook.descr: The ListNoteBook widget is very similar to the TixNoteBook widget: it can be used to display many windows in a limited space using a notebook metaphor. The notebook is divided into a stack of pages (windows). At one time only one of these pages can be shown. The user can navigate through these pages by choosing the name of the desired page in the hlist subwidget.
tkinter.tix.ListNoteBook.name: tkinter.tix.ListNoteBook

tkinter.tix.Meter.descr: The Meter widget can be used to show the progress of a background job which may take a long time to execute.
tkinter.tix.Meter.name: tkinter.tix.Meter

tkinter.tix.NoteBook.descr: The NoteBook widget can be used to display many windows in a limited space using a notebook metaphor. The notebook is divided into a stack of pages. At one time only one of these pages can be shown. The user can navigate through these pages by choosing the visual “tabs” at the top of the NoteBook widget.
tkinter.tix.NoteBook.name: tkinter.tix.NoteBook

tkinter.tix.OptionMenu.descr: The OptionMenu creates a menu button of options.
tkinter.tix.OptionMenu.name: tkinter.tix.OptionMenu

tkinter.tix.PanedWindow.descr: The PanedWindow widget allows the user to interactively manipulate the sizes of several panes. The panes can be arranged either vertically or horizontally. The user changes the sizes of the panes by dragging the resize handle between two panes.
tkinter.tix.PanedWindow.name: tkinter.tix.PanedWindow

tkinter.tix.PopupMenu.descr: The PopupMenu widget can be used as a replacement of the tk_popup command. The advantage of the Tix PopupMenu widget is it requires less application code to manipulate.
tkinter.tix.PopupMenu.name: tkinter.tix.PopupMenu

tkinter.tix.Select.descr: The Select widget is a container of button subwidgets. It can be used to provide radio-box or check-box style of selection options for the user.
tkinter.tix.Select.name: tkinter.tix.Select

tkinter.tix.StdButtonBox.descr: The StdButtonBox widget is a group of standard buttons for Motif-like dialog boxes.
tkinter.tix.StdButtonBox.name: tkinter.tix.StdButtonBox

tkinter.tix.TList.descr: The TList widget can be used to display data in a tabular format. The list entries of a TList widget are similar to the entries in the Tk listbox widget. The main differences are (1) the TList widget can display the list entries in a two dimensional format and (2) you can use graphical images as well as multiple colors and fonts for the list entries.
tkinter.tix.TList.name: tkinter.tix.TList

tkinter.tix.Tk.descr: Toplevel widget of Tix which represents mostly the main window of an application. It has an associated Tcl interpreter.
tkinter.tix.Tk.name: tkinter.tix.Tk

tkinter.tix.Tree.descr: The Tree widget can be used to display hierarchical data in a tree form. The user can adjust the view of the tree by opening or closing parts of the tree.
tkinter.tix.Tree.name: tkinter.tix.Tree

tkinter.tix.tixCommand.descr: The tix commands provide access to miscellaneous elements of Tix‘s internal state and the Tix application context. Most of the information manipulated by these methods pertains to the application as a whole, or to a screen or display, rather than to a particular window.
tkinter.tix.tixCommand.name: tkinter.tix.tixCommand

tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_addbitmapdir.descr: Tix maintains a list of directories under which the tix_getimage() and tix_getbitmap() methods will search for image files. The standard bitmap directory is $TIX_LIBRARY/bitmaps. The tix_addbitmapdir() method adds directory into this list. By using this method, the image files of an applications can also be located using the tix_getimage() or tix_getbitmap() method.
tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_addbitmapdir.name: tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_addbitmapdir

tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_cget.descr: Returns the current value of the configuration option given by option. Option may be any of the configuration options.
tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_cget.name: tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_cget

tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_configure.descr: Query or modify the configuration options of the Tix application context. If no option is specified, returns a dictionary all of the available options. If option is specified with no value, then the method returns a list describing the one named option (this list will be identical to the corresponding sublist of the value returned if no option is specified). If one or more option-value pairs are specified, then the method modifies the given option(s) to have the given value(s); in this case the method returns an empty string. Option may be any of the configuration options.
tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_configure.name: tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_configure

tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_filedialog.descr: Returns the file selection dialog that may be shared among different calls from this application. This method will create a file selection dialog widget when it is called the first time. This dialog will be returned by all subsequent calls to tix_filedialog(). An optional dlgclass parameter can be passed as a string to specified what type of file selection dialog widget is desired. Possible options are tix, FileSelectDialog or tixExFileSelectDialog.
tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_filedialog.name: tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_filedialog

tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_getbitmap.descr: Locates a bitmap file of the name name.xpm or name in one of the bitmap directories (see the tix_addbitmapdir() method). By using tix_getbitmap(), you can avoid hard coding the pathnames of the bitmap files in your application. When successful, it returns the complete pathname of the bitmap file, prefixed with the character @. The returned value can be used to configure the bitmap option of the Tk and Tix widgets.
tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_getbitmap.name: tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_getbitmap

tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_getimage.descr: Locates an image file of the name name.xpm, name.xbm or name.ppm in one of the bitmap directories (see the tix_addbitmapdir() method above). If more than one file with the same name (but different extensions) exist, then the image type is chosen according to the depth of the X display: xbm images are chosen on monochrome displays and color images are chosen on color displays. By using tix_getimage(), you can avoid hard coding the pathnames of the image files in your application. When successful, this method returns the name of the newly created image, which can be used to configure the image option of the Tk and Tix widgets.
tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_getimage.name: tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_getimage

tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_option_get.descr: Gets the options maintained by the Tix scheme mechanism.
tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_option_get.name: tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_option_get

tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_resetoptions.descr: Resets the scheme and fontset of the Tix application to newScheme and newFontSet, respectively. This affects only those widgets created after this call. Therefore, it is best to call the resetoptions method before the creation of any widgets in a Tix application.
tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_resetoptions.name: tkinter.tix.tixCommand.tix_resetoptions

tkinter.ttk.Combobox.descr: If newindex is specified, sets the combobox value to the element position newindex. Otherwise, returns the index of the current value or -1 if the current value is not in the values list.
tkinter.ttk.Combobox.name: tkinter.ttk.Combobox

tkinter.ttk.Combobox.current.descr: If newindex is specified, sets the combobox value to the element position newindex. Otherwise, returns the index of the current value or -1 if the current value is not in the values list.
tkinter.ttk.Combobox.current.name: tkinter.ttk.Combobox.current

tkinter.ttk.Combobox.get.descr: Returns the current value of the combobox.
tkinter.ttk.Combobox.get.name: tkinter.ttk.Combobox.get

tkinter.ttk.Combobox.set.descr: Sets the value of the combobox to value.
tkinter.ttk.Combobox.set.name: tkinter.ttk.Combobox.set

tkinter.ttk.Notebook.descr: Adds a new tab to the notebook.
tkinter.ttk.Notebook.name: tkinter.ttk.Notebook

tkinter.ttk.Notebook.add.descr: Adds a new tab to the notebook.
tkinter.ttk.Notebook.add.name: tkinter.ttk.Notebook.add

tkinter.ttk.Notebook.enable_traversal.descr: Enable keyboard traversal for a toplevel window containing this notebook.
tkinter.ttk.Notebook.enable_traversal.name: tkinter.ttk.Notebook.enable_traversal

tkinter.ttk.Notebook.forget.descr: Removes the tab specified by tab_id, unmaps and unmanages the associated window.
tkinter.ttk.Notebook.forget.name: tkinter.ttk.Notebook.forget

tkinter.ttk.Notebook.hide.descr: Hides the tab specified by tab_id.
tkinter.ttk.Notebook.hide.name: tkinter.ttk.Notebook.hide

tkinter.ttk.Notebook.identify.descr: Returns the name of the tab element at position x, y, or the empty string if none.
tkinter.ttk.Notebook.identify.name: tkinter.ttk.Notebook.identify

tkinter.ttk.Notebook.index.descr: Returns the numeric index of the tab specified by tab_id, or the total number of tabs if tab_id is the string “end”.
tkinter.ttk.Notebook.index.name: tkinter.ttk.Notebook.index

tkinter.ttk.Notebook.insert.descr: Inserts a pane at the specified position.
tkinter.ttk.Notebook.insert.name: tkinter.ttk.Notebook.insert

tkinter.ttk.Notebook.tab.descr: Query or modify the options of the specific tab_id.
tkinter.ttk.Notebook.tab.name: tkinter.ttk.Notebook.tab

tkinter.ttk.Notebook.tabs.descr: Returns a list of windows managed by the notebook.
tkinter.ttk.Notebook.tabs.name: tkinter.ttk.Notebook.tabs

tkinter.ttk.Progressbar.descr: Begin autoincrement mode: schedules a recurring timer event that calls Progressbar.step() every interval milliseconds. If omitted, interval defaults to 50 milliseconds.
tkinter.ttk.Progressbar.name: tkinter.ttk.Progressbar

tkinter.ttk.Progressbar.start.descr: Begin autoincrement mode: schedules a recurring timer event that calls Progressbar.step() every interval milliseconds. If omitted, interval defaults to 50 milliseconds.
tkinter.ttk.Progressbar.start.name: tkinter.ttk.Progressbar.start

tkinter.ttk.Progressbar.step.descr: Increments the progress bar’s value by amount.
tkinter.ttk.Progressbar.step.name: tkinter.ttk.Progressbar.step

tkinter.ttk.Progressbar.stop.descr: Stop autoincrement mode: cancels any recurring timer event initiated by Progressbar.start() for this progress bar.
tkinter.ttk.Progressbar.stop.name: tkinter.ttk.Progressbar.stop

tkinter.ttk.Style.descr: This class is used to manipulate the style database.
tkinter.ttk.Style.name: tkinter.ttk.Style

tkinter.ttk.Style.configure.descr: Query or set the default value of the specified option(s) in style.
tkinter.ttk.Style.configure.name: tkinter.ttk.Style.configure

tkinter.ttk.Style.element_create.descr: Create a new element in the current theme, of the given etype which is expected to be either “image”, “from” or “vsapi”. The latter is only available in Tk 8.6a for Windows XP and Vista and is not described here.
tkinter.ttk.Style.element_create.name: tkinter.ttk.Style.element_create

tkinter.ttk.Style.element_names.descr: Returns the list of elements defined in the current theme.
tkinter.ttk.Style.element_names.name: tkinter.ttk.Style.element_names

tkinter.ttk.Style.element_options.descr: Returns the list of elementname‘s options.
tkinter.ttk.Style.element_options.name: tkinter.ttk.Style.element_options

tkinter.ttk.Style.layout.descr: Define the widget layout for given style. If layoutspec is omitted, return the layout specification for given style.
tkinter.ttk.Style.layout.name: tkinter.ttk.Style.layout

tkinter.ttk.Style.lookup.descr: Returns the value specified for option in style.
tkinter.ttk.Style.lookup.name: tkinter.ttk.Style.lookup

tkinter.ttk.Style.map.descr: Query or sets dynamic values of the specified option(s) in style.
tkinter.ttk.Style.map.name: tkinter.ttk.Style.map

tkinter.ttk.Style.theme_names.descr: Returns a list of all known themes.
tkinter.ttk.Style.theme_names.name: tkinter.ttk.Style.theme_names

tkinter.ttk.Style.theme_settings.descr: Temporarily sets the current theme to themename, apply specified settings and then restore the previous theme.
tkinter.ttk.Style.theme_settings.name: tkinter.ttk.Style.theme_settings

tkinter.ttk.Style.theme_use.descr: If themename is not given, returns the theme in use. Otherwise, sets the current theme to themename, refreshes all widgets and emits a <<ThemeChanged>> event.
tkinter.ttk.Style.theme_use.name: tkinter.ttk.Style.theme_use

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.descr: Returns the bounding box (relative to the treeview widget’s window) of the specified item in the form (x, y, width, height).
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.bbox.descr: Returns the bounding box (relative to the treeview widget’s window) of the specified item in the form (x, y, width, height).
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.bbox.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.bbox

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.column.descr: Query or modify the options for the specified column.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.column.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.column

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.delete.descr: Delete all specified items and all their descendants.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.delete.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.delete

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.detach.descr: Unlinks all of the specified items from the tree.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.detach.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.detach

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.exists.descr: Returns True if the specified item is present in the tree.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.exists.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.exists

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.focus.descr: If item is specified, sets the focus item to item. Otherwise, returns the current focus item, or ‘’ if there is none.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.focus.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.focus

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.get_children.descr: Returns the list of children belonging to item.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.get_children.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.get_children

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.heading.descr: Query or modify the heading options for the specified column.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.heading.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.heading

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.identify.descr: Returns a description of the specified component under the point given by x and y, or the empty string if no such component is present at that position.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.identify.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.identify

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.identify_column.descr: Returns the data column identifier of the cell at position x.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.identify_column.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.identify_column

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.identify_element.descr: Returns the element at position x, y.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.identify_element.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.identify_element

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.identify_row.descr: Returns the item ID of the item at position y.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.identify_row.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.identify_row

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.index.descr: Returns the integer index of item within its parent’s list of children.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.index.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.index

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.insert.descr: Creates a new item and returns the item identifier of the newly created item.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.insert.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.insert

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.item.descr: Query or modify the options for the specified item.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.item.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.item

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.move.descr: Moves item to position index in parent‘s list of children.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.move.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.move

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.next.descr: Returns the identifier of item‘s next sibling, or ‘’ if item is the last child of its parent.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.next.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.next

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.parent.descr: Returns the ID of the parent of item, or ‘’ if item is at the top level of the hierarchy.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.parent.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.parent

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.prev.descr: Returns the identifier of item‘s previous sibling, or ‘’ if item is the first child of its parent.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.prev.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.prev

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.selection.descr: If selop is not specified, returns selected items. Otherwise, it will act according to the following selection methods.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.selection.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.selection

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.selection_toggle.descr: Toggle the selection state of each item in items.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.selection_toggle.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.selection_toggle

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.set.descr: With one argument, returns a dictionary of column/value pairs for the specified item. With two arguments, returns the current value of the specified column. With three arguments, sets the value of given column in given item to the specified value.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.set.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.set

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.tag_bind.descr: Bind a callback for the given event sequence to the tag tagname. When an event is delivered to an item, the callbacks for each of the item’s tags option are called.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.tag_bind.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.tag_bind

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.tag_configure.descr: Query or modify the options for the specified tagname.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.tag_configure.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.tag_configure

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.tag_has.descr: If item is specified, returns 1 or 0 depending on whether the specified item has the given tagname. Otherwise, returns a list of all items that have the specified tag.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.tag_has.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.tag_has

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.xview.descr: Query or modify horizontal position of the treeview.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.xview.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.xview

tkinter.ttk.Treeview.yview.descr: Query or modify vertical position of the treeview.
tkinter.ttk.Treeview.yview.name: tkinter.ttk.Treeview.yview

tkinter.ttk.Widget.descr: Returns the name of the element at position x y, or the empty string if the point does not lie within any element.
tkinter.ttk.Widget.name: tkinter.ttk.Widget

tkinter.ttk.Widget.identify.descr: Returns the name of the element at position x y, or the empty string if the point does not lie within any element.
tkinter.ttk.Widget.identify.name: tkinter.ttk.Widget.identify

tkinter.ttk.Widget.instate.descr: Test the widget’s state. If a callback is not specified, returns True if the widget state matches statespec and False otherwise. If callback is specified then it is called with args if widget state matches statespec.
tkinter.ttk.Widget.instate.name: tkinter.ttk.Widget.instate

tkinter.ttk.Widget.state.descr: Modify or inquire widget state. If statespec is specified, sets the widget state according to it and return a new statespec indicating which flags were changed. If statespec is not specified, returns the currently-enabled state flags.
tkinter.ttk.Widget.state.name: tkinter.ttk.Widget.state

to_bytes.descr: Return an array of bytes representing an integer.
to_bytes.name: int.to_bytes

tobytes.descr: Convert the array to an array of machine values and return the bytes representation (the same sequence of bytes that would be written to a file by the tofile() method.)
tobytes.name: array.array.tobytes

tofile.descr: Write all items (as machine values) to the file object f.
tofile.name: array.array.tofile

tolist.descr: Convert the array to an ordinary list with the same items.
tolist.name: array.array.tolist

tounicode.descr: Convert the array to a unicode string. The array must be a type 'u' array; otherwise a ValueError is raised. Use array.tobytes().decode(enc) to obtain a unicode string from an array of some other type.
tounicode.name: array.array.tounicode

trace.CoverageResults.descr: A container for coverage results, created by Trace.results(). Should not be created directly by the user.
trace.CoverageResults.name: trace.CoverageResults

trace.CoverageResults.update.descr: Merge in data from another CoverageResults object.
trace.CoverageResults.update.name: trace.CoverageResults.update

trace.CoverageResults.write_results.descr: Write coverage results. Set show_missing to show lines that had no hits. Set summary to include in the output the coverage summary per module. coverdir specifies the directory into which the coverage result files will be output. If None, the results for each source file are placed in its directory.
trace.CoverageResults.write_results.name: trace.CoverageResults.write_results

trace.Trace.descr: Create an object to trace execution of a single statement or expression. All parameters are optional. count enables counting of line numbers. trace enables line execution tracing. countfuncs enables listing of the functions called during the run. countcallers enables call relationship tracking. ignoremods is a list of modules or packages to ignore. ignoredirs is a list of directories whose modules or packages should be ignored. infile is the name of the file from which to read stored count information. outfile is the name of the file in which to write updated count information. timing enables a timestamp relative to when tracing was started to be displayed.
trace.Trace.name: trace.Trace
trace.Trace.syntax: class trace.Trace(count=1, trace=1, countfuncs=0, countcallers=0, ignoremods=(), ignoredirs=(), infile=None, outfile=None, timing=False)

trace.Trace.results.descr: Return a CoverageResults object that contains the cumulative results of all previous calls to run, runctx and runfunc for the given Trace instance. Does not reset the accumulated trace results.
trace.Trace.results.name: trace.Trace.results

trace.Trace.run.descr: Execute the command and gather statistics from the execution with the current tracing parameters. cmd must be a string or code object, suitable for passing into exec().
trace.Trace.run.name: trace.Trace.run

trace.Trace.runctx.descr: Execute the command and gather statistics from the execution with the current tracing parameters, in the defined global and local environments. If not defined, globals and locals default to empty dictionaries.
trace.Trace.runctx.name: trace.Trace.runctx

trace.Trace.runfunc.descr: Call func with the given arguments under control of the Trace object with the current tracing parameters.
trace.Trace.runfunc.name: trace.Trace.runfunc

traceback.extract_stack.descr: Extract the raw traceback from the current stack frame. The return value has the same format as for extract_tb(). The optional f and limit arguments have the same meaning as for print_stack().
traceback.extract_stack.name: traceback.extract_stack

traceback.extract_tb.descr: Return a list of up to limit “pre-processed” stack trace entries extracted from the traceback object traceback. It is useful for alternate formatting of stack traces. If limit is omitted or None, all entries are extracted. A “pre-processed” stack trace entry is a quadruple (filename, line number, function name, text) representing the information that is usually printed for a stack trace. The text is a string with leading and trailing whitespace stripped; if the source is not available it is None.
traceback.extract_tb.name: traceback.extract_tb

traceback.format_exc.descr: This is like print_exc(limit) but returns a string instead of printing to a file.
traceback.format_exc.name: traceback.format_exc

traceback.format_exception.descr: Format a stack trace and the exception information. The arguments have the same meaning as the corresponding arguments to print_exception(). The return value is a list of strings, each ending in a newline and some containing internal newlines. When these lines are concatenated and printed, exactly the same text is printed as does print_exception().
traceback.format_exception.name: traceback.format_exception

traceback.format_exception_only.descr: Format the exception part of a traceback. The arguments are the exception type and value such as given by sys.last_type and sys.last_value. The return value is a list of strings, each ending in a newline. Normally, the list contains a single string; however, for SyntaxError exceptions, it contains several lines that (when printed) display detailed information about where the syntax error occurred. The message indicating which exception occurred is the always last string in the list.
traceback.format_exception_only.name: traceback.format_exception_only

traceback.format_list.descr: Given a list of tuples as returned by extract_tb() or extract_stack(), return a list of strings ready for printing. Each string in the resulting list corresponds to the item with the same index in the argument list. Each string ends in a newline; the strings may contain internal newlines as well, for those items whose source text line is not None.
traceback.format_list.name: traceback.format_list

traceback.print_exc.descr: This is a shorthand for print_exception(*sys.exc_info()).
traceback.print_exc.name: traceback.print_exc

traceback.print_exception.descr: Print exception information and up to limit stack trace entries from traceback to file. This differs from print_tb() in the following ways:
traceback.print_exception.name: traceback.print_exception
traceback.print_exception.syntax: traceback.print_exception(type, value, traceback, limit=None, file=None, chain=True)

traceback.print_last.descr: This is a shorthand for print_exception(sys.last_type, sys.last_value, sys.last_traceback, limit, file). In general it will work only after an exception has reached an interactive prompt (see sys.last_type).
traceback.print_last.name: traceback.print_last

traceback.print_stack.descr: This function prints a stack trace from its invocation point. The optional f argument can be used to specify an alternate stack frame to start. The optional limit and file arguments have the same meaning as for print_exception().
traceback.print_stack.name: traceback.print_stack

traceback.print_tb.descr: Print up to limit stack trace entries from traceback. If limit is omitted or None, all entries are printed. If file is omitted or None, the output goes to sys.stderr; otherwise it should be an open file or file-like object to receive the output.
traceback.print_tb.name: traceback.print_tb

translate.descr: Return a copy of the s where all characters have been mapped through the map which must be a dictionary of Unicode ordinals (integers) to Unicode ordinals, strings or None. Unmapped characters are left untouched. Characters mapped to None are deleted.
translate.name: str.translate

tty.setcbreak.descr: Change the mode of file descriptor fd to cbreak. If when is omitted, it defaults to termios.TCSAFLUSH, and is passed to termios.tcsetattr().
tty.setcbreak.name: tty.setcbreak

tty.setraw.descr: Change the mode of the file descriptor fd to raw. If when is omitted, it defaults to termios.TCSAFLUSH, and is passed to termios.tcsetattr().
tty.setraw.name: tty.setraw

tuple.descr: Rather than being a function, tuple is actually an immutable sequence type, as documented in Tuples and Sequence Types — list, tuple, range.
tuple.name: tuple

turtle.RawPen.descr: Create a turtle. The turtle has all methods described above as “methods of Turtle/RawTurtle”.
turtle.RawPen.name: turtle.RawPen

turtle.RawTurtle.descr: Create a turtle. The turtle has all methods described above as “methods of Turtle/RawTurtle”.
turtle.RawTurtle.name: turtle.RawTurtle

turtle.Screen.descr: Subclass of TurtleScreen, with four methods added.
turtle.Screen.name: turtle.Screen

turtle.ScrolledCanvas.descr: Used by class Screen, which thus automatically provides a ScrolledCanvas as playground for the turtles.
turtle.ScrolledCanvas.name: turtle.ScrolledCanvas

turtle.Shape.descr: Data structure modeling shapes. The pair (type_, data) must follow this specification:
turtle.Shape.name: turtle.Shape

turtle.Turtle.descr: Subclass of RawTurtle, has the same interface but draws on a default Screen object created automatically when needed for the first time.
turtle.Turtle.name: turtle.Turtle

turtle.TurtleScreen.descr: Provides screen oriented methods like setbg() etc. that are described above.
turtle.TurtleScreen.name: turtle.TurtleScreen

turtle.Vec2D.descr: A two-dimensional vector class, used as a helper class for implementing turtle graphics. May be useful for turtle graphics programs too. Derived from tuple, so a vector is a tuple!
turtle.Vec2D.name: turtle.Vec2D

turtle.addshape.descr: There are three different ways to call this function:
turtle.addshape.name: turtle.addshape

turtle.back.descr: Move the turtle backward by distance, opposite to the direction the turtle is headed. Do not change the turtle’s heading.
turtle.back.name: turtle.back

turtle.backward.descr: Move the turtle backward by distance, opposite to the direction the turtle is headed. Do not change the turtle’s heading.
turtle.backward.name: turtle.backward

turtle.begin_fill.descr: To be called just before drawing a shape to be filled.
turtle.begin_fill.name: turtle.begin_fill

turtle.begin_poly.descr: Start recording the vertices of a polygon. Current turtle position is first vertex of polygon.
turtle.begin_poly.name: turtle.begin_poly

turtle.bgcolor.descr: Set or return background color of the TurtleScreen.
turtle.bgcolor.name: turtle.bgcolor

turtle.bgpic.descr: Set background image or return name of current backgroundimage. If picname is a filename, set the corresponding image as background. If picname is "nopic", delete background image, if present. If picname is None, return the filename of the current backgroundimage.
turtle.bgpic.name: turtle.bgpic

turtle.bk.descr: Move the turtle backward by distance, opposite to the direction the turtle is headed. Do not change the turtle’s heading.
turtle.bk.name: turtle.bk

turtle.circle.descr: Draw a circle with given radius. The center is radius units left of the turtle; extent – an angle – determines which part of the circle is drawn. If extent is not given, draw the entire circle. If extent is not a full circle, one endpoint of the arc is the current pen position. Draw the arc in counterclockwise direction if radius is positive, otherwise in clockwise direction. Finally the direction of the turtle is changed by the amount of extent.
turtle.circle.name: turtle.circle

turtle.clear.descr: Delete the turtle’s drawings from the screen. Do not move turtle. State and position of the turtle as well as drawings of other turtles are not affected.
turtle.clear.name: turtle.clear

turtle.clearscreen.descr: Delete all drawings and all turtles from the TurtleScreen. Reset the now empty TurtleScreen to its initial state: white background, no background image, no event bindings and tracing on.
turtle.clearscreen.name: turtle.clearscreen

turtle.clearstamps.descr: Delete all or first/last n of turtle’s stamps. If n is None, delete all stamps, if n > 0 delete first n stamps, else if n < 0 delete last n stamps.
turtle.clearstamps.name: turtle.clearstamps

turtle.clone.descr: Create and return a clone of the turtle with same position, heading and turtle properties.
turtle.clone.name: turtle.clone

turtle.color.descr: Return or set pencolor and fillcolor.
turtle.color.name: turtle.color

turtle.colormode.descr: Return the colormode or set it to 1.0 or 255. Subsequently r, g, b values of color triples have to be in the range 0..cmode.
turtle.colormode.name: turtle.colormode

turtle.degrees.descr: Set angle measurement units, i.e. set number of “degrees” for a full circle. Default value is 360 degrees.
turtle.degrees.name: turtle.degrees

turtle.delay.descr: Set or return the drawing delay in milliseconds. (This is approximately the time interval between two consecutive canvas updates.) The longer the drawing delay, the slower the animation.
turtle.delay.name: turtle.delay

turtle.distance.descr: Return the distance from the turtle to (x,y), the given vector, or the given other turtle, in turtle step units.
turtle.distance.name: turtle.distance

turtle.done.descr: Starts event loop - calling Tkinter’s mainloop function. Must be the last statement in a turtle graphics program. Must not be used if a script is run from within IDLE in -n mode (No subprocess) - for interactive use of turtle graphics.
turtle.done.name: turtle.done

turtle.dot.descr: Draw a circular dot with diameter size, using color. If size is not given, the maximum of pensize+4 and 2*pensize is used.
turtle.dot.name: turtle.dot

turtle.down.descr: Pull the pen down – drawing when moving.
turtle.down.name: turtle.down

turtle.end_fill.descr: Fill the shape drawn after the last call to begin_fill().
turtle.end_fill.name: turtle.end_fill

turtle.end_poly.descr: Stop recording the vertices of a polygon. Current turtle position is last vertex of polygon. This will be connected with the first vertex.
turtle.end_poly.name: turtle.end_poly

turtle.exitonclick.descr: Bind bye() method to mouse clicks on the Screen.
turtle.exitonclick.name: turtle.exitonclick

turtle.fd.descr: Move the turtle forward by the specified distance, in the direction the turtle is headed.
turtle.fd.name: turtle.fd

turtle.filling.descr: Return fillstate (True if filling, False else).
turtle.filling.name: turtle.filling

turtle.forward.descr: Move the turtle forward by the specified distance, in the direction the turtle is headed.
turtle.forward.name: turtle.forward

turtle.get_shapepoly.descr: Return the current shape polygon as tuple of coordinate pairs. This can be used to define a new shape or components of a compound shape.
turtle.get_shapepoly.name: turtle.get_shapepoly

turtle.getcanvas.descr: Return the Canvas of this TurtleScreen. Useful for insiders who know what to do with a Tkinter Canvas.
turtle.getcanvas.name: turtle.getcanvas

turtle.getpen.descr: Return the Turtle object itself. Only reasonable use: as a function to return the “anonymous turtle”:
turtle.getpen.name: turtle.getpen

turtle.getscreen.descr: Return the TurtleScreen object the turtle is drawing on. TurtleScreen methods can then be called for that object.
turtle.getscreen.name: turtle.getscreen

turtle.getshapes.descr: Return a list of names of all currently available turtle shapes.
turtle.getshapes.name: turtle.getshapes

turtle.getturtle.descr: Return the Turtle object itself. Only reasonable use: as a function to return the “anonymous turtle”:
turtle.getturtle.name: turtle.getturtle

turtle.goto.descr: If y is None, x must be a pair of coordinates or a Vec2D (e.g. as returned by pos()).
turtle.goto.name: turtle.goto

turtle.heading.descr: Return the turtle’s current heading (value depends on the turtle mode, see mode()).
turtle.heading.name: turtle.heading

turtle.hideturtle.descr: Make the turtle invisible. It’s a good idea to do this while you’re in the middle of doing some complex drawing, because hiding the turtle speeds up the drawing observably.
turtle.hideturtle.name: turtle.hideturtle

turtle.home.descr: Move turtle to the origin – coordinates (0,0) – and set its heading to its start-orientation (which depends on the mode, see mode()).
turtle.home.name: turtle.home

turtle.ht.descr: Make the turtle invisible. It’s a good idea to do this while you’re in the middle of doing some complex drawing, because hiding the turtle speeds up the drawing observably.
turtle.ht.name: turtle.ht

turtle.isdown.descr: Return True if pen is down, False if it’s up.
turtle.isdown.name: turtle.isdown

turtle.isvisible.descr: Return True if the Turtle is shown, False if it’s hidden.
turtle.isvisible.name: turtle.isvisible

turtle.left.descr: Turn turtle left by angle units. (Units are by default degrees, but can be set via the degrees() and radians() functions.) Angle orientation depends on the turtle mode, see mode().
turtle.left.name: turtle.left

turtle.listen.descr: Set focus on TurtleScreen (in order to collect key-events). Dummy arguments are provided in order to be able to pass listen() to the onclick method.
turtle.listen.name: turtle.listen

turtle.lt.descr: Turn turtle left by angle units. (Units are by default degrees, but can be set via the degrees() and radians() functions.) Angle orientation depends on the turtle mode, see mode().
turtle.lt.name: turtle.lt

turtle.mainloop.descr: Starts event loop - calling Tkinter’s mainloop function. Must be the last statement in a turtle graphics program. Must not be used if a script is run from within IDLE in -n mode (No subprocess) - for interactive use of turtle graphics.
turtle.mainloop.name: turtle.mainloop

turtle.mode.descr: Set turtle mode (“standard”, “logo” or “world”) and perform reset. If mode is not given, current mode is returned.
turtle.mode.name: turtle.mode

turtle.numinput.descr: Pop up a dialog window for input of a number. title is the title of the dialog window, prompt is a text mostly describing what numerical information to input. default: default value, minval: minimum value for imput, maxval: maximum value for input The number input must be in the range minval .. maxval if these are given. If not, a hint is issued and the dialog remains open for correction. Return the number input. If the dialog is canceled, return None.
turtle.numinput.name: turtle.numinput

turtle.onclick.descr: Bind fun to mouse-click events on this turtle. If fun is None, existing bindings are removed. Example for the anonymous turtle, i.e. the procedural way:
turtle.onclick.name: turtle.onclick

turtle.ondrag.descr: Bind fun to mouse-move events on this turtle. If fun is None, existing bindings are removed.
turtle.ondrag.name: turtle.ondrag

turtle.onkey.descr: Bind fun to key-release event of key. If fun is None, event bindings are removed. Remark: in order to be able to register key-events, TurtleScreen must have the focus. (See method listen().)
turtle.onkey.name: turtle.onkey

turtle.onkeypress.descr: Bind fun to key-press event of key if key is given, or to any key-press-event if no key is given. Remark: in order to be able to register key-events, TurtleScreen must have focus. (See method listen().)
turtle.onkeypress.name: turtle.onkeypress

turtle.onkeyrelease.descr: Bind fun to key-release event of key. If fun is None, event bindings are removed. Remark: in order to be able to register key-events, TurtleScreen must have the focus. (See method listen().)
turtle.onkeyrelease.name: turtle.onkeyrelease

turtle.onrelease.descr: Bind fun to mouse-button-release events on this turtle. If fun is None, existing bindings are removed.
turtle.onrelease.name: turtle.onrelease

turtle.onscreenclick.descr: Bind fun to mouse-click events on this screen. If fun is None, existing bindings are removed.
turtle.onscreenclick.name: turtle.onscreenclick

turtle.ontimer.descr: Install a timer that calls fun after t milliseconds.
turtle.ontimer.name: turtle.ontimer

turtle.pd.descr: Pull the pen down – drawing when moving.
turtle.pd.name: turtle.pd

turtle.pen.descr: Return or set the pen’s attributes in a “pen-dictionary” with the following key/value pairs:
turtle.pen.name: turtle.pen

turtle.pendown.descr: Pull the pen down – drawing when moving.
turtle.pendown.name: turtle.pendown

turtle.pensize.descr: Set the line thickness to width or return it. If resizemode is set to “auto” and turtleshape is a polygon, that polygon is drawn with the same line thickness. If no argument is given, the current pensize is returned.
turtle.pensize.name: turtle.pensize

turtle.penup.descr: Pull the pen up – no drawing when moving.
turtle.penup.name: turtle.penup

turtle.pos.descr: Return the turtle’s current location (x,y) (as a Vec2D vector).
turtle.pos.name: turtle.pos

turtle.position.descr: Return the turtle’s current location (x,y) (as a Vec2D vector).
turtle.position.name: turtle.position

turtle.pu.descr: Pull the pen up – no drawing when moving.
turtle.pu.name: turtle.pu

turtle.radians.descr: Set the angle measurement units to radians. Equivalent to degrees(2*math.pi).
turtle.radians.name: turtle.radians

turtle.register_shape.descr: There are three different ways to call this function:
turtle.register_shape.name: turtle.register_shape

turtle.reset.descr: Delete the turtle’s drawings from the screen, re-center the turtle and set variables to the default values.
turtle.reset.name: turtle.reset

turtle.resetscreen.descr: Reset all Turtles on the Screen to their initial state.
turtle.resetscreen.name: turtle.resetscreen

turtle.resizemode.descr: Set resizemode to one of the values: “auto”, “user”, “noresize”. If rmode is not given, return current resizemode. Different resizemodes have the following effects:
turtle.resizemode.name: turtle.resizemode

turtle.right.descr: Turn turtle right by angle units. (Units are by default degrees, but can be set via the degrees() and radians() functions.) Angle orientation depends on the turtle mode, see mode().
turtle.right.name: turtle.right

turtle.rt.descr: Turn turtle right by angle units. (Units are by default degrees, but can be set via the degrees() and radians() functions.) Angle orientation depends on the turtle mode, see mode().
turtle.rt.name: turtle.rt

turtle.screensize.descr: If no arguments are given, return current (canvaswidth, canvasheight). Else resize the canvas the turtles are drawing on. Do not alter the drawing window. To observe hidden parts of the canvas, use the scrollbars. With this method, one can make visible those parts of a drawing which were outside the canvas before.
turtle.screensize.name: turtle.screensize

turtle.seth.descr: Set the orientation of the turtle to to_angle. Here are some common directions in degrees:
turtle.seth.name: turtle.seth

turtle.setheading.descr: Set the orientation of the turtle to to_angle. Here are some common directions in degrees:
turtle.setheading.name: turtle.setheading

turtle.setpos.descr: If y is None, x must be a pair of coordinates or a Vec2D (e.g. as returned by pos()).
turtle.setpos.name: turtle.setpos

turtle.setposition.descr: If y is None, x must be a pair of coordinates or a Vec2D (e.g. as returned by pos()).
turtle.setposition.name: turtle.setposition

turtle.settiltangle.descr: Rotate the turtleshape to point in the direction specified by angle, regardless of its current tilt-angle. Do not change the turtle’s heading (direction of movement).
turtle.settiltangle.name: turtle.settiltangle

turtle.setundobuffer.descr: Set or disable undobuffer. If size is an integer an empty undobuffer of given size is installed. size gives the maximum number of turtle actions that can be undone by the undo() method/function. If size is None, the undobuffer is disabled.
turtle.setundobuffer.name: turtle.setundobuffer

turtle.setup.descr: Set the size and position of the main window. Default values of arguments are stored in the configuration dictionary and can be changed via a turtle.cfg file.
turtle.setup.name: turtle.setup

turtle.setworldcoordinates.descr: Set up user-defined coordinate system and switch to mode “world” if necessary. This performs a screen.reset(). If mode “world” is already active, all drawings are redrawn according to the new coordinates.
turtle.setworldcoordinates.name: turtle.setworldcoordinates

turtle.setx.descr: Set the turtle’s first coordinate to x, leave second coordinate unchanged.
turtle.setx.name: turtle.setx

turtle.sety.descr: Set the turtle’s second coordinate to y, leave first coordinate unchanged.
turtle.sety.name: turtle.sety

turtle.shape.descr: Set turtle shape to shape with given name or, if name is not given, return name of current shape. Shape with name must exist in the TurtleScreen’s shape dictionary. Initially there are the following polygon shapes: “arrow”, “turtle”, “circle”, “square”, “triangle”, “classic”. To learn about how to deal with shapes see Screen method register_shape().
turtle.shape.name: turtle.shape

turtle.shapesize.descr: Return or set the pen’s attributes x/y-stretchfactors and/or outline. Set resizemode to “user”. If and only if resizemode is set to “user”, the turtle will be displayed stretched according to its stretchfactors: stretch_wid is stretchfactor perpendicular to its orientation, stretch_len is stretchfactor in direction of its orientation, outline determines the width of the shapes’s outline.
turtle.shapesize.name: turtle.shapesize

turtle.shapetransform.descr: Set or return the current transformation matrix of the turtle shape.
turtle.shapetransform.name: turtle.shapetransform

turtle.shearfactor.descr: Set or return the current shearfactor. Shear the turtleshape according to the given shearfactor shear, which is the tangent of the shear angle. Do not change the turtle’s heading (direction of movement). If shear is not given: return the current shearfactor, i. e. the tangent of the shear angle, by which lines parallel to the heading of the turtle are sheared.
turtle.shearfactor.name: turtle.shearfactor

turtle.speed.descr: Set the turtle’s speed to an integer value in the range 0..10. If no argument is given, return current speed.
turtle.speed.name: turtle.speed

turtle.stamp.descr: Stamp a copy of the turtle shape onto the canvas at the current turtle position. Return a stamp_id for that stamp, which can be used to delete it by calling clearstamp(stamp_id).
turtle.stamp.name: turtle.stamp

turtle.textinput.descr: Pop up a dialog window for input of a string. Parameter title is the title of the dialog window, propmt is a text mostly describing what information to input. Return the string input. If the dialog is canceled, return None.
turtle.textinput.name: turtle.textinput

turtle.tilt.descr: Rotate the turtleshape by angle from its current tilt-angle, but do not change the turtle’s heading (direction of movement).
turtle.tilt.name: turtle.tilt

turtle.tiltangle.descr: Set or return the current tilt-angle. If angle is given, rotate the turtleshape to point in the direction specified by angle, regardless of its current tilt-angle. Do not change the turtle’s heading (direction of movement). If angle is not given: return the current tilt-angle, i. e. the angle between the orientation of the turtleshape and the heading of the turtle (its direction of movement).
turtle.tiltangle.name: turtle.tiltangle

turtle.title.descr: Set title of turtle window to titlestring.
turtle.title.name: turtle.title

turtle.towards.descr: Return the angle between the line from turtle position to position specified by (x,y), the vector or the other turtle. This depends on the turtle’s start orientation which depends on the mode - “standard”/”world” or “logo”).
turtle.towards.name: turtle.towards

turtle.tracer.descr: Turn turtle animation on/off and set delay for update drawings. If n is given, only each n-th regular screen update is really performed. (Can be used to accelerate the drawing of complex graphics.) When called without arguments, returns the currently stored value of n. Second argument sets delay value (see delay()).
turtle.tracer.name: turtle.tracer

turtle.turtles.descr: Return the list of turtles on the screen.
turtle.turtles.name: turtle.turtles

turtle.turtlesize.descr: Return or set the pen’s attributes x/y-stretchfactors and/or outline. Set resizemode to “user”. If and only if resizemode is set to “user”, the turtle will be displayed stretched according to its stretchfactors: stretch_wid is stretchfactor perpendicular to its orientation, stretch_len is stretchfactor in direction of its orientation, outline determines the width of the shapes’s outline.
turtle.turtlesize.name: turtle.turtlesize

turtle.undo.descr: Undo (repeatedly) the last turtle action(s). Number of available undo actions is determined by the size of the undobuffer.
turtle.undo.name: turtle.undo

turtle.undobufferentries.descr: Return number of entries in the undobuffer.
turtle.undobufferentries.name: turtle.undobufferentries

turtle.up.descr: Pull the pen up – no drawing when moving.
turtle.up.name: turtle.up

turtle.update.descr: Perform a TurtleScreen update. To be used when tracer is turned off.
turtle.update.name: turtle.update

turtle.width.descr: Set the line thickness to width or return it. If resizemode is set to “auto” and turtleshape is a polygon, that polygon is drawn with the same line thickness. If no argument is given, the current pensize is returned.
turtle.width.name: turtle.width

turtle.window_height.descr: Return the height of the turtle window.
turtle.window_height.name: turtle.window_height

turtle.window_width.descr: Return the width of the turtle window.
turtle.window_width.name: turtle.window_width

turtle.write.descr: Write text - the string representation of arg - at the current turtle position according to align (“left”, “center” or right”) and with the given font. If move is true, the pen is moved to the bottom-right corner of the text. By default, move is False.
turtle.write.name: turtle.write

turtle.write_docstringdict.descr: Create and write docstring-dictionary to a Python script with the given filename. This function has to be called explicitly (it is not used by the turtle graphics classes). The docstring dictionary will be written to the Python script filename.py. It is intended to serve as a template for translation of the docstrings into different languages.
turtle.write_docstringdict.name: turtle.write_docstringdict

type.descr: The isinstance() built-in function is recommended for testing the type of an object, because it takes subclasses into account.
type.name: type

typecode.descr: The typecode character used to create the array.
typecode.name: array.array.typecode

typecodes.descr: A string with all available type codes.
typecodes.name: array.typecodes

types.BuiltinFunctionType.descr: The type of built-in functions like len() or sys.exit(), and methods of built-in classes. (Here, the term “built-in” means “written in C”.)
types.BuiltinFunctionType.name: types.BuiltinFunctionType

types.BuiltinMethodType.descr: The type of built-in functions like len() or sys.exit(), and methods of built-in classes. (Here, the term “built-in” means “written in C”.)
types.BuiltinMethodType.name: types.BuiltinMethodType

types.FrameType.descr: The type of frame objects such as found in tb.tb_frame if tb is a traceback object.
types.FrameType.name: types.FrameType

types.FunctionType.descr: The type of user-defined functions and functions created by lambda expressions.
types.FunctionType.name: types.FunctionType

types.GeneratorType.descr: The type of generator-iterator objects, produced by calling a generator function.
types.GeneratorType.name: types.GeneratorType

types.GetSetDescriptorType.descr: The type of objects defined in extension modules with PyGetSetDef, such as FrameType.f_locals or array.array.typecode. This type is used as descriptor for object attributes; it has the same purpose as the property type, but for classes defined in extension modules.
types.GetSetDescriptorType.name: types.GetSetDescriptorType

types.LambdaType.descr: The type of user-defined functions and functions created by lambda expressions.
types.LambdaType.name: types.LambdaType

types.MappingProxyType.descr: Read-only proxy of a mapping. It provides a dynamic view on the mapping’s entries, which means that when the mapping changes, the view reflects these changes.
types.MappingProxyType.name: types.MappingProxyType

types.MappingProxyType.copy.descr: Return a shallow copy of the underlying mapping.
types.MappingProxyType.copy.name: types.MappingProxyType.copy

types.MappingProxyType.get.descr: Return the value for key if key is in the underlying mapping, else default. If default is not given, it defaults to None, so that this method never raises a KeyError.
types.MappingProxyType.get.name: types.MappingProxyType.get

types.MappingProxyType.items.descr: Return a new view of the underlying mapping’s items ((key, value) pairs).
types.MappingProxyType.items.name: types.MappingProxyType.items

types.MappingProxyType.keys.descr: Return a new view of the underlying mapping’s keys.
types.MappingProxyType.keys.name: types.MappingProxyType.keys

types.MappingProxyType.values.descr: Return a new view of the underlying mapping’s values.
types.MappingProxyType.values.name: types.MappingProxyType.values

types.MemberDescriptorType.descr: The type of objects defined in extension modules with PyMemberDef, such as datetime.timedelta.days. This type is used as descriptor for simple C data members which use standard conversion functions; it has the same purpose as the property type, but for classes defined in extension modules.
types.MemberDescriptorType.name: types.MemberDescriptorType

types.MethodType.descr: The type of methods of user-defined class instances.
types.MethodType.name: types.MethodType

types.SimpleNamespace.descr: A simple object subclass that provides attribute access to its namespace, as well as a meaningful repr.
types.SimpleNamespace.name: types.SimpleNamespace

types.TracebackType.descr: The type of traceback objects such as found in sys.exc_info()[2].
types.TracebackType.name: types.TracebackType

types.new_class.descr: Creates a class object dynamically using the appropriate metaclass.
types.new_class.name: types.new_class

types.prepare_class.descr: Calculates the appropriate metaclass and creates the class namespace.
types.prepare_class.name: types.prepare_class

unicodedata.bidirectional.descr: Returns the bidirectional class assigned to the character chr as string. If no such value is defined, an empty string is returned.
unicodedata.bidirectional.name: unicodedata.bidirectional

unicodedata.category.descr: Returns the general category assigned to the character chr as string.
unicodedata.category.name: unicodedata.category

unicodedata.combining.descr: Returns the canonical combining class assigned to the character chr as integer. Returns 0 if no combining class is defined.
unicodedata.combining.name: unicodedata.combining

unicodedata.decimal.descr: Returns the decimal value assigned to the character chr as integer. If no such value is defined, default is returned, or, if not given, ValueError is raised.
unicodedata.decimal.name: unicodedata.decimal

unicodedata.decomposition.descr: Returns the character decomposition mapping assigned to the character chr as string. An empty string is returned in case no such mapping is defined.
unicodedata.decomposition.name: unicodedata.decomposition

unicodedata.digit.descr: Returns the digit value assigned to the character chr as integer. If no such value is defined, default is returned, or, if not given, ValueError is raised.
unicodedata.digit.name: unicodedata.digit

unicodedata.east_asian_width.descr: Returns the east asian width assigned to the character chr as string.
unicodedata.east_asian_width.name: unicodedata.east_asian_width

unicodedata.lookup.descr: Look up character by name. If a character with the given name is found, return the corresponding character. If not found, KeyError is raised.
unicodedata.lookup.name: unicodedata.lookup

unicodedata.mirrored.descr: Returns the mirrored property assigned to the character chr as integer. Returns 1 if the character has been identified as a “mirrored” character in bidirectional text, 0 otherwise.
unicodedata.mirrored.name: unicodedata.mirrored

unicodedata.name.descr: Returns the name assigned to the character chr as a string. If no name is defined, default is returned, or, if not given, ValueError is raised.
unicodedata.name.name: unicodedata.name

unicodedata.normalize.descr: Return the normal form form for the Unicode string unistr. Valid values for form are ‘NFC’, ‘NFKC’, ‘NFD’, and ‘NFKD’.
unicodedata.normalize.name: unicodedata.normalize

unicodedata.numeric.descr: Returns the numeric value assigned to the character chr as float. If no such value is defined, default is returned, or, if not given, ValueError is raised.
unicodedata.numeric.name: unicodedata.numeric

unicodedata.ucd_3_2_0.descr: This is an object that has the same methods as the entire module, but uses the Unicode database version 3.2 instead, for applications that require this specific version of the Unicode database (such as IDNA).
unicodedata.ucd_3_2_0.name: unicodedata.ucd_3_2_0

unicodedata.unidata_version.descr: The version of the Unicode database used in this module.
unicodedata.unidata_version.name: unicodedata.unidata_version

unittest.FunctionTestCase.descr: This class implements the portion of the TestCase interface which allows the test runner to drive the test, but does not provide the methods which test code can use to check and report errors. This is used to create test cases using legacy test code, allowing it to be integrated into a unittest-based test framework.
unittest.FunctionTestCase.name: unittest.FunctionTestCase

unittest.SkipTest.descr: This exception is raised to skip a test.
unittest.SkipTest.name: unittest.SkipTest

unittest.TestCase.descr: Instances of the TestCase class represent the logical test units in the unittest universe. This class is intended to be used as a base class, with specific tests being implemented by concrete subclasses. This class implements the interface needed by the test runner to allow it to drive the tests, and methods that the test code can use to check for and report various kinds of failure.
unittest.TestCase.name: unittest.TestCase

unittest.TestCase.addCleanup.descr: Add a function to be called after tearDown() to cleanup resources used during the test. Functions will be called in reverse order to the order they are added (LIFO). They are called with any arguments and keyword arguments passed into addCleanup() when they are added.
unittest.TestCase.addCleanup.name: unittest.TestCase.addCleanup

unittest.TestCase.addTypeEqualityFunc.descr: Registers a type-specific method called by assertEqual() to check if two objects of exactly the same typeobj (not subclasses) compare equal. function must take two positional arguments and a third msg=None keyword argument just as assertEqual() does. It must raise self.failureException(msg) when inequality between the first two parameters is detected – possibly providing useful information and explaining the inequalities in details in the error message.
unittest.TestCase.addTypeEqualityFunc.name: unittest.TestCase.addTypeEqualityFunc

unittest.TestCase.assertAlmostEqual.descr: Test that first and second are approximately (or not approximately) equal by computing the difference, rounding to the given number of decimal places (default 7), and comparing to zero. Note that these methods round the values to the given number of decimal places (i.e. like the round() function) and not significant digits.
unittest.TestCase.assertAlmostEqual.name: unittest.TestCase.assertAlmostEqual

unittest.TestCase.assertCountEqual.descr: Test that sequence first contains the same elements as second, regardless of their order. When they don’t, an error message listing the differences between the sequences will be generated.
unittest.TestCase.assertCountEqual.name: unittest.TestCase.assertCountEqual

unittest.TestCase.assertDictEqual.descr: Test that two dictionaries are equal. If not, an error message is constructed that shows the differences in the dictionaries. This method will be used by default to compare dictionaries in calls to assertEqual().
unittest.TestCase.assertDictEqual.name: unittest.TestCase.assertDictEqual

unittest.TestCase.assertEqual.descr: Test that first and second are equal. If the values do not compare equal, the test will fail.
unittest.TestCase.assertEqual.name: unittest.TestCase.assertEqual

unittest.TestCase.assertFalse.descr: Test that expr is true (or false).
unittest.TestCase.assertFalse.name: unittest.TestCase.assertFalse

unittest.TestCase.assertGreater.descr: Test that first is respectively >, >=, < or <= than second depending on the method name. If not, the test will fail:
unittest.TestCase.assertGreater.name: unittest.TestCase.assertGreater

unittest.TestCase.assertGreaterEqual.descr: Test that first is respectively >, >=, < or <= than second depending on the method name. If not, the test will fail:
unittest.TestCase.assertGreaterEqual.name: unittest.TestCase.assertGreaterEqual

unittest.TestCase.assertIn.descr: Test that first is (or is not) in second.
unittest.TestCase.assertIn.name: unittest.TestCase.assertIn

unittest.TestCase.assertIs.descr: Test that first and second evaluate (or don’t evaluate) to the same object.
unittest.TestCase.assertIs.name: unittest.TestCase.assertIs

unittest.TestCase.assertIsInstance.descr: Test that obj is (or is not) an instance of cls (which can be a class or a tuple of classes, as supported by isinstance()). To check for the exact type, use assertIs(type(obj), cls).
unittest.TestCase.assertIsInstance.name: unittest.TestCase.assertIsInstance

unittest.TestCase.assertIsNone.descr: Test that expr is (or is not) None.
unittest.TestCase.assertIsNone.name: unittest.TestCase.assertIsNone

unittest.TestCase.assertIsNot.descr: Test that first and second evaluate (or don’t evaluate) to the same object.
unittest.TestCase.assertIsNot.name: unittest.TestCase.assertIsNot

unittest.TestCase.assertIsNotNone.descr: Test that expr is (or is not) None.
unittest.TestCase.assertIsNotNone.name: unittest.TestCase.assertIsNotNone

unittest.TestCase.assertLess.descr: Test that first is respectively >, >=, < or <= than second depending on the method name. If not, the test will fail:
unittest.TestCase.assertLess.name: unittest.TestCase.assertLess

unittest.TestCase.assertLessEqual.descr: Test that first is respectively >, >=, < or <= than second depending on the method name. If not, the test will fail:
unittest.TestCase.assertLessEqual.name: unittest.TestCase.assertLessEqual

unittest.TestCase.assertListEqual.descr: Tests that two lists or tuples are equal. If not, an error message is constructed that shows only the differences between the two. An error is also raised if either of the parameters are of the wrong type. These methods are used by default when comparing lists or tuples with assertEqual().
unittest.TestCase.assertListEqual.name: unittest.TestCase.assertListEqual

unittest.TestCase.assertMultiLineEqual.descr: Test that the multiline string first is equal to the string second. When not equal a diff of the two strings highlighting the differences will be included in the error message. This method is used by default when comparing strings with assertEqual().
unittest.TestCase.assertMultiLineEqual.name: unittest.TestCase.assertMultiLineEqual

unittest.TestCase.assertNotAlmostEqual.descr: Test that first and second are approximately (or not approximately) equal by computing the difference, rounding to the given number of decimal places (default 7), and comparing to zero. Note that these methods round the values to the given number of decimal places (i.e. like the round() function) and not significant digits.
unittest.TestCase.assertNotAlmostEqual.name: unittest.TestCase.assertNotAlmostEqual

unittest.TestCase.assertNotEqual.descr: Test that first and second are not equal. If the values do compare equal, the test will fail.
unittest.TestCase.assertNotEqual.name: unittest.TestCase.assertNotEqual

unittest.TestCase.assertNotIn.descr: Test that first is (or is not) in second.
unittest.TestCase.assertNotIn.name: unittest.TestCase.assertNotIn

unittest.TestCase.assertNotIsInstance.descr: Test that obj is (or is not) an instance of cls (which can be a class or a tuple of classes, as supported by isinstance()). To check for the exact type, use assertIs(type(obj), cls).
unittest.TestCase.assertNotIsInstance.name: unittest.TestCase.assertNotIsInstance

unittest.TestCase.assertNotRegex.descr: Test that a regex search matches (or does not match) text. In case of failure, the error message will include the pattern and the text (or the pattern and the part of text that unexpectedly matched). regex may be a regular expression object or a string containing a regular expression suitable for use by re.search().
unittest.TestCase.assertNotRegex.name: unittest.TestCase.assertNotRegex

unittest.TestCase.assertRaises.descr: Test that an exception is raised when callable is called with any positional or keyword arguments that are also passed to assertRaises(). The test passes if exception is raised, is an error if another exception is raised, or fails if no exception is raised. To catch any of a group of exceptions, a tuple containing the exception classes may be passed as exception.
unittest.TestCase.assertRaises.name: unittest.TestCase.assertRaises

unittest.TestCase.assertRaisesRegex.descr: Like assertRaises() but also tests that regex matches on the string representation of the raised exception. regex may be a regular expression object or a string containing a regular expression suitable for use by re.search(). Examples:
unittest.TestCase.assertRaisesRegex.name: unittest.TestCase.assertRaisesRegex

unittest.TestCase.assertRegex.descr: Test that a regex search matches (or does not match) text. In case of failure, the error message will include the pattern and the text (or the pattern and the part of text that unexpectedly matched). regex may be a regular expression object or a string containing a regular expression suitable for use by re.search().
unittest.TestCase.assertRegex.name: unittest.TestCase.assertRegex

unittest.TestCase.assertSequenceEqual.descr: Tests that two sequences are equal. If a seq_type is supplied, both first and second must be instances of seq_type or a failure will be raised. If the sequences are different an error message is constructed that shows the difference between the two.
unittest.TestCase.assertSequenceEqual.name: unittest.TestCase.assertSequenceEqual

unittest.TestCase.assertSetEqual.descr: Tests that two sets are equal. If not, an error message is constructed that lists the differences between the sets. This method is used by default when comparing sets or frozensets with assertEqual().
unittest.TestCase.assertSetEqual.name: unittest.TestCase.assertSetEqual

unittest.TestCase.assertTrue.descr: Test that expr is true (or false).
unittest.TestCase.assertTrue.name: unittest.TestCase.assertTrue

unittest.TestCase.assertTupleEqual.descr: Tests that two lists or tuples are equal. If not, an error message is constructed that shows only the differences between the two. An error is also raised if either of the parameters are of the wrong type. These methods are used by default when comparing lists or tuples with assertEqual().
unittest.TestCase.assertTupleEqual.name: unittest.TestCase.assertTupleEqual

unittest.TestCase.assertWarns.descr: Test that a warning is triggered when callable is called with any positional or keyword arguments that are also passed to assertWarns(). The test passes if warning is triggered and fails if it isn’t. Any exception is an error. To catch any of a group of warnings, a tuple containing the warning classes may be passed as warnings.
unittest.TestCase.assertWarns.name: unittest.TestCase.assertWarns

unittest.TestCase.assertWarnsRegex.descr: Like assertWarns() but also tests that regex matches on the message of the triggered warning. regex may be a regular expression object or a string containing a regular expression suitable for use by re.search(). Example:
unittest.TestCase.assertWarnsRegex.name: unittest.TestCase.assertWarnsRegex

unittest.TestCase.countTestCases.descr: Return the number of tests represented by this test object. For TestCase instances, this will always be 1.
unittest.TestCase.countTestCases.name: unittest.TestCase.countTestCases

unittest.TestCase.debug.descr: Run the test without collecting the result. This allows exceptions raised by the test to be propagated to the caller, and can be used to support running tests under a debugger.
unittest.TestCase.debug.name: unittest.TestCase.debug

unittest.TestCase.defaultTestResult.descr: Return an instance of the test result class that should be used for this test case class (if no other result instance is provided to the run() method).
unittest.TestCase.defaultTestResult.name: unittest.TestCase.defaultTestResult

unittest.TestCase.doCleanups.descr: This method is called unconditionally after tearDown(), or after setUp() if setUp() raises an exception.
unittest.TestCase.doCleanups.name: unittest.TestCase.doCleanups

unittest.TestCase.fail.descr: Signals a test failure unconditionally, with msg or None for the error message.
unittest.TestCase.fail.name: unittest.TestCase.fail

unittest.TestCase.failureException.descr: This class attribute gives the exception raised by the test method. If a test framework needs to use a specialized exception, possibly to carry additional information, it must subclass this exception in order to “play fair” with the framework. The initial value of this attribute is AssertionError.
unittest.TestCase.failureException.name: unittest.TestCase.failureException

unittest.TestCase.id.descr: Return a string identifying the specific test case. This is usually the full name of the test method, including the module and class name.
unittest.TestCase.id.name: unittest.TestCase.id

unittest.TestCase.longMessage.descr: If set to True then any explicit failure message you pass in to the assert methods will be appended to the end of the normal failure message. The normal messages contain useful information about the objects involved, for example the message from assertEqual shows you the repr of the two unequal objects. Setting this attribute to True allows you to have a custom error message in addition to the normal one.
unittest.TestCase.longMessage.name: unittest.TestCase.longMessage

unittest.TestCase.maxDiff.descr: This attribute controls the maximum length of diffs output by assert methods that report diffs on failure. It defaults to 80*8 characters. Assert methods affected by this attribute are assertSequenceEqual() (including all the sequence comparison methods that delegate to it), assertDictEqual() and assertMultiLineEqual().
unittest.TestCase.maxDiff.name: unittest.TestCase.maxDiff

unittest.TestCase.run.descr: Run the test, collecting the result into the TestResult object passed as result. If result is omitted or None, a temporary result object is created (by calling the defaultTestResult() method) and used. The result object is returned to run()‘s caller.
unittest.TestCase.run.name: unittest.TestCase.run

unittest.TestCase.setUp.descr: Method called to prepare the test fixture. This is called immediately before calling the test method; any exception raised by this method will be considered an error rather than a test failure. The default implementation does nothing.
unittest.TestCase.setUp.name: unittest.TestCase.setUp

unittest.TestCase.setUpClass.descr: A class method called before tests in an individual class run. setUpClass is called with the class as the only argument and must be decorated as a classmethod():
unittest.TestCase.setUpClass.name: unittest.TestCase.setUpClass

unittest.TestCase.shortDescription.descr: Returns a description of the test, or None if no description has been provided. The default implementation of this method returns the first line of the test method’s docstring, if available, or None.
unittest.TestCase.shortDescription.name: unittest.TestCase.shortDescription

unittest.TestCase.skipTest.descr: Calling this during a test method or setUp() skips the current test. See Skipping tests and expected failures for more information.
unittest.TestCase.skipTest.name: unittest.TestCase.skipTest

unittest.TestCase.tearDown.descr: Method called immediately after the test method has been called and the result recorded. This is called even if the test method raised an exception, so the implementation in subclasses may need to be particularly careful about checking internal state. Any exception raised by this method will be considered an error rather than a test failure. This method will only be called if the setUp() succeeds, regardless of the outcome of the test method. The default implementation does nothing.
unittest.TestCase.tearDown.name: unittest.TestCase.tearDown

unittest.TestCase.tearDownClass.descr: A class method called after tests in an individual class have run. tearDownClass is called with the class as the only argument and must be decorated as a classmethod():
unittest.TestCase.tearDownClass.name: unittest.TestCase.tearDownClass

unittest.TestLoader.descr: The TestLoader class is used to create test suites from classes and modules. Normally, there is no need to create an instance of this class; the unittest module provides an instance that can be shared as unittest.defaultTestLoader. Using a subclass or instance, however, allows customization of some configurable properties.
unittest.TestLoader.name: unittest.TestLoader

unittest.TestLoader.discover.descr: Find and return all test modules from the specified start directory, recursing into subdirectories to find them. Only test files that match pattern will be loaded. (Using shell style pattern matching.) Only module names that are importable (i.e. are valid Python identifiers) will be loaded.
unittest.TestLoader.discover.name: unittest.TestLoader.discover

unittest.TestLoader.getTestCaseNames.descr: Return a sorted sequence of method names found within testCaseClass; this should be a subclass of TestCase.
unittest.TestLoader.getTestCaseNames.name: unittest.TestLoader.getTestCaseNames

unittest.TestLoader.loadTestsFromModule.descr: Return a suite of all tests cases contained in the given module. This method searches module for classes derived from TestCase and creates an instance of the class for each test method defined for the class.
unittest.TestLoader.loadTestsFromModule.name: unittest.TestLoader.loadTestsFromModule

unittest.TestLoader.loadTestsFromName.descr: Return a suite of all tests cases given a string specifier.
unittest.TestLoader.loadTestsFromName.name: unittest.TestLoader.loadTestsFromName

unittest.TestLoader.loadTestsFromNames.descr: Similar to loadTestsFromName(), but takes a sequence of names rather than a single name. The return value is a test suite which supports all the tests defined for each name.
unittest.TestLoader.loadTestsFromNames.name: unittest.TestLoader.loadTestsFromNames

unittest.TestLoader.loadTestsFromTestCas.descr: Return a suite of all tests cases contained in the TestCase-derived testCaseClass.
unittest.TestLoader.loadTestsFromTestCas.name: unittest.TestLoader.loadTestsFromTestCase

unittest.TestLoader.sortTestMethodsUsing.descr: Function to be used to compare method names when sorting them in getTestCaseNames() and all the loadTestsFrom*() methods.
unittest.TestLoader.sortTestMethodsUsing.name: unittest.TestLoader.sortTestMethodsUsing

unittest.TestLoader.suiteClass.descr: Callable object that constructs a test suite from a list of tests. No methods on the resulting object are needed. The default value is the TestSuite class.
unittest.TestLoader.suiteClass.name: unittest.TestLoader.suiteClass

unittest.TestLoader.testMethodPrefix.descr: String giving the prefix of method names which will be interpreted as test methods. The default value is 'test'.
unittest.TestLoader.testMethodPrefix.name: unittest.TestLoader.testMethodPrefix

unittest.TestResult.descr: This class is used to compile information about which tests have succeeded and which have failed.
unittest.TestResult.name: unittest.TestResult

unittest.TestResult.addError.descr: Called when the test case test raises an unexpected exception. err is a tuple of the form returned by sys.exc_info(): (type, value, traceback).
unittest.TestResult.addError.name: unittest.TestResult.addError

unittest.TestResult.addExpectedFailure.descr: Called when the test case test fails, but was marked with the expectedFailure() decorator.
unittest.TestResult.addExpectedFailure.name: unittest.TestResult.addExpectedFailure

unittest.TestResult.addFailure.descr: Called when the test case test signals a failure. err is a tuple of the form returned by sys.exc_info(): (type, value, traceback).
unittest.TestResult.addFailure.name: unittest.TestResult.addFailure

unittest.TestResult.addSkip.descr: Called when the test case test is skipped. reason is the reason the test gave for skipping.
unittest.TestResult.addSkip.name: unittest.TestResult.addSkip

unittest.TestResult.addSuccess.descr: Called when the test case test succeeds.
unittest.TestResult.addSuccess.name: unittest.TestResult.addSuccess

unittest.TestResult.addUnexpectedSuccess.descr: Called when the test case test was marked with the expectedFailure() decorator, but succeeded.
unittest.TestResult.addUnexpectedSuccess.name: unittest.TestResult.addUnexpectedSuccess

unittest.TestResult.buffer.descr: If set to true, sys.stdout and sys.stderr will be buffered in between startTest() and stopTest() being called. Collected output will only be echoed onto the real sys.stdout and sys.stderr if the test fails or errors. Any output is also attached to the failure / error message.
unittest.TestResult.buffer.name: unittest.TestResult.buffer

unittest.TestResult.errors.descr: A list containing 2-tuples of TestCase instances and strings holding formatted tracebacks. Each tuple represents a test which raised an unexpected exception.
unittest.TestResult.errors.name: unittest.TestResult.errors

unittest.TestResult.expectedFailures.descr: A list containing 2-tuples of TestCase instances and strings holding formatted tracebacks. Each tuple represents an expected failure of the test case.
unittest.TestResult.expectedFailures.name: unittest.TestResult.expectedFailures

unittest.TestResult.failfast.descr: If set to true stop() will be called on the first failure or error, halting the test run.
unittest.TestResult.failfast.name: unittest.TestResult.failfast

unittest.TestResult.failures.descr: A list containing 2-tuples of TestCase instances and strings holding formatted tracebacks. Each tuple represents a test where a failure was explicitly signalled using the TestCase.assert*() methods.
unittest.TestResult.failures.name: unittest.TestResult.failures

unittest.TestResult.shouldStop.descr: Set to True when the execution of tests should stop by stop().
unittest.TestResult.shouldStop.name: unittest.TestResult.shouldStop

unittest.TestResult.skipped.descr: A list containing 2-tuples of TestCase instances and strings holding the reason for skipping the test.
unittest.TestResult.skipped.name: unittest.TestResult.skipped

unittest.TestResult.startTest.descr: Called when the test case test is about to be run.
unittest.TestResult.startTest.name: unittest.TestResult.startTest

unittest.TestResult.startTestRun.descr: Called once before any tests are executed.
unittest.TestResult.startTestRun.name: unittest.TestResult.startTestRun

unittest.TestResult.stop.descr: This method can be called to signal that the set of tests being run should be aborted by setting the shouldStop attribute to True. TestRunner objects should respect this flag and return without running any additional tests.
unittest.TestResult.stop.name: unittest.TestResult.stop

unittest.TestResult.stopTest.descr: Called after the test case test has been executed, regardless of the outcome.
