unittest.TestResult.stopTest.name: unittest.TestResult.stopTest

unittest.TestResult.stopTestRun.descr: Called once after all tests are executed.
unittest.TestResult.stopTestRun.name: unittest.TestResult.stopTestRun

unittest.TestResult.testsRun.descr: The total number of tests run so far.
unittest.TestResult.testsRun.name: unittest.TestResult.testsRun

unittest.TestResult.unexpectedSuccesses.descr: A list containing TestCase instances that were marked as expected failures, but succeeded.
unittest.TestResult.unexpectedSuccesses.name: unittest.TestResult.unexpectedSuccesses

unittest.TestResult.wasSuccessful.descr: Return True if all tests run so far have passed, otherwise returns False.
unittest.TestResult.wasSuccessful.name: unittest.TestResult.wasSuccessful

unittest.TestSuite.descr: This class represents an aggregation of individual tests cases and test suites. The class presents the interface needed by the test runner to allow it to be run as any other test case. Running a TestSuite instance is the same as iterating over the suite, running each test individually.
unittest.TestSuite.name: unittest.TestSuite

unittest.TestSuite.__iter__.descr: Tests grouped by a TestSuite are always accessed by iteration. Subclasses can lazily provide tests by overriding __iter__(). Note that this method maybe called several times on a single suite (for example when counting tests or comparing for equality) so the tests returned must be the same for repeated iterations.
unittest.TestSuite.__iter__.name: unittest.TestSuite.__iter__

unittest.TestSuite.addTest.descr: Add a TestCase or TestSuite to the suite.
unittest.TestSuite.addTest.name: unittest.TestSuite.addTest

unittest.TestSuite.addTests.descr: Add all the tests from an iterable of TestCase and TestSuite instances to this test suite.
unittest.TestSuite.addTests.name: unittest.TestSuite.addTests

unittest.TestSuite.countTestCases.descr: Return the number of tests represented by this test object, including all individual tests and sub-suites.
unittest.TestSuite.countTestCases.name: unittest.TestSuite.countTestCases

unittest.TestSuite.debug.descr: Run the tests associated with this suite without collecting the result. This allows exceptions raised by the test to be propagated to the caller and can be used to support running tests under a debugger.
unittest.TestSuite.debug.name: unittest.TestSuite.debug

unittest.TestSuite.run.descr: Run the tests associated with this suite, collecting the result into the test result object passed as result. Note that unlike TestCase.run(), TestSuite.run() requires the result object to be passed in.
unittest.TestSuite.run.name: unittest.TestSuite.run

unittest.TextTestResult.descr: A concrete implementation of TestResult used by the TextTestRunner.
unittest.TextTestResult.name: unittest.TextTestResult

unittest.TextTestRunner.descr: A basic test runner implementation that outputs results to a stream. If stream is None, the default, sys.stderr is used as the output stream. This class has a few configurable parameters, but is essentially very simple. Graphical applications which run test suites should provide alternate implementations.
unittest.TextTestRunner.name: unittest.TextTestRunner
unittest.TextTestRunner.syntax: class unittest.TextTestRunner(stream=None, descriptions=True, verbosity=1, failfast=False, buffer=False, resultclass=None, warnings=None)

unittest.TextTestRunner._makeResult.descr: This method returns the instance of TestResult used by run(). It is not intended to be called directly, but can be overridden in subclasses to provide a custom TestResult.
unittest.TextTestRunner._makeResult.name: unittest.TextTestRunner._makeResult

unittest.defaultTestLoader.descr: Instance of the TestLoader class intended to be shared. If no customization of the TestLoader is needed, this instance can be used instead of repeatedly creating new instances.
unittest.defaultTestLoader.name: unittest.defaultTestLoader

unittest.expectedFailure.descr: Mark the test as an expected failure. If the test fails when run, the test is not counted as a failure.
unittest.expectedFailure.name: unittest.expectedFailure

unittest.installHandler.descr: Install the control-c handler. When a signal.SIGINT is received (usually in response to the user pressing control-c) all registered results have stop() called.
unittest.installHandler.name: unittest.installHandler

unittest.main.descr: A command-line program that loads a set of tests from module and runs them; this is primarily for making test modules conveniently executable. The simplest use for this function is to include the following line at the end of a test script:
unittest.main.name: unittest.main
unittest.main.syntax: unittest.main(module='__main__', defaultTest=None, argv=None, testRunner=None, testLoader=unittest.defaultTestLoader, exit=True, verbosity=1, failfast=None, catchbreak=None, buffer=None, warnings=None)

unittest.mock.MagicMock.descr: MagicMock is a subclass of Mock with default implementations of most of the magic methods. You can use MagicMock without having to configure the magic methods yourself.
unittest.mock.MagicMock.name: unittest.mock.MagicMock

unittest.mock.Mock.descr: Create a new Mock object. Mock takes several optional arguments that specify the behaviour of the Mock object:
unittest.mock.Mock.name: unittest.mock.Mock
unittest.mock.Mock.syntax: class unittest.mock.Mock(spec=None, side_effect=None, return_value=DEFAULT, wraps=None, name=None, spec_set=None, **kwargs)

unittest.mock.Mock.__class__.descr: Normally the __class__ attribute of an object will return its type. For a mock object with a spec __class__ returns the spec class instead. This allows mock objects to pass isinstance tests for the object they are replacing / masquerading as:
unittest.mock.Mock.__class__.name: unittest.mock.Mock.__class__

unittest.mock.Mock.__dir__.descr: Mock objects limit the results of dir(some_mock) to useful results. For mocks with a spec this includes all the permitted attributes for the mock.
unittest.mock.Mock.__dir__.name: unittest.mock.Mock.__dir__

unittest.mock.Mock._get_child_mock.descr: Create the child mocks for attributes and return value. By default child mocks will be the same type as the parent. Subclasses of Mock may want to override this to customize the way child mocks are made.
unittest.mock.Mock._get_child_mock.name: unittest.mock.Mock._get_child_mock

unittest.mock.Mock.assert_any_call.descr: assert the mock has been called with the specified arguments.
unittest.mock.Mock.assert_any_call.name: unittest.mock.Mock.assert_any_call

unittest.mock.Mock.assert_called_once_wi.descr: Assert that the mock was called exactly once and with the specified arguments.
unittest.mock.Mock.assert_called_once_wi.name: unittest.mock.Mock.assert_called_once_with

unittest.mock.Mock.assert_called_with.descr: This method is a convenient way of asserting that calls are made in a particular way:
unittest.mock.Mock.assert_called_with.name: unittest.mock.Mock.assert_called_with

unittest.mock.Mock.assert_has_calls.descr: assert the mock has been called with the specified calls. The mock_calls list is checked for the calls.
unittest.mock.Mock.assert_has_calls.name: unittest.mock.Mock.assert_has_calls

unittest.mock.Mock.attach_mock.descr: Attach a mock as an attribute of this one, replacing its name and parent. Calls to the attached mock will be recorded in the method_calls and mock_calls attributes of this one.
unittest.mock.Mock.attach_mock.name: unittest.mock.Mock.attach_mock

unittest.mock.Mock.call_args.descr: This is either None (if the mock hasn’t been called), or the arguments that the mock was last called with. This will be in the form of a tuple: the first member is any ordered arguments the mock was called with (or an empty tuple) and the second member is any keyword arguments (or an empty dictionary).
unittest.mock.Mock.call_args.name: unittest.mock.Mock.call_args

unittest.mock.Mock.call_args_list.descr: This is a list of all the calls made to the mock object in sequence (so the length of the list is the number of times it has been called). Before any calls have been made it is an empty list. The call object can be used for conveniently constructing lists of calls to compare with call_args_list.
unittest.mock.Mock.call_args_list.name: unittest.mock.Mock.call_args_list

unittest.mock.Mock.call_count.descr: An integer telling you how many times the mock object has been called:
unittest.mock.Mock.call_count.name: unittest.mock.Mock.call_count

unittest.mock.Mock.called.descr: A boolean representing whether or not the mock object has been called:
unittest.mock.Mock.called.name: unittest.mock.Mock.called

unittest.mock.Mock.configure_mock.descr: Set attributes on the mock through keyword arguments.
unittest.mock.Mock.configure_mock.name: unittest.mock.Mock.configure_mock

unittest.mock.Mock.method_calls.descr: As well as tracking calls to themselves, mocks also track calls to methods and attributes, and their methods and attributes:
unittest.mock.Mock.method_calls.name: unittest.mock.Mock.method_calls

unittest.mock.Mock.mock_add_spec.descr: Add a spec to a mock. spec can either be an object or a list of strings. Only attributes on the spec can be fetched as attributes from the mock.
unittest.mock.Mock.mock_add_spec.name: unittest.mock.Mock.mock_add_spec

unittest.mock.Mock.mock_calls.descr: mock_calls records all calls to the mock object, its methods, magic methods and return value mocks.
unittest.mock.Mock.mock_calls.name: unittest.mock.Mock.mock_calls

unittest.mock.Mock.reset_mock.descr: The reset_mock method resets all the call attributes on a mock object:
unittest.mock.Mock.reset_mock.name: unittest.mock.Mock.reset_mock

unittest.mock.Mock.return_value.descr: Set this to configure the value returned by calling the mock:
unittest.mock.Mock.return_value.name: unittest.mock.Mock.return_value

unittest.mock.Mock.side_effect.descr: This can either be a function to be called when the mock is called, or an exception (class or instance) to be raised.
unittest.mock.Mock.side_effect.name: unittest.mock.Mock.side_effect

unittest.mock.NonCallableMock.descr: A non-callable version of Mock. The constructor parameters have the same meaning of Mock, with the exception of return_value and side_effect which have no meaning on a non-callable mock.
unittest.mock.NonCallableMock.name: unittest.mock.NonCallableMock

unittest.mock.PropertyMock.descr: A mock intended to be used as a property, or other descriptor, on a class. PropertyMock provides __get__ and __set__ methods so you can specify a return value when it is fetched.
unittest.mock.PropertyMock.name: unittest.mock.PropertyMock

unittest.mock.call.descr: call is a helper object for making simpler assertions, for comparing with call_args, call_args_list, mock_calls and method_calls. call can also be used with assert_has_calls().
unittest.mock.call.name: unittest.mock.call

unittest.mock.call.call_list.descr: For a call object that represents multiple calls, call_list returns a list of all the intermediate calls as well as the final call.
unittest.mock.call.call_list.name: unittest.mock.call.call_list

unittest.mock.create_autospec.descr: Create a mock object using another object as a spec. Attributes on the mock will use the corresponding attribute on the spec object as their spec.
unittest.mock.create_autospec.name: unittest.mock.create_autospec

unittest.mock.mock_open.descr: A helper function to create a mock to replace the use of open. It works for open called directly or used as a context manager.
unittest.mock.mock_open.name: unittest.mock.mock_open

unittest.mock.patch.descr: patch acts as a function decorator, class decorator or a context manager. Inside the body of the function or with statement, the target is patched with a new object. When the function/with statement exits the patch is undone.
unittest.mock.patch.name: unittest.mock.patch
unittest.mock.patch.syntax: unittest.mock.patch(target, new=DEFAULT, spec=None, create=False, spec_set=None, autospec=None, new_callable=None, **kwargs)

unittest.mock.patch.dict.descr: Patch a dictionary, or dictionary like object, and restore the dictionary to its original state after the test.
unittest.mock.patch.dict.name: unittest.mock.patch.dict

unittest.mock.patch.multiple.descr: Perform multiple patches in a single call. It takes the object to be patched (either as an object or a string to fetch the object by importing) and keyword arguments for the patches:
unittest.mock.patch.multiple.name: unittest.mock.patch.multiple
unittest.mock.patch.multiple.syntax: patch.multiple(target, spec=None, create=False, spec_set=None, autospec=None, new_callable=None, **kwargs)

unittest.mock.patch.object.descr: patch the named member (attribute) on an object (target) with a mock object.
unittest.mock.patch.object.name: unittest.mock.patch.object
unittest.mock.patch.object.syntax: patch.object(target, attribute, new=DEFAULT, spec=None, create=False, spec_set=None, autospec=None, new_callable=None, **kwargs)

unittest.mock.patch.stopall.descr: Stop all active patches. Only stops patches started with start.
unittest.mock.patch.stopall.name: unittest.mock.patch.stopall

unittest.mock.sentinel.descr: The sentinel object provides a convenient way of providing unique objects for your tests.
unittest.mock.sentinel.name: unittest.mock.sentinel

unittest.registerResult.descr: Register a TestResult object for control-c handling. Registering a result stores a weak reference to it, so it doesn’t prevent the result from being garbage collected.
unittest.registerResult.name: unittest.registerResult

unittest.removeHandler.descr: When called without arguments this function removes the control-c handler if it has been installed. This function can also be used as a test decorator to temporarily remove the handler whilst the test is being executed:
unittest.removeHandler.name: unittest.removeHandler

unittest.removeResult.descr: Remove a registered result. Once a result has been removed then stop() will no longer be called on that result object in response to a control-c.
unittest.removeResult.name: unittest.removeResult

unittest.skip.descr: Unconditionally skip the decorated test. reason should describe why the test is being skipped.
unittest.skip.name: unittest.skip

unittest.skipIf.descr: Skip the decorated test if condition is true.
unittest.skipIf.name: unittest.skipIf

unittest.skipUnless.descr: Skip the decorated test unless condition is true.
unittest.skipUnless.name: unittest.skipUnless

update.descr: Update the dictionary with the key/value pairs from other, overwriting existing keys. Return None.
update.name: dict.update

upper.descr: Return a copy of the string with all the cased characters [4] converted to uppercase. Note that str.upper().isupper() might be False if s contains uncased characters or if the Unicode category of the resulting character(s) is not “Lu” (Letter, uppercase), but e.g. “Lt” (Letter, titlecase).
upper.name: str.upper

urllib.error.ContentTooShortError.descr: This exception is raised when the urlretrieve() function detects that the amount of the downloaded data is less than the expected amount (given by the Content-Length header). The content attribute stores the downloaded (and supposedly truncated) data.
urllib.error.ContentTooShortError.name: urllib.error.ContentTooShortError

urllib.error.HTTPError.descr: Though being an exception (a subclass of URLError), an HTTPError can also function as a non-exceptional file-like return value (the same thing that urlopen() returns). This is useful when handling exotic HTTP errors, such as requests for authentication.
urllib.error.HTTPError.name: urllib.error.HTTPError

urllib.error.HTTPError.code.descr: An HTTP status code as defined in RFC 2616. This numeric value corresponds to a value found in the dictionary of codes as found in http.server.BaseHTTPRequestHandler.responses.
urllib.error.HTTPError.code.name: urllib.error.HTTPError.code

urllib.error.HTTPError.reason.descr: This is usually a string explaining the reason for this error.
urllib.error.HTTPError.reason.name: urllib.error.HTTPError.reason

urllib.error.URLError.descr: The handlers raise this exception (or derived exceptions) when they run into a problem. It is a subclass of OSError.
urllib.error.URLError.name: urllib.error.URLError

urllib.error.URLError.reason.descr: The reason for this error. It can be a message string or another exception instance.
urllib.error.URLError.reason.name: urllib.error.URLError.reason

urllib.parse.DefragResult.descr: Concrete class for urldefrag() results containing str data. The encode() method returns a DefragResultBytes instance.
urllib.parse.DefragResult.name: urllib.parse.DefragResult

urllib.parse.DefragResultBytes.descr: Concrete class for urldefrag() results containing bytes data. The decode() method returns a DefragResult instance.
urllib.parse.DefragResultBytes.name: urllib.parse.DefragResultBytes

urllib.parse.ParseResult.descr: Concrete class for urlparse() results containing str data. The encode() method returns a ParseResultBytes instance.
urllib.parse.ParseResult.name: urllib.parse.ParseResult
urllib.parse.ParseResult.syntax: class urllib.parse.ParseResult(scheme, netloc, path, params, query, fragment)

urllib.parse.ParseResultBytes.descr: Concrete class for urlparse() results containing bytes data. The decode() method returns a ParseResult instance.
urllib.parse.ParseResultBytes.name: urllib.parse.ParseResultBytes
urllib.parse.ParseResultBytes.syntax: class urllib.parse.ParseResultBytes(scheme, netloc, path, params, query, fragment)

urllib.parse.SplitResult.descr: Concrete class for urlsplit() results containing str data. The encode() method returns a SplitResultBytes instance.
urllib.parse.SplitResult.name: urllib.parse.SplitResult
urllib.parse.SplitResult.syntax: class urllib.parse.SplitResult(scheme, netloc, path, query, fragment)

urllib.parse.SplitResultBytes.descr: Concrete class for urlsplit() results containing bytes data. The decode() method returns a SplitResult instance.
urllib.parse.SplitResultBytes.name: urllib.parse.SplitResultBytes
urllib.parse.SplitResultBytes.syntax: class urllib.parse.SplitResultBytes(scheme, netloc, path, query, fragment)

urllib.parse.parse_qs.descr: Parse a query string given as a string argument (data of type application/x-www-form-urlencoded). Data are returned as a dictionary. The dictionary keys are the unique query variable names and the values are lists of values for each name.
urllib.parse.parse_qs.name: urllib.parse.parse_qs

urllib.parse.parse_qsl.descr: Parse a query string given as a string argument (data of type application/x-www-form-urlencoded). Data are returned as a list of name, value pairs.
urllib.parse.parse_qsl.name: urllib.parse.parse_qsl

urllib.parse.quote.descr: Replace special characters in string using the %xx escape. Letters, digits, and the characters '_.-' are never quoted. By default, this function is intended for quoting the path section of URL. The optional safe parameter specifies additional ASCII characters that should not be quoted — its default value is '/'.
urllib.parse.quote.name: urllib.parse.quote

urllib.parse.quote_from_bytes.descr: Like quote(), but accepts a bytes object rather than a str, and does not perform string-to-bytes encoding.
urllib.parse.quote_from_bytes.name: urllib.parse.quote_from_bytes

urllib.parse.quote_plus.descr: Like quote(), but also replace spaces by plus signs, as required for quoting HTML form values when building up a query string to go into a URL. Plus signs in the original string are escaped unless they are included in safe. It also does not have safe default to '/'.
urllib.parse.quote_plus.name: urllib.parse.quote_plus

urllib.parse.unquote.descr: Replace %xx escapes by their single-character equivalent. The optional encoding and errors parameters specify how to decode percent-encoded sequences into Unicode characters, as accepted by the bytes.decode() method.
urllib.parse.unquote.name: urllib.parse.unquote

urllib.parse.unquote_plus.descr: Like unquote(), but also replace plus signs by spaces, as required for unquoting HTML form values.
urllib.parse.unquote_plus.name: urllib.parse.unquote_plus

urllib.parse.unquote_to_bytes.descr: Replace %xx escapes by their single-octet equivalent, and return a bytes object.
urllib.parse.unquote_to_bytes.name: urllib.parse.unquote_to_bytes

urllib.parse.urldefrag.descr: If url contains a fragment identifier, return a modified version of url with no fragment identifier, and the fragment identifier as a separate string. If there is no fragment identifier in url, return url unmodified and an empty string.
urllib.parse.urldefrag.name: urllib.parse.urldefrag

urllib.parse.urlencode.descr: Convert a mapping object or a sequence of two-element tuples, which may either be a str or a bytes, to a “percent-encoded” string. If the resultant string is to be used as a data for POST operation with urlopen() function, then it should be properly encoded to bytes, otherwise it would result in a TypeError.
urllib.parse.urlencode.name: urllib.parse.urlencode

urllib.parse.urljoin.descr: Construct a full (“absolute”) URL by combining a “base URL” (base) with another URL (url). Informally, this uses components of the base URL, in particular the addressing scheme, the network location and (part of) the path, to provide missing components in the relative URL. For example:
urllib.parse.urljoin.name: urllib.parse.urljoin

urllib.parse.urllib.parse.SplitResult.ge.descr: Return the re-combined version of the original URL as a string. This may differ from the original URL in that the scheme may be normalized to lower case and empty components may be dropped. Specifically, empty parameters, queries, and fragment identifiers will be removed.
urllib.parse.urllib.parse.SplitResult.ge.name: urllib.parse.urllib.parse.SplitResult.geturl

urllib.parse.urlparse.descr: Parse a URL into six components, returning a 6-tuple. This corresponds to the general structure of a URL: scheme://netloc/path;parameters?query#fragment. Each tuple item is a string, possibly empty. The components are not broken up in smaller parts (for example, the network location is a single string), and % escapes are not expanded. The delimiters as shown above are not part of the result, except for a leading slash in the path component, which is retained if present. For example:
urllib.parse.urlparse.name: urllib.parse.urlparse

urllib.parse.urlsplit.descr: This is similar to urlparse(), but does not split the params from the URL. This should generally be used instead of urlparse() if the more recent URL syntax allowing parameters to be applied to each segment of the path portion of the URL (see RFC 2396) is wanted. A separate function is needed to separate the path segments and parameters. This function returns a 5-tuple: (addressing scheme, network location, path, query, fragment identifier).
urllib.parse.urlsplit.name: urllib.parse.urlsplit

urllib.parse.urlunparse.descr: Construct a URL from a tuple as returned by urlparse(). The parts argument can be any six-item iterable. This may result in a slightly different, but equivalent URL, if the URL that was parsed originally had unnecessary delimiters (for example, a ? with an empty query; the RFC states that these are equivalent).
urllib.parse.urlunparse.name: urllib.parse.urlunparse

urllib.parse.urlunsplit.descr: Combine the elements of a tuple as returned by urlsplit() into a complete URL as a string. The parts argument can be any five-item iterable. This may result in a slightly different, but equivalent URL, if the URL that was parsed originally had unnecessary delimiters (for example, a ? with an empty query; the RFC states that these are equivalent).
urllib.parse.urlunsplit.name: urllib.parse.urlunsplit

urllib.request.AbstractBasicAuthHandler.descr: This is a mixin class that helps with HTTP authentication, both to the remote host and to a proxy. password_mgr, if given, should be something that is compatible with HTTPPasswordMgr; refer to section HTTPPasswordMgr Objects for information on the interface that must be supported.
urllib.request.AbstractBasicAuthHandler.name: urllib.request.AbstractBasicAuthHandler

urllib.request.AbstractBasicAuthHandler..descr: Handle an authentication request by getting a user/password pair, and re-trying the request. authreq should be the name of the header where the information about the realm is included in the request, host specifies the URL and path to authenticate for, req should be the (failed) Request object, and headers should be the error headers.
urllib.request.AbstractBasicAuthHandler..name: urllib.request.AbstractBasicAuthHandler.http_error_auth_reqed

urllib.request.AbstractDigestAuthHandler.descr: This is a mixin class that helps with HTTP authentication, both to the remote host and to a proxy. password_mgr, if given, should be something that is compatible with HTTPPasswordMgr; refer to section HTTPPasswordMgr Objects for information on the interface that must be supported.
urllib.request.AbstractDigestAuthHandler.name: urllib.request.AbstractDigestAuthHandler

urllib.request.AbstractDigestAuthHandler.descr: authreq should be the name of the header where the information about the realm is included in the request, host should be the host to authenticate to, req should be the (failed) Request object, and headers should be the error headers.
urllib.request.AbstractDigestAuthHandler.name: urllib.request.AbstractDigestAuthHandler.http_error_auth_reqed

urllib.request.BaseHandler.descr: This is the base class for all registered handlers — and handles only the simple mechanics of registration.
urllib.request.BaseHandler.name: urllib.request.BaseHandler

urllib.request.BaseHandler.default_open.descr: This method is not defined in BaseHandler, but subclasses should define it if they want to catch all URLs.
urllib.request.BaseHandler.default_open.name: urllib.request.BaseHandler.default_open

urllib.request.BaseHandler.http_error_de.descr: This method is not defined in BaseHandler, but subclasses should override it if they intend to provide a catch-all for otherwise unhandled HTTP errors. It will be called automatically by the OpenerDirector getting the error, and should not normally be called in other circumstances.
urllib.request.BaseHandler.http_error_de.name: urllib.request.BaseHandler.http_error_default

urllib.request.BaseHandler.http_error_nn.descr: nnn should be a three-digit HTTP error code. This method is also not defined in BaseHandler, but will be called, if it exists, on an instance of a subclass, when an HTTP error with code nnn occurs.
urllib.request.BaseHandler.http_error_nn.name: urllib.request.BaseHandler.http_error_nnn

urllib.request.BaseHandler.parent.descr: A valid OpenerDirector, which can be used to open using a different protocol, or handle errors.
urllib.request.BaseHandler.parent.name: urllib.request.BaseHandler.parent

urllib.request.BaseHandler.unknown_open.descr: This method is not defined in BaseHandler, but subclasses should define it if they want to catch all URLs with no specific registered handler to open it.
urllib.request.BaseHandler.unknown_open.name: urllib.request.BaseHandler.unknown_open

urllib.request.CacheFTPHandler.descr: Open FTP URLs, keeping a cache of open FTP connections to minimize delays.
urllib.request.CacheFTPHandler.name: urllib.request.CacheFTPHandler

urllib.request.CacheFTPHandler.setMaxCon.descr: Set maximum number of cached connections to m.
urllib.request.CacheFTPHandler.setMaxCon.name: urllib.request.CacheFTPHandler.setMaxConns

urllib.request.CacheFTPHandler.setTimeou.descr: Set timeout of connections to t seconds.
urllib.request.CacheFTPHandler.setTimeou.name: urllib.request.CacheFTPHandler.setTimeout

urllib.request.FTPHandler.ftp_open.descr: Open the FTP file indicated by req. The login is always done with empty username and password.
urllib.request.FTPHandler.ftp_open.name: urllib.request.FTPHandler.ftp_open

urllib.request.FancyURLopener.prompt_use.descr: Return information needed to authenticate the user at the given host in the specified security realm. The return value should be a tuple, (user, password), which can be used for basic authentication.
urllib.request.FancyURLopener.prompt_use.name: urllib.request.FancyURLopener.prompt_user_passwd

urllib.request.FileHandler.file_open.descr: Open the file locally, if there is no host name, or the host name is 'localhost'.
urllib.request.FileHandler.file_open.name: urllib.request.FileHandler.file_open

urllib.request.HTTPBasicAuthHandler.descr: Handle authentication with the remote host. password_mgr, if given, should be something that is compatible with HTTPPasswordMgr; refer to section HTTPPasswordMgr Objects for information on the interface that must be supported. HTTPBasicAuthHandler will raise a ValueError when presented with a wrong Authentication scheme.
urllib.request.HTTPBasicAuthHandler.name: urllib.request.HTTPBasicAuthHandler

urllib.request.HTTPBasicAuthHandler.http.descr: Retry the request with authentication information, if available.
urllib.request.HTTPBasicAuthHandler.http.name: urllib.request.HTTPBasicAuthHandler.http_error_401

urllib.request.HTTPCookieProcessor.descr: A class to handle HTTP Cookies.
urllib.request.HTTPCookieProcessor.name: urllib.request.HTTPCookieProcessor

urllib.request.HTTPCookieProcessor.cooki.descr: The http.cookiejar.CookieJar in which cookies are stored.
urllib.request.HTTPCookieProcessor.cooki.name: urllib.request.HTTPCookieProcessor.cookiejar

urllib.request.HTTPDefaultErrorHandler.descr: A class which defines a default handler for HTTP error responses; all responses are turned into HTTPError exceptions.
urllib.request.HTTPDefaultErrorHandler.name: urllib.request.HTTPDefaultErrorHandler

urllib.request.HTTPDigestAuthHandler.descr: Handle authentication with the remote host. password_mgr, if given, should be something that is compatible with HTTPPasswordMgr; refer to section HTTPPasswordMgr Objects for information on the interface that must be supported. When both Digest Authentication Handler and Basic Authentication Handler are both added, Digest Authentication is always tried first. If the Digest Authentication returns a 40x response again, it is sent to Basic Authentication handler to Handle. This Handler method will raise a ValueError when presented with an authentication scheme other than Digest or Basic.
urllib.request.HTTPDigestAuthHandler.name: urllib.request.HTTPDigestAuthHandler

urllib.request.HTTPDigestAuthHandler.htt.descr: Retry the request with authentication information, if available.
urllib.request.HTTPDigestAuthHandler.htt.name: urllib.request.HTTPDigestAuthHandler.http_error_401

urllib.request.HTTPHandler.descr: A class to handle opening of HTTP URLs.
urllib.request.HTTPHandler.name: urllib.request.HTTPHandler

urllib.request.HTTPHandler.http_open.descr: Send an HTTP request, which can be either GET or POST, depending on req.has_data().
urllib.request.HTTPHandler.http_open.name: urllib.request.HTTPHandler.http_open

urllib.request.HTTPPasswordMgr.descr: Keep a database of (realm, uri) -> (user, password) mappings.
urllib.request.HTTPPasswordMgr.name: urllib.request.HTTPPasswordMgr

urllib.request.HTTPPasswordMgr.add_passw.descr: uri can be either a single URI, or a sequence of URIs. realm, user and passwd must be strings. This causes (user, passwd) to be used as authentication tokens when authentication for realm and a super-URI of any of the given URIs is given.
urllib.request.HTTPPasswordMgr.add_passw.name: urllib.request.HTTPPasswordMgr.add_password

urllib.request.HTTPPasswordMgr.find_user.descr: Get user/password for given realm and URI, if any. This method will return (None, None) if there is no matching user/password.
urllib.request.HTTPPasswordMgr.find_user.name: urllib.request.HTTPPasswordMgr.find_user_password

urllib.request.HTTPPasswordMgrWithDefaul.descr: Keep a database of (realm, uri) -> (user, password) mappings. A realm of None is considered a catch-all realm, which is searched if no other realm fits.
urllib.request.HTTPPasswordMgrWithDefaul.name: urllib.request.HTTPPasswordMgrWithDefaultRealm

urllib.request.HTTPRedirectHandler.http_.descr: Redirect to the Location: or URI: URL. This method is called by the parent OpenerDirector when getting an HTTP ‘moved permanently’ response.
urllib.request.HTTPRedirectHandler.http_.name: urllib.request.HTTPRedirectHandler.http_error_301

urllib.request.HTTPRedirectHandler.http_.descr: The same as http_error_301(), but called for the ‘found’ response.
urllib.request.HTTPRedirectHandler.http_.name: urllib.request.HTTPRedirectHandler.http_error_302

urllib.request.HTTPRedirectHandler.http_.descr: The same as http_error_301(), but called for the ‘see other’ response.
urllib.request.HTTPRedirectHandler.http_.name: urllib.request.HTTPRedirectHandler.http_error_303

urllib.request.HTTPRedirectHandler.http_.descr: The same as http_error_301(), but called for the ‘temporary redirect’ response.
urllib.request.HTTPRedirectHandler.http_.name: urllib.request.HTTPRedirectHandler.http_error_307

urllib.request.HTTPRedirectHandler.redir.descr: Return a Request or None in response to a redirect. This is called by the default implementations of the http_error_30*() methods when a redirection is received from the server. If a redirection should take place, return a new Request to allow http_error_30*() to perform the redirect to newurl. Otherwise, raise HTTPError if no other handler should try to handle this URL, or return None if you can’t but another handler might.
urllib.request.HTTPRedirectHandler.redir.name: urllib.request.HTTPRedirectHandler.redirect_request
urllib.request.HTTPRedirectHandler.redir.syntax: HTTPRedirectHandler.redirect_request(req, fp, code, msg, hdrs, newurl)

urllib.request.HTTPSHandler.descr: A class to handle opening of HTTPS URLs. context and check_hostname have the same meaning as in http.client.HTTPSConnection.
urllib.request.HTTPSHandler.name: urllib.request.HTTPSHandler

urllib.request.HTTPSHandler.https_open.descr: Send an HTTPS request, which can be either GET or POST, depending on req.has_data().
urllib.request.HTTPSHandler.https_open.name: urllib.request.HTTPSHandler.https_open

urllib.request.OpenerDirector.descr: The OpenerDirector class opens URLs via BaseHandlers chained together. It manages the chaining of handlers, and recovery from errors.
urllib.request.OpenerDirector.name: urllib.request.OpenerDirector

urllib.request.OpenerDirector.add_handle.descr: handler should be an instance of BaseHandler. The following methods are searched, and added to the possible chains (note that HTTP errors are a special case).
urllib.request.OpenerDirector.add_handle.name: urllib.request.OpenerDirector.add_handler

urllib.request.OpenerDirector.error.descr: Handle an error of the given protocol. This will call the registered error handlers for the given protocol with the given arguments (which are protocol specific). The HTTP protocol is a special case which uses the HTTP response code to determine the specific error handler; refer to the http_error_*() methods of the handler classes.
urllib.request.OpenerDirector.error.name: urllib.request.OpenerDirector.error

urllib.request.OpenerDirector.open.descr: Open the given url (which can be a request object or a string), optionally passing the given data. Arguments, return values and exceptions raised are the same as those of urlopen() (which simply calls the open() method on the currently installed global OpenerDirector). The optional timeout parameter specifies a timeout in seconds for blocking operations like the connection attempt (if not specified, the global default timeout setting will be used). The timeout feature actually works only for HTTP, HTTPS and FTP connections).
urllib.request.OpenerDirector.open.name: urllib.request.OpenerDirector.open

urllib.request.ProxyBasicAuthHandler.descr: Handle authentication with the proxy. password_mgr, if given, should be something that is compatible with HTTPPasswordMgr; refer to section HTTPPasswordMgr Objects for information on the interface that must be supported.
urllib.request.ProxyBasicAuthHandler.name: urllib.request.ProxyBasicAuthHandler

urllib.request.ProxyBasicAuthHandler.htt.descr: Retry the request with authentication information, if available.
urllib.request.ProxyBasicAuthHandler.htt.name: urllib.request.ProxyBasicAuthHandler.http_error_407

urllib.request.ProxyDigestAuthHandler.descr: Handle authentication with the proxy. password_mgr, if given, should be something that is compatible with HTTPPasswordMgr; refer to section HTTPPasswordMgr Objects for information on the interface that must be supported.
urllib.request.ProxyDigestAuthHandler.name: urllib.request.ProxyDigestAuthHandler

urllib.request.ProxyDigestAuthHandler.ht.descr: Retry the request with authentication information, if available.
urllib.request.ProxyDigestAuthHandler.ht.name: urllib.request.ProxyDigestAuthHandler.http_error_407

urllib.request.ProxyHandler.descr: Cause requests to go through a proxy. If proxies is given, it must be a dictionary mapping protocol names to URLs of proxies. The default is to read the list of proxies from the environment variables <protocol>_proxy. If no proxy environment variables are set, then in a Windows environment proxy settings are obtained from the registry’s Internet Settings section, and in a Mac OS X environment proxy information is retrieved from the OS X System Configuration Framework.
urllib.request.ProxyHandler.name: urllib.request.ProxyHandler

urllib.request.Request.descr: This class is an abstraction of a URL request.
urllib.request.Request.name: urllib.request.Request
urllib.request.Request.syntax: class urllib.request.Request(url, data=None, headers={}, origin_req_host=None, unverifiable=False, method=None)

urllib.request.Request.add_data.descr: Set the Request data to data. This is ignored by all handlers except HTTP handlers — and there it should be a byte string, and will change the request to be POST rather than GET. Deprecated in 3.3, use Request.data.
urllib.request.Request.add_data.name: urllib.request.Request.add_data

urllib.request.Request.add_header.descr: Add another header to the request. Headers are currently ignored by all handlers except HTTP handlers, where they are added to the list of headers sent to the server. Note that there cannot be more than one header with the same name, and later calls will overwrite previous calls in case the key collides. Currently, this is no loss of HTTP functionality, since all headers which have meaning when used more than once have a (header-specific) way of gaining the same functionality using only one header.
urllib.request.Request.add_header.name: urllib.request.Request.add_header

urllib.request.Request.add_unredirected_.descr: Add a header that will not be added to a redirected request.
urllib.request.Request.add_unredirected_.name: urllib.request.Request.add_unredirected_header

urllib.request.Request.data.descr: The entity body for the request, or None if not specified.
urllib.request.Request.data.name: urllib.request.Request.data

urllib.request.Request.full_url.descr: The original URL passed to the constructor.
urllib.request.Request.full_url.name: urllib.request.Request.full_url

urllib.request.Request.get_data.descr: Return the instance’s data. Deprecated in 3.3, use Request.data.
urllib.request.Request.get_data.name: urllib.request.Request.get_data

urllib.request.Request.get_full_url.descr: Return the URL given in the constructor.
urllib.request.Request.get_full_url.name: urllib.request.Request.get_full_url

urllib.request.Request.get_header.descr: Return the value of the given header. If the header is not present, return the default value.
urllib.request.Request.get_header.name: urllib.request.Request.get_header

urllib.request.Request.get_host.descr: Return the host to which a connection will be made. Deprecated in 3.3, use Request.host.
urllib.request.Request.get_host.name: urllib.request.Request.get_host

urllib.request.Request.get_method.descr: Return a string indicating the HTTP request method. If Request.method is not None, return its value, otherwise return 'GET' if Request.data is None, or 'POST' if it’s not. This is only meaningful for HTTP requests.
urllib.request.Request.get_method.name: urllib.request.Request.get_method

urllib.request.Request.get_origin_req_ho.descr: Return the request-host of the origin transaction, as defined by RFC 2965. See the documentation for the Request constructor. Deprecated in 3.3, use Request.origin_req_host.
urllib.request.Request.get_origin_req_ho.name: urllib.request.Request.get_origin_req_host

urllib.request.Request.get_selector.descr: Return the selector — the part of the URL that is sent to the server. Deprecated in 3.3, use Request.selector.
urllib.request.Request.get_selector.name: urllib.request.Request.get_selector

urllib.request.Request.get_type.descr: Return the type of the URL — also known as the scheme. Deprecated in 3.3, use Request.type.
urllib.request.Request.get_type.name: urllib.request.Request.get_type

urllib.request.Request.has_data.descr: Return whether the instance has a non-None data. Deprecated in 3.3, use Request.data.
urllib.request.Request.has_data.name: urllib.request.Request.has_data

urllib.request.Request.has_header.descr: Return whether the instance has the named header (checks both regular and unredirected).
urllib.request.Request.has_header.name: urllib.request.Request.has_header

urllib.request.Request.header_items.descr: Return a list of tuples (header_name, header_value) of the Request headers.
urllib.request.Request.header_items.name: urllib.request.Request.header_items

urllib.request.Request.host.descr: The URI authority, typically a host, but may also contain a port separated by a colon.
urllib.request.Request.host.name: urllib.request.Request.host

urllib.request.Request.is_unverifiable.descr: Return whether the request is unverifiable, as defined by RFC 2965. See the documentation for the Request constructor. Deprecated in 3.3, use Request.unverifiable.
urllib.request.Request.is_unverifiable.name: urllib.request.Request.is_unverifiable

urllib.request.Request.method.descr: The HTTP request method to use. This value is used by get_method() to override the computed HTTP request method that would otherwise be returned. This attribute is initialized with the value of the method argument passed to the constructor.
urllib.request.Request.method.name: urllib.request.Request.method

urllib.request.Request.origin_req_host.descr: The original host for the request, without port.
urllib.request.Request.origin_req_host.name: urllib.request.Request.origin_req_host

urllib.request.Request.selector.descr: The URI path. If the Request uses a proxy, then selector will be the full url that is passed to the proxy.
urllib.request.Request.selector.name: urllib.request.Request.selector

urllib.request.Request.set_proxy.descr: Prepare the request by connecting to a proxy server. The host and type will replace those of the instance, and the instance’s selector will be the original URL given in the constructor.
urllib.request.Request.set_proxy.name: urllib.request.Request.set_proxy

urllib.request.Request.unverifiable.descr: boolean, indicates whether the request is unverifiable as defined by RFC 2965.
urllib.request.Request.unverifiable.name: urllib.request.Request.unverifiable

urllib.request.URLopener.open.descr: Open fullurl using the appropriate protocol. This method sets up cache and proxy information, then calls the appropriate open method with its input arguments. If the scheme is not recognized, open_unknown() is called. The data argument has the same meaning as the data argument of urlopen().
urllib.request.URLopener.open.name: urllib.request.URLopener.open

urllib.request.URLopener.open_unknown.descr: Overridable interface to open unknown URL types.
urllib.request.URLopener.open_unknown.name: urllib.request.URLopener.open_unknown

urllib.request.URLopener.retrieve.descr: Retrieves the contents of url and places it in filename. The return value is a tuple consisting of a local filename and either a email.message.Message object containing the response headers (for remote URLs) or None (for local URLs). The caller must then open and read the contents of filename. If filename is not given and the URL refers to a local file, the input filename is returned. If the URL is non-local and filename is not given, the filename is the output of tempfile.mktemp() with a suffix that matches the suffix of the last path component of the input URL. If reporthook is given, it must be a function accepting three numeric parameters: A chunk number, the maximum size chunks are read in and the total size of the download (-1 if unknown). It will be called once at the start and after each chunk of data is read from the network. reporthook is ignored for local URLs.
urllib.request.URLopener.retrieve.name: urllib.request.URLopener.retrieve

urllib.request.URLopener.version.descr: Variable that specifies the user agent of the opener object. To get urllib to tell servers that it is a particular user agent, set this in a subclass as a class variable or in the constructor before calling the base constructor.
urllib.request.URLopener.version.name: urllib.request.URLopener.version

urllib.request.UnknownHandler.descr: A catch-all class to handle unknown URLs.
urllib.request.UnknownHandler.name: urllib.request.UnknownHandler

urllib.request.build_opener.descr: Return an OpenerDirector instance, which chains the handlers in the order given. handlers can be either instances of BaseHandler, or subclasses of BaseHandler (in which case it must be possible to call the constructor without any parameters). Instances of the following classes will be in front of the handlers, unless the handlers contain them, instances of them or subclasses of them: ProxyHandler (if proxy settings are detected), UnknownHandler, HTTPHandler, HTTPDefaultErrorHandler, HTTPRedirectHandler, FTPHandler, FileHandler, HTTPErrorProcessor.
urllib.request.build_opener.name: urllib.request.build_opener

urllib.request.getproxies.descr: This helper function returns a dictionary of scheme to proxy server URL mappings. It scans the environment for variables named <scheme>_proxy, in a case insensitive approach, for all operating systems first, and when it cannot find it, looks for proxy information from Mac OSX System Configuration for Mac OS X and Windows Systems Registry for Windows.
urllib.request.getproxies.name: urllib.request.getproxies

urllib.request.install_opener.descr: Install an OpenerDirector instance as the default global opener. Installing an opener is only necessary if you want urlopen to use that opener; otherwise, simply call OpenerDirector.open() instead of urlopen(). The code does not check for a real OpenerDirector, and any class with the appropriate interface will work.
urllib.request.install_opener.name: urllib.request.install_opener

urllib.request.pathname2url.descr: Convert the pathname path from the local syntax for a path to the form used in the path component of a URL. This does not produce a complete URL. The return value will already be quoted using the quote() function.
urllib.request.pathname2url.name: urllib.request.pathname2url

urllib.request.url2pathname.descr: Convert the path component path from a percent-encoded URL to the local syntax for a path. This does not accept a complete URL. This function uses unquote() to decode path.
urllib.request.url2pathname.name: urllib.request.url2pathname

urllib.request.urlcleanup.descr: Cleans up temporary files that may have been left behind by previous calls to urlretrieve().
urllib.request.urlcleanup.name: urllib.request.urlcleanup

urllib.request.urlopen.descr: Open the URL url, which can be either a string or a Request object.
urllib.request.urlopen.name: urllib.request.urlopen
urllib.request.urlopen.syntax: urllib.request.urlopen(url, data=None[, timeout], *, cafile=None, capath=None, cadefault=False)

urllib.request.urlretrieve.descr: Copy a network object denoted by a URL to a local file. If the URL points to a local file, the object will not be copied unless filename is supplied. Return a tuple (filename, headers) where filename is the local file name under which the object can be found, and headers is whatever the info() method of the object returned by urlopen() returned (for a remote object). Exceptions are the same as for urlopen().
urllib.request.urlretrieve.name: urllib.request.urlretrieve

urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser.descr: This class provides methods to read, parse and answer questions about the robots.txt file at url.
urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser.name: urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser

urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser.can_f.descr: Returns True if the useragent is allowed to fetch the url according to the rules contained in the parsed robots.txt file.
urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser.can_f.name: urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser.can_fetch

urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser.modif.descr: Sets the time the robots.txt file was last fetched to the current time.
urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser.modif.name: urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser.modified

urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser.mtime.descr: Returns the time the robots.txt file was last fetched. This is useful for long-running web spiders that need to check for new robots.txt files periodically.
urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser.mtime.name: urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser.mtime

urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser.read.descr: Reads the robots.txt URL and feeds it to the parser.
urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser.read.name: urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser.read

urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser.set_u.descr: Sets the URL referring to a robots.txt file.
urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser.set_u.name: urllib.robotparser.RobotFileParser.set_url

uu.Error.descr: Subclass of Exception, this can be raised by uu.decode() under various situations, such as described above, but also including a badly formatted header, or truncated input file.
uu.Error.name: uu.Error

uu.decode.descr: This call decodes uuencoded file in_file placing the result on file out_file. If out_file is a pathname, mode is used to set the permission bits if the file must be created. Defaults for out_file and mode are taken from the uuencode header. However, if the file specified in the header already exists, a uu.Error is raised.
uu.decode.name: uu.decode

uu.encode.descr: Uuencode file in_file into file out_file. The uuencoded file will have the header specifying name and mode as the defaults for the results of decoding the file. The default defaults are taken from in_file, or '-' and 0o666 respectively.
uu.encode.name: uu.encode

uuid.UUID.descr: Create a UUID from either a string of 32 hexadecimal digits, a string of 16 bytes as the bytes argument, a string of 16 bytes in little-endian order as the bytes_le argument, a tuple of six integers (32-bit time_low, 16-bit time_mid, 16-bit time_hi_version, 8-bit clock_seq_hi_variant, 8-bit clock_seq_low, 48-bit node) as the fields argument, or a single 128-bit integer as the int argument. When a string of hex digits is given, curly braces, hyphens, and a URN prefix are all optional. For example, these expressions all yield the same UUID:
uuid.UUID.name: uuid.UUID
uuid.UUID.syntax: class uuid.UUID(hex=None, bytes=None, bytes_le=None, fields=None, int=None, version=None)

uuid.UUID.bytes.descr: The UUID as a 16-byte string (containing the six integer fields in big-endian byte order).
uuid.UUID.bytes.name: uuid.UUID.bytes

uuid.UUID.bytes_le.descr: The UUID as a 16-byte string (with time_low, time_mid, and time_hi_version in little-endian byte order).
uuid.UUID.bytes_le.name: uuid.UUID.bytes_le

uuid.UUID.fields.descr: A tuple of the six integer fields of the UUID, which are also available as six individual attributes and two derived attributes:
uuid.UUID.fields.name: uuid.UUID.fields

uuid.UUID.hex.descr: The UUID as a 32-character hexadecimal string.
uuid.UUID.hex.name: uuid.UUID.hex

uuid.UUID.urn.descr: The UUID as a URN as specified in RFC 4122.
uuid.UUID.urn.name: uuid.UUID.urn

uuid.UUID.variant.descr: The UUID variant, which determines the internal layout of the UUID. This will be one of the integer constants RESERVED_NCS, RFC_4122, RESERVED_MICROSOFT, or RESERVED_FUTURE.
uuid.UUID.variant.name: uuid.UUID.variant

uuid.UUID.version.descr: The UUID version number (1 through 5, meaningful only when the variant is RFC_4122).
uuid.UUID.version.name: uuid.UUID.version

uuid.getnode.descr: Get the hardware address as a 48-bit positive integer. The first time this runs, it may launch a separate program, which could be quite slow. If all attempts to obtain the hardware address fail, we choose a random 48-bit number with its eighth bit set to 1 as recommended in RFC 4122. “Hardware address” means the MAC address of a network interface, and on a machine with multiple network interfaces the MAC address of any one of them may be returned.
uuid.getnode.name: uuid.getnode

uuid.uuid1.descr: Generate a UUID from a host ID, sequence number, and the current time. If node is not given, getnode() is used to obtain the hardware address. If clock_seq is given, it is used as the sequence number; otherwise a random 14-bit sequence number is chosen.
uuid.uuid1.name: uuid.uuid1

uuid.uuid3.descr: Generate a UUID based on the MD5 hash of a namespace identifier (which is a UUID) and a name (which is a string).
uuid.uuid3.name: uuid.uuid3

uuid.uuid5.descr: Generate a UUID based on the SHA-1 hash of a namespace identifier (which is a UUID) and a name (which is a string).
uuid.uuid5.name: uuid.uuid5

values.descr: Return a new view of the dictionary’s values. See the documentation of view objects.
values.name: dict.values

vars.descr: Return the __dict__ attribute for a module, class, instance, or any other object with a __dict__ attribute.
vars.name: vars

venv.EnvBuilder.descr: The EnvBuilder class accepts the following keyword arguments on instantiation:
venv.EnvBuilder.name: venv.EnvBuilder

venv.EnvBuilder.create.descr: This method takes as required argument the path (absolute or relative to the current directory) of the target directory which is to contain the virtual environment. The create method will either create the environment in the specified directory, or raise an appropriate exception.
venv.EnvBuilder.create.name: venv.EnvBuilder.create

venv.EnvBuilder.create_configuration.descr: Creates the pyvenv.cfg configuration file in the environment.
venv.EnvBuilder.create_configuration.name: venv.EnvBuilder.create_configuration

venv.EnvBuilder.ensure_directories.descr: Creates the environment directory and all necessary directories, and returns a context object. This is just a holder for attributes (such as paths), for use by the other methods. The directories are allowed to exist already, as long as either clear or upgrade were specified to allow operating on an existing environment directory.
venv.EnvBuilder.ensure_directories.name: venv.EnvBuilder.ensure_directories

venv.EnvBuilder.install_scripts.descr: path is the path to a directory that should contain subdirectories “common”, “posix”, “nt”, each containing scripts destined for the bin directory in the environment. The contents of “common” and the directory corresponding to os.name are copied after some text replacement of placeholders:
venv.EnvBuilder.install_scripts.name: venv.EnvBuilder.install_scripts

venv.EnvBuilder.post_setup.descr: A placeholder method which can be overridden in third party implementations to pre-install packages in the virtual environment or perform other post-creation steps.
venv.EnvBuilder.post_setup.name: venv.EnvBuilder.post_setup

venv.EnvBuilder.setup_python.descr: Creates a copy of the Python executable (and, under Windows, DLLs) in the environment. On a POSIX system, if a specific executable python3.x was used, symlinks to python and python3 will be created pointing to that executable, unless files with those names already exist.
venv.EnvBuilder.setup_python.name: venv.EnvBuilder.setup_python

venv.EnvBuilder.setup_scripts.descr: Installs activation scripts appropriate to the platform into the virtual environment.
venv.EnvBuilder.setup_scripts.name: venv.EnvBuilder.setup_scripts

venv.create.descr: Create an EnvBuilder with the given keyword arguments, and call its create() method with the env_dir argument.
venv.create.name: venv.create

warnings.catch_warnings.descr: A context manager that copies and, upon exit, restores the warnings filter and the showwarning() function. If the record argument is False (the default) the context manager returns None on entry. If record is True, a list is returned that is progressively populated with objects as seen by a custom showwarning() function (which also suppresses output to sys.stdout). Each object in the list has attributes with the same names as the arguments to showwarning().
warnings.catch_warnings.name: warnings.catch_warnings

warnings.filterwarnings.descr: Insert an entry into the list of warnings filter specifications. The entry is inserted at the front by default; if append is true, it is inserted at the end. This checks the types of the arguments, compiles the message and module regular expressions, and inserts them as a tuple in the list of warnings filters. Entries closer to the front of the list override entries later in the list, if both match a particular warning. Omitted arguments default to a value that matches everything.
warnings.filterwarnings.name: warnings.filterwarnings
warnings.filterwarnings.syntax: warnings.filterwarnings(action, message='', category=Warning, module='', lineno=0, append=False)

warnings.formatwarning.descr: Format a warning the standard way. This returns a string which may contain embedded newlines and ends in a newline. line is a line of source code to be included in the warning message; if line is not supplied, formatwarning() will try to read the line specified by filename and lineno.
warnings.formatwarning.name: warnings.formatwarning

warnings.resetwarnings.descr: Reset the warnings filter. This discards the effect of all previous calls to filterwarnings(), including that of the -W command line options and calls to simplefilter().
warnings.resetwarnings.name: warnings.resetwarnings

warnings.showwarning.descr: Write a warning to a file. The default implementation calls formatwarning(message, category, filename, lineno, line) and writes the resulting string to file, which defaults to sys.stderr. You may replace this function with any callable by assigning to warnings.showwarning. line is a line of source code to be included in the warning message; if line is not supplied, showwarning() will try to read the line specified by filename and lineno.
warnings.showwarning.name: warnings.showwarning
warnings.showwarning.syntax: warnings.showwarning(message, category, filename, lineno, file=None, line=None)

warnings.simplefilter.descr: Insert a simple entry into the list of warnings filter specifications. The meaning of the function parameters is as for filterwarnings(), but regular expressions are not needed as the filter inserted always matches any message in any module as long as the category and line number match.
warnings.simplefilter.name: warnings.simplefilter

warnings.warn.descr: Issue a warning, or maybe ignore it or raise an exception. The category argument, if given, must be a warning category class (see above); it defaults to UserWarning. Alternatively message can be a Warning instance, in which case category will be ignored and message.__class__ will be used. In this case the message text will be str(message). This function raises an exception if the particular warning issued is changed into an error by the warnings filter see above. The stacklevel argument can be used by wrapper functions written in Python, like this:
warnings.warn.name: warnings.warn

warnings.warn_explicit.descr: This is a low-level interface to the functionality of warn(), passing in explicitly the message, category, filename and line number, and optionally the module name and the registry (which should be the __warningregistry__ dictionary of the module). The module name defaults to the filename with .py stripped; if no registry is passed, the warning is never suppressed. message must be a string and category a subclass of Warning or message may be a Warning instance, in which case category will be ignored.
warnings.warn_explicit.name: warnings.warn_explicit
warnings.warn_explicit.syntax: warnings.warn_explicit(message, category, filename, lineno, module=None, registry=None, module_globals=None)

wave.Error.descr: An error raised when something is impossible because it violates the WAV specification or hits an implementation deficiency.
wave.Error.name: wave.Error

wave.Wave_read.close.descr: Close the stream if it was opened by wave, and make the instance unusable. This is called automatically on object collection.
wave.Wave_read.close.name: wave.Wave_read.close

wave.Wave_read.getcompname.descr: Human-readable version of getcomptype(). Usually 'not compressed' parallels 'NONE'.
wave.Wave_read.getcompname.name: wave.Wave_read.getcompname

wave.Wave_read.getcomptype.descr: Returns compression type ('NONE' is the only supported type).
wave.Wave_read.getcomptype.name: wave.Wave_read.getcomptype

wave.Wave_read.getnchannels.descr: Returns number of audio channels (1 for mono, 2 for stereo).
wave.Wave_read.getnchannels.name: wave.Wave_read.getnchannels

wave.Wave_read.getparams.descr: Returns a tuple (nchannels, sampwidth, framerate, nframes, comptype, compname), equivalent to output of the get*() methods.
wave.Wave_read.getparams.name: wave.Wave_read.getparams

wave.Wave_read.readframes.descr: Reads and returns at most n frames of audio, as a string of bytes.
wave.Wave_read.readframes.name: wave.Wave_read.readframes

wave.Wave_read.rewind.descr: Rewind the file pointer to the beginning of the audio stream.
wave.Wave_read.rewind.name: wave.Wave_read.rewind

wave.Wave_read.setpos.descr: Set the file pointer to the specified position.
wave.Wave_read.setpos.name: wave.Wave_read.setpos

wave.Wave_write.close.descr: Make sure nframes is correct, and close the file if it was opened by wave. This method is called upon object collection.
wave.Wave_write.close.name: wave.Wave_write.close

wave.Wave_write.setcomptype.descr: Set the compression type and description. At the moment, only compression type NONE is supported, meaning no compression.
wave.Wave_write.setcomptype.name: wave.Wave_write.setcomptype

wave.Wave_write.setframerate.descr: Set the frame rate to n.
wave.Wave_write.setframerate.name: wave.Wave_write.setframerate

wave.Wave_write.setnframes.descr: Set the number of frames to n. This will be changed later if more frames are written.
wave.Wave_write.setnframes.name: wave.Wave_write.setnframes

wave.Wave_write.setparams.descr: The tuple should be (nchannels, sampwidth, framerate, nframes, comptype, compname), with values valid for the set*() methods. Sets all parameters.
wave.Wave_write.setparams.name: wave.Wave_write.setparams

wave.Wave_write.setsampwidth.descr: Set the sample width to n bytes.
wave.Wave_write.setsampwidth.name: wave.Wave_write.setsampwidth

wave.Wave_write.tell.descr: Return current position in the file, with the same disclaimer for the Wave_read.tell() and Wave_read.setpos() methods.
wave.Wave_write.tell.name: wave.Wave_write.tell

wave.Wave_write.writeframes.descr: Write audio frames and make sure nframes is correct.
wave.Wave_write.writeframes.name: wave.Wave_write.writeframes

wave.Wave_write.writeframesraw.descr: Write audio frames, without correcting nframes.
wave.Wave_write.writeframesraw.name: wave.Wave_write.writeframesraw

wave.open.descr: If file is a string, open the file by that name, otherwise treat it as a seekable file-like object. mode can be any of
wave.open.name: wave.open

wave.openfp.descr: A synonym for open(), maintained for backwards compatibility.
wave.openfp.name: wave.openfp

weakref.CallableProxyType.descr: The type object for proxies of callable objects.
weakref.CallableProxyType.name: weakref.CallableProxyType

weakref.ProxyType.descr: The type object for proxies of objects which are not callable.
weakref.ProxyType.name: weakref.ProxyType

weakref.ProxyTypes.descr: Sequence containing all the type objects for proxies. This can make it simpler to test if an object is a proxy without being dependent on naming both proxy types.
weakref.ProxyTypes.name: weakref.ProxyTypes

weakref.ReferenceError.descr: Exception raised when a proxy object is used but the underlying object has been collected. This is the same as the standard ReferenceError exception.
weakref.ReferenceError.name: weakref.ReferenceError

weakref.ReferenceType.descr: The type object for weak references objects.
weakref.ReferenceType.name: weakref.ReferenceType

weakref.WeakKeyDictionary.descr: Mapping class that references keys weakly. Entries in the dictionary will be discarded when there is no longer a strong reference to the key. This can be used to associate additional data with an object owned by other parts of an application without adding attributes to those objects. This can be especially useful with objects that override attribute accesses.
weakref.WeakKeyDictionary.name: weakref.WeakKeyDictionary

weakref.WeakKeyDictionary.keyrefs.descr: Return an iterable of the weak references to the keys.
weakref.WeakKeyDictionary.keyrefs.name: weakref.WeakKeyDictionary.keyrefs

weakref.WeakSet.descr: Set class that keeps weak references to its elements. An element will be discarded when no strong reference to it exists any more.
weakref.WeakSet.name: weakref.WeakSet

weakref.WeakValueDictionary.descr: Mapping class that references values weakly. Entries in the dictionary will be discarded when no strong reference to the value exists any more.
weakref.WeakValueDictionary.name: weakref.WeakValueDictionary

weakref.WeakValueDictionary.valuerefs.descr: Return an iterable of the weak references to the values.
weakref.WeakValueDictionary.valuerefs.name: weakref.WeakValueDictionary.valuerefs

weakref.getweakrefcount.descr: Return the number of weak references and proxies which refer to object.
weakref.getweakrefcount.name: weakref.getweakrefcount

weakref.getweakrefs.descr: Return a list of all weak reference and proxy objects which refer to object.
weakref.getweakrefs.name: weakref.getweakrefs

weakref.proxy.descr: Return a proxy to object which uses a weak reference. This supports use of the proxy in most contexts instead of requiring the explicit dereferencing used with weak reference objects. The returned object will have a type of either ProxyType or CallableProxyType, depending on whether object is callable. Proxy objects are not hashable regardless of the referent; this avoids a number of problems related to their fundamentally mutable nature, and prevent their use as dictionary keys. callback is the same as the parameter of the same name to the ref() function.
weakref.proxy.name: weakref.proxy

weakref.ref.descr: Return a weak reference to object. The original object can be retrieved by calling the reference object if the referent is still alive; if the referent is no longer alive, calling the reference object will cause None to be returned. If callback is provided and not None, and the returned weakref object is still alive, the callback will be called when the object is about to be finalized; the weak reference object will be passed as the only parameter to the callback; the referent will no longer be available.
weakref.ref.name: weakref.ref

webbrowser.Error.descr: Exception raised when a browser control error occurs.
webbrowser.Error.name: webbrowser.Error

webbrowser.controller.open.descr: Display url using the browser handled by this controller. If new is 1, a new browser window is opened if possible. If new is 2, a new browser page (“tab”) is opened if possible.
webbrowser.controller.open.name: webbrowser.controller.open

webbrowser.controller.open_new.descr: Open url in a new window of the browser handled by this controller, if possible, otherwise, open url in the only browser window. Alias open_new().
webbrowser.controller.open_new.name: webbrowser.controller.open_new

webbrowser.controller.open_new_tab.descr: Open url in a new page (“tab”) of the browser handled by this controller, if possible, otherwise equivalent to open_new().
webbrowser.controller.open_new_tab.name: webbrowser.controller.open_new_tab

webbrowser.get.descr: Return a controller object for the browser type using. If using is None, return a controller for a default browser appropriate to the caller’s environment.
webbrowser.get.name: webbrowser.get

webbrowser.open.descr: Display url using the default browser. If new is 0, the url is opened in the same browser window if possible. If new is 1, a new browser window is opened if possible. If new is 2, a new browser page (“tab”) is opened if possible. If autoraise is True, the window is raised if possible (note that under many window managers this will occur regardless of the setting of this variable).
webbrowser.open.name: webbrowser.open

webbrowser.open_new.descr: Open url in a new window of the default browser, if possible, otherwise, open url in the only browser window.
webbrowser.open_new.name: webbrowser.open_new

webbrowser.open_new_tab.descr: Open url in a new page (“tab”) of the default browser, if possible, otherwise equivalent to open_new().
webbrowser.open_new_tab.name: webbrowser.open_new_tab

webbrowser.register.descr: Register the browser type name. Once a browser type is registered, the get() function can return a controller for that browser type. If instance is not provided, or is None, constructor will be called without parameters to create an instance when needed. If instance is provided, constructor will never be called, and may be None.
webbrowser.register.name: webbrowser.register

winreg.CloseKey.descr: Closes a previously opened registry key. The hkey argument specifies a previously opened key.
winreg.CloseKey.name: winreg.CloseKey

winreg.ConnectRegistry.descr: Establishes a connection to a predefined registry handle on another computer, and returns a handle object.
winreg.ConnectRegistry.name: winreg.ConnectRegistry

winreg.CreateKey.descr: Creates or opens the specified key, returning a handle object.
winreg.CreateKey.name: winreg.CreateKey

winreg.CreateKeyEx.descr: Creates or opens the specified key, returning a handle object.
winreg.CreateKeyEx.name: winreg.CreateKeyEx

winreg.DeleteValue.descr: Removes a named value from a registry key.
winreg.DeleteValue.name: winreg.DeleteValue

winreg.DisableReflectionKey.descr: Disables registry reflection for 32-bit processes running on a 64-bit operating system.
winreg.DisableReflectionKey.name: winreg.DisableReflectionKey

winreg.EnableReflectionKey.descr: Restores registry reflection for the specified disabled key.
winreg.EnableReflectionKey.name: winreg.EnableReflectionKey

winreg.EnumKey.descr: Enumerates subkeys of an open registry key, returning a string.
winreg.EnumKey.name: winreg.EnumKey

winreg.EnumValue.descr: Enumerates values of an open registry key, returning a tuple.
winreg.EnumValue.name: winreg.EnumValue

winreg.ExpandEnvironmentStrings.descr: Expands environment variable placeholders %NAME% in strings like REG_EXPAND_SZ:
winreg.ExpandEnvironmentStrings.name: winreg.ExpandEnvironmentStrings

winreg.FlushKey.descr: Writes all the attributes of a key to the registry.
winreg.FlushKey.name: winreg.FlushKey

winreg.LoadKey.descr: Creates a subkey under the specified key and stores registration information from a specified file into that subkey.
winreg.LoadKey.name: winreg.LoadKey

winreg.OpenKey.descr: Opens the specified key, returning a handle object.
winreg.OpenKey.name: winreg.OpenKey

winreg.OpenKeyEx.descr: Opens the specified key, returning a handle object.
winreg.OpenKeyEx.name: winreg.OpenKeyEx

winreg.PyHKEY.Detach.descr: Detaches the Windows handle from the handle object.
winreg.PyHKEY.Detach.name: winreg.PyHKEY.Detach

winreg.PyHKEY.__enter__.descr: The HKEY object implements __enter__() and __exit__() and thus supports the context protocol for the with statement:
winreg.PyHKEY.__enter__.name: winreg.PyHKEY.__enter__

winreg.PyHKEY.__exit__.descr: The HKEY object implements __enter__() and __exit__() and thus supports the context protocol for the with statement:
winreg.PyHKEY.__exit__.name: winreg.PyHKEY.__exit__

winreg.QueryInfoKey.descr: Returns information about a key, as a tuple.
winreg.QueryInfoKey.name: winreg.QueryInfoKey

winreg.QueryReflectionKey.descr: Determines the reflection state for the specified key.
winreg.QueryReflectionKey.name: winreg.QueryReflectionKey

winreg.QueryValue.descr: Retrieves the unnamed value for a key, as a string.
winreg.QueryValue.name: winreg.QueryValue

winreg.QueryValueEx.descr: Retrieves the type and data for a specified value name associated with an open registry key.
winreg.QueryValueEx.name: winreg.QueryValueEx

winreg.SaveKey.descr: Saves the specified key, and all its subkeys to the specified file.
winreg.SaveKey.name: winreg.SaveKey

winreg.SetValue.descr: Associates a value with a specified key.
winreg.SetValue.name: winreg.SetValue

winreg.SetValueEx.descr: Stores data in the value field of an open registry key.
winreg.SetValueEx.name: winreg.SetValueEx

winsound.Beep.descr: Beep the PC’s speaker. The frequency parameter specifies frequency, in hertz, of the sound, and must be in the range 37 through 32,767. The duration parameter specifies the number of milliseconds the sound should last. If the system is not able to beep the speaker, RuntimeError is raised.
winsound.Beep.name: winsound.Beep

winsound.MessageBeep.descr: Call the underlying MessageBeep() function from the Platform API. This plays a sound as specified in the registry. The type argument specifies which sound to play; possible values are -1, MB_ICONASTERISK, MB_ICONEXCLAMATION, MB_ICONHAND, MB_ICONQUESTION, and MB_OK, all described below. The value -1 produces a “simple beep”; this is the final fallback if a sound cannot be played otherwise.
winsound.MessageBeep.name: winsound.MessageBeep

winsound.PlaySound.descr: Call the underlying PlaySound() function from the Platform API. The sound parameter may be a filename, audio data as a string, or None. Its interpretation depends on the value of flags, which can be a bitwise ORed combination of the constants described below. If the sound parameter is None, any currently playing waveform sound is stopped. If the system indicates an error, RuntimeError is raised.
winsound.PlaySound.name: winsound.PlaySound

wsgiref.handlers.BaseCGIHandler.descr: Similar to CGIHandler, but instead of using the sys and os modules, the CGI environment and I/O streams are specified explicitly. The multithread and multiprocess values are used to set the wsgi.multithread and wsgi.multiprocess flags for any applications run by the handler instance.
wsgiref.handlers.BaseCGIHandler.name: wsgiref.handlers.BaseCGIHandler
wsgiref.handlers.BaseCGIHandler.syntax: class wsgiref.handlers.BaseCGIHandler(stdin, stdout, stderr, environ, multithread=True, multiprocess=False)

wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.descr: This is an abstract base class for running WSGI applications. Each instance will handle a single HTTP request, although in principle you could create a subclass that was reusable for multiple requests.
wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.name: wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler

wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler._flush.descr: Force buffered data to be transmitted to the client. It’s okay if this method is a no-op (i.e., if _write() actually sends the data).
wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler._flush.name: wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler._flush

wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler._write.descr: Buffer the bytes data for transmission to the client. It’s okay if this method actually transmits the data; BaseHandler just separates write and flush operations for greater efficiency when the underlying system actually has such a distinction.
wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler._write.name: wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler._write

wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.add_cgi_var.descr: Insert CGI variables for the current request into the environ attribute.
wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.add_cgi_var.name: wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.add_cgi_vars

wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.error_body.descr: The error response body. This should be an HTTP response body bytestring. It defaults to the plain text, “A server error occurred. Please contact the administrator.”
wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.error_body.name: wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.error_body

wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.error_heade.descr: The HTTP headers used for error responses. This should be a list of WSGI response headers ((name, value) tuples), as described in PEP 3333. The default list just sets the content type to text/plain.
wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.error_heade.name: wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.error_headers

wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.error_outpu.descr: This method is a WSGI application to generate an error page for the user. It is only invoked if an error occurs before headers are sent to the client.
wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.error_outpu.name: wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.error_output

wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.error_statu.descr: The HTTP status used for error responses. This should be a status string as defined in PEP 3333; it defaults to a 500 code and message.
wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.error_statu.name: wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.error_status

wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.get_scheme.descr: Return the URL scheme being used for the current request. The default implementation uses the guess_scheme() function from wsgiref.util to guess whether the scheme should be “http” or “https”, based on the current request’s environ variables.
wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.get_scheme.name: wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.get_scheme

wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.get_stderr.descr: Return an output stream object suitable for use as the wsgi.errors of the request currently being processed.
wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.get_stderr.name: wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.get_stderr

wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.get_stdin.descr: Return an input stream object suitable for use as the wsgi.input of the request currently being processed.
wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.get_stdin.name: wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.get_stdin

wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.http_versio.descr: If origin_server is true, this string attribute is used to set the HTTP version of the response set to the client. It defaults to "1.0".
wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.http_versio.name: wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.http_version

wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.log_excepti.descr: Log the exc_info tuple in the server log. exc_info is a (type, value, traceback) tuple. The default implementation simply writes the traceback to the request’s wsgi.errors stream and flushes it. Subclasses can override this method to change the format or retarget the output, mail the traceback to an administrator, or whatever other action may be deemed suitable.
wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.log_excepti.name: wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.log_exception

wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.origin_serv.descr: This attribute should be set to a true value if the handler’s _write() and _flush() are being used to communicate directly to the client, rather than via a CGI-like gateway protocol that wants the HTTP status in a special Status: header.
wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.origin_serv.name: wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.origin_server

wsgiref.handlers.BaseHandler.os_environ.descr: The default environment variables to be included in every request’s WSGI environment.
